<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Onetime 'junk' fish, dogfish now endangered by overfishing  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN FINUCANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Fishermen who turned a onetime ''junk'' fish into
a moneymaker are upset about plans to place limits on their catch.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the restrictions are necessary to protect
the spiny dogfish, or cape shark, from being overfished.
</P>
<P>
   ''Either we act now and save what's left of the population or we
let them fish this public resource to collapse within a few years
and they'll be out of business either way,'' said Sonja Fordham,
fisheries project manager at the Center for Marine Conservation in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Frady, a spokeswoman for the Northeast region of the
National Marine Fisheries Service, said new regulations to protect
the spiny dogfish were going into effect today, barring any
unforeseen developments.
</P>
<P>
   They call for limiting the catch for the current fishing year to
10,000 metric tons, or about 22 million pounds, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that number, which would affect the fishing year from
May 1, 1999 to April 30 of this year, would probably be met.
</P>
<P>
   But she said there was considerable controversy over where the
limits should be set for the next fishing year.
</P>
<P>
   The two quasi-governmental bodies that jointly regulate the
dogfish industry off the East Coast are at odds, with the New
England Fishery Management Council calling for much less
restrictive limits than the Mid-Atlantic Fishery Management
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a deep cutback in the allowable haul of spiny
dogfish sticks in the craw of the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Mickelson, attorney for the American Dogfish Association,
which represents both dogfish processing plants and fishermen, said
more study is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line to the whole thing is that if it's true that
the fishery should be sharply reduced or closed down, it should be
done with good, substantial and in-depth information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Manley, fisheries commissioner for the city of New
Bedford, said cutbacks would have ''a major impact'' on his city.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was ironic because fishermen had been encouraged
in the 1990s to go after species such as the dogfish because of the
depletion of stocks of more popular fish like the haddock, cod and
flounder.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did their job well and now here we go again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham said environmentalists had been ''calling for management
of this particular vulnerable species for more than five years so
we could avoid exactly this situation. But there's been too much
opposition to this plan so it's years behind schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If we act now, we ... have an opportunity to recover the
population perhaps within a decade. If we continue the status quo,
the population will collapse in just a few years and rebuilding
will be stretched out more than three decades,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
