<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, March 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Net Cited in Insider Trading Scheme
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nineteen people were charged Tuesday with illegally
pocketing more than $8 million from secrets traded in cyberspace chat rooms, an
insider trading case that prosecutors said was the first to use the Internet.
Two of main organizers pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit insider trading
and other charges. Richard Walker, director of enforcement for the Securities
and Exchange Commission, called the case ''one of the most elaborate insider
trading schemes in history.'' The Internet figured so prominently in the scheme
that U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White and the commission noted that the case was the
first ever alleging that the Internet was used to pass inside information.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nominations Clinched, Bush With Advantage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new poll shows George W. Bush holds a slight advantage
among likely voters in the presidential race against Al Gore, as both
presidential candidates clinched their party's nominations in the southern
primaries Tuesday. Bush is also drawing more of the John McCain supporters that
both he and Gore are aggressively trying to attract, according to the poll
released Tuesday. The Texas governor has 49 percent to 43 percent for Gore in
the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Other recent polls have shown the race very close
or with the vice president slightly ahead, but many of them polled registered
voters. Narrowing the poll to likely voters often improves the numbers of the
Republican candidate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., Britain Urge Open Gene Access
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shares in biotechnology companies hoping to profit from
the sale of genetic data were hammered Tuesday after the United States and
Britain agreed to openly share data from a groundbreaking project to decode the
human genetic pattern. The two governments are the leading players in the
nonprofit Human Genome Project, which plans to publish a full genetic map on the
Internet by 2003. The information, which President Clinton called ''the
scientific breakthrough of the century, perhaps of all time,'' would be
available free to scientists and researchers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Tosses School Voucher Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A judge threw out the nation's first statewide
school voucher system Tuesday, ruling that Florida's Constitution bars public
money from being spent on private education. Gov. Jeb Bush, who championed the
program, promised to find the money to keep it going despite what happens in
court. An appeal is certain. ''We'll raise the money,'' Bush said. ''This is the
first inning of a long drawn out legal battle.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Releases China Trade Text
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, under pressure from Congress,
released the text of its landmark trade agreement with China Tuesday and pledged
intensive enforcement to ensure that China opens its markets. Administration
officials insisted the 250 pages of detailed text that it sent to each member of
Congress and released to news organizations confirm its claims that U.S.
exporters stand to reap billions of dollars from lowered trade barriers promised
by China. Opponents quickly seized on what they view as serious shortcomings of
the agreement: the lack of protections for workers, the environment or human
rights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ind. OKs Posting Ten Commandments
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Democratic Gov. Frank O'Bannon signed legislation
Tuesday allowing schools and other government entities to post the Ten
Commandments in their buildings if they are displayed with other historical
documents. The governor also said a new monument will be erected on the
Statehouse grounds this summer featuring the commandments, the preamble to the
U.S. Constitution and the Bill of Rights. The law takes effect July 1. The
Indiana Civil Liberties Union, which contends the law violates the
constitutional separation of church and state, said it likely would sue shortly
after the monument goes up.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Wednesday following sharp drops on Wall
Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 230.79 points to 18,911.05 in early
trading. In New York, the Nasdaq fell 200.61, or 4.1 percent, to close at
4,706.63, its second-worst point drop in history. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 135.89, to 9,811.24.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks beat Rockets 91-85
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell scored 27 points, reserve John Wallace
added 17, and Marcus Camby returned from the injured list and made a big
defensive play as the Knicks beat the Houston Rockets 91-85 Tuesday night. About
two hours before tipoff, the Knicks learned the league office had temporarily
dropped its requirement that coaches wear a microphone for nationally televised
games. It was good news to Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who had been one of the
most outspoken critics of the policy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
