<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton defends fundraising; says Giuliani slow to aid libraries  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, launching one of her
toughest attacks yet against Senate rival Rudolph Giuliani, says
the New York City mayor should get an overdue notice when it comes
to helping libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are too many leaders on the Republican side, from
Capitol Hill to Gracie Mansion (the mayor's official residence) who
year after year, come budget time, reject their responsibilities to
our public libraries,'' the first lady told several hundred
librarians attending a conference Tuesday sponsored by the New York
Library Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year, once again, the mayor of New York has proposed
cutting the library budget by a whopping 19 percent,'' she added.
''Imagine if someone in the Senate from New York ... stood for a 19
percent cut to our libraries.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton sought to stay on the attack against the
Republican mayor, reporters were intent on asking her about a
report in The New York Times that she had benefitted from a $50,000
fund-raising dinner hosted by Pakistani-Americans for her on Staten
Island on Feb. 22. At the time, Pakistani-Americans were lobbying
the Clinton administration to have the president visit Pakistan
during his upcoming trip to India. Last week, the president
announced he would also visit Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady at first refused to talk about the issue, saying
she wasn't going to conduct a ''walking news conference'' as she
left the librarians' event. Later, after speaking to the New York
State School Boards Association, Clinton told reporters that the
fund-raising event had no impact on her husband's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anybody thinks they can influence the president by making a
contribution to me, they are dead wrong, and I think there is no
evidence of that,'' she said, adding that it was well known that
her husband had always wanted to include Pakistan in his trip.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Clinton said that if any contributors are saying they
are giving to her with the hope of influencing administration
policy, ''that is inappropriate and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also said that if a Senate candidate were to
eliminate as contributors any New Yorkers who belonged to an ethnic
group with foreign policy concerns, ''it would be very difficult to
run for office in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speech to the school board members from across the state,
Clinton continued her attacks on Giuliani and his support for
school vouchers for parents who want to take their children out of
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Calling vouchers ''gimmicks,'' Clinton said ''this election
presents New Yorkers with a stark choice, a choice to walk away
from our public schools, cutting schools and slashing (city
education) budgets by almost $7 billion, or digging in and making
sure that not a single child from a single school falls through the
cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the librarians that local communities and local
libraries should decide on an individual basis whether to employ
filters on their computer systems designed to keep children from
being exposed to smut or violence on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she also said that ''personally, if I were in a
library I would employ filters because I think that there is a lot
of stuff on the Web that is just not appropriate for children, or
for adults for that matter. But you wouldn't want to do anything
other than filter for children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
