<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican assemblyman lashes out at top Pataki aide  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A war of words has broken out between Gov.
George Pataki and a Republican assemblyman who says the governor's
chief aide threatened to run someone against him in a primary for
refusing to support George W. Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I was Pataki, I would just fire'' Zenia Mucha, said
Assemblyman Thomas Kirwan, a former state trooper and Orange County
Republican who was one of the first prominent New York Republicans
to endorse Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Mucha on Tuesday denied threatening Kirwan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sad commentary that people will say or do anything to
get attention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zenia Mucha is an extremely valuable member of this
administration,'' Pataki said. ''If he has a problem with her or
any member of this administration, he shouldn't run to reporters,
he should pick up the phone and call me.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first public fallout from McCain's unsuccessful
attempt to win New York state in the Republican presidential
primary. Most of the party establishment was behind Bush and tried
to keep McCain from being able to compete on the primary ballot in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Kirwan was elected as a McCain delegate, garnering the
second-most votes in the state's 26nd Congressional District. The
other delegates elected in the district were state Sen. Thomas
Libous, R-Binghamton, and Joseph Laughney, Broome County's GOP
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won the March 7 presidential primary in New York with at
least 67 of the 93 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The state Republican Party, with the support of Pataki, Bush's
state campaign chairman, had tried earlier to keep McCain off the
ballot but failed. After that, the party put all of its resources
into ensuring Bush would win the state's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of this, a couple of members have told me that Zenia
Mucha has said with expletives deleted, in fact with language that
rivaled Joe Pesci in 'Goodfellas,' that I better be prepared for a
primary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a Bush sweep of the primaries on March 7, McCain dropped
out of the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Mucha, known for her fierce and sometimes coarse defense of
Pataki, denied ever threatening Kirwan. ''Before today, I've never
given a passing thought to ... what is his name?'' Mucha asked.
</P>
<P>
   When prompted with Kirwan's name, she continued, ''And in spite
of today's events, that statement holds true. All I can say is, you
know, I guess people will say or do anything to get attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucha, once an aide to former U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, is
Pataki's chief spokeswoman and among his closest advisers. Mucha,
who makes $147,490 a year, successfully ran his reelection race for
governor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as I can convince Zenia Mucha to turn down much
greater offers in the private sector and keep working to improve
this state, I'm going to try to do everything I can to keep her
here,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirwan admitted that Mucha never personally threatened him and
that he heard about it secondhand. He refused to say who his
sources were, and said he had not tried to call Mucha or Pataki to
confirm what he was told. ''I didn't see a point to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kirwan said if Mucha wants to see him in a primary, she
should move into his district and challenge him herself.
</P>
<P>
   ''If she does, I will kick her rear end back to Albany,'' Kirwan
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Kirwan has been in the state Legislature since 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
