<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions say they won't oppose CSEA contract with state  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A union president who agitated against the
state's contract offer to the Civil Service Employees Association
last year said he supports the new tentative contract agreement it
has reached with the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Quirk, president of the 1,500-member State Court Officers
union, said Tuesday that with a few modifications, the Civil
Service Employees Association contract is one he would endorse to
his own members.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative CSEA pact includes across-the-board salary
increases of 3 percent retroactive to October 1999, 3 percent
effective April 2000, and 3.5 percent in both April 2001 and April
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were given the exact same offer today and it has some big
positives,'' Quirk said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, fearing the state would base his union's contract
negotiations upon the tentative agreement reached by the
77,000-member CSEA, Quirk led an advertising campaign urging CSEA
members to reject the state's offer of an 11 percent increase over
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state has been telling us for 25 years that we can't have
more than CSEA,'' Quirk said. ''I got sick and tired of CSEA
accepting bad deals that caused harm to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The union then representing state prison guards, Council 82,
also campaigned among CSEA members in favor of rejecting the 1999
tentative contract agreement. Council 82 has since lost the right
to bargain for guards.
</P>
<P>
   The state has traditionally tried to settle contracts first with
CSEA, and make its contracts with all other state worker unions fit
within the wage and benefit parameters of the CSEA deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new contract they've got is a direct result of the actions
we took,'' Quirk said. ''We forced the CSEA's hand, and without
that, they'd have accepted the offer of last year that wasn't good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's offer to the CSEA last year was overwhelmingly
rejected and in the year since, CSEA and other unions have staged
protests at Pataki events across the state demanding a sweeter
deal.
</P>
<P>
   CSEA spokesman Stephen Madarasz said that Quirk had no impact on
the CSEA's contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had ads that attacked CSEA and caused turmoil but that's
it,'' Madarasz said. ''He hasn't been anywhere working to advance
the cause of New York State workers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our members didn't need Dennis Quirk telling them to vote
no,'' Madarasz said. ''And for him to even suggest that he had
something to do with the process that resulted in this contract is
a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a scavenger -- a parasite who just waits by to reap the
benefits of what CSEA has done.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wage-increase provisions, CSEA's contract also
eliminates the 3 percent yearly pension contribution for employees
who have worked 10 years or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0014 </TRAILER>
