<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charlotte Frank, Harry Phillips III elected as Regents  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- There will be two new faces at Board of
Regents meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Frank, of Manhattan, and Harry Phillips III, of
Hartsdale, were elected Tuesday to the 16-member educational
policy-making panel and will step into the board's two vacant
slots.
</P>
<P>
   They replace retiring Regent Ed Meyers, the board's
longest-serving member, and Harold Levy, who left to become the
interim chancellor of the New York City school system.
</P>
<P>
   Five other Regents -- Diane McGivern, Adelaide Sanford, Robert
Johnson, James Dawson and Robert Bennett -- were reappointed by the
state Legislature to new five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   Regents are unpaid and one is chosen from each of the state's 12
judicial districts. The other four are at-large selections.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the majority of the Republican senators boycotted
the election process. Since the Assembly has 150 members and the
Senate 61, the process of selecting the Regents is essentially
controlled by the Assembly Democratic majority plus the Democrats
in the minority in the state Senate. The Republican members can't
stop the Democrats from electing who they want for the Regents
board and complain about the process every year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we again are witnessing a process that will compromise
the quality of education in New York state,'' said Senate Education
Chairman John Kuhl, one of the few Republicans who showed up in the
state Assembly chamber Tuesday to protest the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kenneth LaValle, a Suffolk County Republican, has sued to
overturn the Regents' election process. While he lost in state
Supreme Court, the case has been appealed to the midlevel Appellate
Division of state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The irony is that the Democrats talked about the Republican
presidential primary being Byzantine and a throwback to the old
Soviet Union,'' LaValle said of the recently completed GOP
balloting won by George W. Bush. ''The senators aren't even needed
for this process.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When they allow us to take part in the confirmation process,
we'll talk about the election process,'' said Patricia Lynch,
spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver. The Senate gets to
confirm most gubernatorial nominations of cabinet-level
commissioners, and trustees and board members at state agencies and
authorities, without input from the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Education Chairman Steven Sanders, a Manhattan
Democrat, said more than 90 people applied for the seven slots on
the Board of Regents. In 1998, only about 20 people applied for two
positions on the 15-member educational policy-making panel.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders also conducted seven days of public interviews of all
the candidates. ''We made an exhaustive search to find the best
people,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank is vice president for research and development for the
McGraw Hill Educational and Professional Publishing Group in
Manhattan. She also worked for the New York City School Board as
the executive director of the division of curriculum and
instruction, director of curriculum development as well as a former
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has been chairman of Westchester Community College's
board for the last five years, and has been a trustee since 1989.
He also served as director, treasurer and vice president of the New
York Community College Trustees of SUNY and served on several of
its committees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
