<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comptroller: Thruway Authority low-balled revenue figures  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state Thruway Authority underestimated
traffic and revenue figures in order to justify a proposed toll
increase, New York's comptroller is contending.
</P>
<P>
   H. Carl McCall said the Thruway Authority projected an
''artificially low'' growth rate in traffic of 2 percent over the
next six years when making its case for a toll hike -- though over
the past 12 years passenger vehicle traffic on the Thruway has been
increasing by 3 percent a year and commercial traffic by 4 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
   The authority said last month it needed tolls to be raised by up
to 3 percent a year to generate $216 million more for improvements
to the superhighway and other transportation facilities over the
next five years. With Gov. George Pataki and the chief leaders of
the state Legislature coming out against a toll hike, Thruway
administrators later withdrew the toll hike plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the Thruway first proposed its toll increase, I said
there wasn't justification for the level of increase they wanted,''
McCall said Tuesday. ''Here's the proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Thruway officials have defended their revenue projections,
saying a projected falloff in traffic is one of the chief reasons
why they need to embark on an expansion and repair program.
</P>
<P>
   Terry O'Brien, a Thruway Authority spokesman, said the agency is
basing its estimates on ''sound, conservative revenue
projections.'' Because of Thruway traffic increases over the past
decade, there are congestion overloads at certain times on some
stretches of the roadway which will hinder traffic expansion,
O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst thing we can do is to sit out our hands and do
nothing,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall insisted Tuesday that the Thruway Authority's traffic
expansion figures are not compatible with economic projections from
Pataki, who appointed the board of the Thruway Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor is predicting a much stronger economy than what
appears to have been incorporated in the Thruway forecast,'' said
McCall, a Democrat who may be the Democratic challenger to the
Republican governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the state Assembly have proposed taking the
operation and maintenance of the state canal system away from the
Thruway Authority and returning them to the state's general fund.
That means all taxpayers, and not just tollpayers on the Thruway,
would bear the cost of keeping up the canal system.
</P>
<P>
   It costs the Thruway Authority between $55 million and $60
million a year to maintain the canal system, which includes
remnants of the historic Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   McCall also said the Authority does not need to turn over two
other stretches of non-toll superhighway it also maintains --
Interstate 287, the Cross-Westchester Expressway, and Interstate 84
between the Connecticut and Pennsylvania lines -- to another state
agency as a cost-saving move.
</P>
<P>
   Thruway administrators have not endorsed divesting any
non-Thruway holdings to other state agencies but they have insisted
that the renovation and expansion program is necessary to keep the
highway safe and productive.
</P>
<P>
   Thruway officials say this year's toll increase, tied to a
multi-city construction cost index under the Authority's proposal,
would have been 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that increase, the Authority said the tolls on its
roadway would still be among the lowest for toll highways in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, a Columbia County
Republican who early on championed the idea of the Thruway
Authority giving up the state canal system, said Tuesday that
McCall's analysis was flawed. He argued it did not take into
account the cost to the Authority of higher interest payments when
the Thruway borrowed money due to what Wall Street has perceived as
its added exposure to risk because of the canal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
