<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki to propose wide-ranging gun-control legislation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki will call today for
mandatory trigger locks to be installed on all guns sold in New
York and insist that ballistic ''fingerprints'' be made by
manufacturers of all firearms marketed here.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he will also call for the minimum age for handgun
purchases in New York to go from 18 to 21, for a ban on assault
weapons and for instant background checks to be made of gun buyers
at flea markets and gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''At a crime scene people don't leave the gun very often but
they do leave bullets or shell casings,'' Pataki told ABC News
Tuesday night, ''and what we would have now is a tool where the
police could check the ballistic DNA of that bullet or shell casing
against every gun that would be sold here in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki scheduled a news conference today in New York City to
formally propose the legislation, as well as an appearance on ABC's
''Good Morning America'' to outline the bill. His aides Tuesday
night refused to say more about the governor's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's legislation would require gun makers to fire all guns
before they are sold so that the telltale markings the barrels make
on bullets can be recorded. That information -- likened to
fingerprints in humans -- would be stored in a state computer which
authorities could use to match against bullets and shell casings
found at scenes of gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association has been opposed to the taking of
bullet samples for the government, contending that it is a
preliminary step toward national gun registration. A spokesman for
the NRA did not return repeated telephone calls seeking comment on
Pataki's pending legislation Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   All the provisions the Republican governor will propose have
been supported in the past in some form by the Democrat-dominated
state Assembly in New York. But the Republican state Senate,
despite proposals from some of its majority members from New York
City and its suburbs, has not approved any of the anti-gun
measures.
</P>
<P>
   John McArdle, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno, said Republicans have been ''looking'' at various gun
provisions for years. In some cases, Republicans have been trying
to determine whether federal gun legislation would supersede what
the Legislature could do on a state level, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans have not been given details of Pataki's
impending legislation, McArdle said, but would review whatever the
governor sent them.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he knows his legislation would put him out of step
with Republicans nationally, who generally oppose too-stringent
anti-gun measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately if you think it's the right thing you have to
pursue it,'' he told ABC News. ''I'm hoping we can get this through
the Legislature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0015 </TRAILER>
