<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Republicans propose $2.5 billion road, bridge bond act  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Approval by one chamber of a new $2.5
billion borrowing proposal and by the other of new ''tax-free''
development zones will be among the highlights of today's expected
passage by the state Legislature of budget resolutions for New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption by the Democrat-dominated Assembly and
Republican-controlled Senate of budget resolutions for the 2000-01
spending package will be largely symbolic acts on the road toward
passage of a new state budget.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Republicans Tuesday proposed placing the bond act
before voters this November, with the proceeds going for highway
and bridge improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno acknowledged that the state
is already in too much debt, but he said it was nevertheless proper
to bond for $2.5 billion to pay for transportation construction and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public understands that it is appropriate to bond out,''
Bruno said. ''Why? Because you'll use the roads and bridges for the
next 20, 30, 40, 50 years. So why should the public this year pay
for roads they're going to use for the next 40 years?''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said the bond act proposal would be included in
their resolution advocating the spending of about $77 billion in
the 2000-01 fiscal year, or what Bruno said would be about $500
million more than Gov. George Pataki proposed spending in January.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Democrats who dominate the Assembly said their
budget resolution -- also to be approved in that chamber today --
would include $85 million in tax cuts in the next fiscal year. The
tax cuts would total $750 million when fully implemented in four
years. Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said Democrats would wait
until today to reveal the bottom line on how much their budget
resolution proposes spending.
</P>
<P>
   And, Pataki said Tuesday he would like to increase from $750
million to $1.25 billion the amount of surplus state funds New York
applies to reducing debt in the fiscal year beginning April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said the proposed bond act would be designed to bring the
size of the overall five-year plan for bridge- and highway-building
in New York to $16.5 billion, or to precisely what the new
five-year capital plan for the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority advocates spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said there has been parity historically between spending
on MTA transit facilities in the New York City region and on
bridges and highways.
</P>
<P>
   If placed before voters, the $2.5 billion borrowing proposal
would be the largest in New York since 1988, when New Yorkers
approved a $3 billion road- and bridge-building plan.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent bond act proposal, a $2.4 billion plan for
school construction, was defeated in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The specific highway and bridge projects to be funded through a
new bond act would be agreed to by Bruno, Silver and Pataki before
going to voters, according to the Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Tuesday he had not seen the Senate proposal and was
waiting for details.
</P>
<P>
   The bond act proposal was only one of several budget-related
initiatives Tuesday in Albany:
</P>
<P>
   --Senate Republicans proposed a $400 million tax cut in the next
fiscal year, including a previously announced plan to eliminate the
state's 4 percent sales tax on gasoline and diesel fuel. The Senate
plan would total $1.9 billion when fully implemented in four years.
The Republicans said they would spend $875 million more on public
school education than in the current fiscal year or $520 million
more than Pataki has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate budget resolution would expand the maximum Tuition
Assistance Program college grant from $4,150 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   --Assembly Democrats advanced a more modest tax-cut plan. Much of
the $85 million would go to a two-month suspension of the state's
gasoline tax to encourage motorists to vacation in New York this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno called the Assembly tax-cut plan ''paltry,'' at least in
the first year, while Silver suggested the Senate wants to cut
taxes far more deeply than the state can afford.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly will propose turning state Economic Development
Zones into ''tax-free'' zones, with state aid focused on
encouraging businesses in economically disadvantaged parts of the
states.
</P>
<P>
   --Pataki's debt-reduction plan would apply $1 billion toward
reducing debt in the 2000-01 fiscal year, with the rest going to
offset debt in the 2001-02 fiscal year. Debt can be cut by funding
some programs on a pay-as-you-go basis instead of bonding for it,
and by refinancing particularly high-cost obligations at lower
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Approval today of the Senate and Assembly majorities' budget
resolutions could set the stage for the appointment of conference
committees to work out differences.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and the governor have failed to pass a budget by the
April 1 start of a new fiscal year for 15 straight years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0015 </TRAILER>
