<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribune Deal: It's a Family Affair  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Like other parts of the media industry,
newspaper companies have been consolidating rapidly in order to
build their clout in an increasingly competitive business. But the
boardroom coup that led to the Tribune Co.'s purchase of Times
Mirror Monday showcases a major difference that still sets
newspaper publishers apart from the rest of the media world: family
control.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Chandler family, which controlled the Los
Angeles Times for more than a century, had been scaling back direct
involvement since Otis Chandler retired as publisher in 1980, they
continued to wield great behind-the-scenes power with two-thirds of
the company's voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   That's what allowed the Chandlers do an end-run around their
controversial chairman and CEO Mark Willes, who was unaware of the
buyout talks until two weeks ago and will leave the company when
the deal is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a wave of consolidation in the newspaper business, most
of the leading publications -- The New York Times, The Washington
Post, The Wall Street Journal -- continue to have strong control by
families, often through separate classes of stock that have greater
voting power than the shares commonly traded on the market.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of control has long been held up as an important
element of American journalism, allowing publishers to look beyond
the short-term profit concerns to keep an independent voice and
consider issues of editorial integrity and community service.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it's no surprise that the decline of family ownership and
control in recent years has been bemoaned by many industry
observers as a worrisome trend. Some are already seeing the
Chandlers' $6 billion deal to sell Times Mirror to Tribune in the
same light.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion piece for Tuesday's Wall Street Journal entitled
''American Journalism Loses Another Family,'' Duke journalism
professor Susan E. Tifft wrote: ''Newspapers need leadership that
looks beyond the bottom line. And family owners are more likely to
provide that kind of leadership than are corporate behemoths
obedient to the quarterly whip of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other examples of family operations which have sold their
newspapers:
</P>
<P>
   --Chronicle Publishing Co., owned by the descendants of founder
M.H. de Young, sold the San Francisco Chronicle last year to Hearst
Corp., publisher of the rival San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   --The Daniels family sold The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh to The
McClatchy Co. in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Still, opinions are divided on the issue of whether family
ownership is still a must-have for good newspapers. In fact,
Tribune has a strong reputation with leading papers such as the
Chicago Tribune, but it has no major family ownership or control.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the mere fact of family ownership does not guarantee
that a newspaper will rise above its peers, says Ben Bagdikian,
former dean of the journalism school at the University of
California, Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ''Historically, there have been many unexceptional ones that
were family-owned,'' Bagdikian said. ''But all of the exceptional
ones have been family-owned, so it does make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times, the flagship of Times Mirror, has been on
both sides of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Chandler, the Times publisher from the 1960s through 1980
built the Times into a respected national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Willes, the former cereal company executive hired in 1995, was
accused of boosting profits at the expense of good journalism.
</P>
<P>
   He closed profit-poor newspapers like New York Newday and The
(Baltimore) Evening Sun.
</P>
<P>
   He also tried to generate new revenue by pulling down the
traditional wall between the news and advertising departments.
</P>
<P>
   That drew sharp criticism from advocates of journalistic
independence, which culminated last year when The Times agreed to
share advertising revenue with The Staples Center sports arena, the
subject of a special section in The Times' Sunday magazine.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.timesmirror.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.tribune.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
