<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribune Went Around Times Mirror CEO  </HEADLINE>
By TOM VERDIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Merger talks between Times Mirror and The
Tribune Co. were rekindled in January after an initial overture
last spring went nowhere, a former Times Mirror executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based Tribune made its first inquiry in May with Times
Mirror chief executive Mark Willes, who briefly discussed it with
the board before the issue was dropped, said Tom Unterman, Times
Mirror Co.'s former chief financial officer who is now advising the
controlling Chandler family through the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co. executives then decided to go around Willes and
speak directly to the Chandler family, which has operated the
flagship Los Angeles Times for more than a century and controls
about 65 percent of Times Mirror stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first discussions were in January over lunch'' in Los
Angeles, Unterman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Willes didn't find out about the negotiations until two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly $6 billion deal, which requires shareholder
approval, will create the nation's third largest newspaper company.
Diversified operations of the new company will include 22
television stations and Internet news sites that will attract 3.4
million visits a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday that Camilla Chandler
Frost, one of seven trustees of the two Chandler Trusts, said many
on the Times Mirror board were becoming ''disillusioned'' with
Willes' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Some board members were unhappy with Willes' concentration on
the company's core newspaper business, feeling Times Mirror needed
to diversify into other media to remain profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not doing what we should be doing -- looking toward the
future,'' Frost said. ''Everything we had that wasn't absolutely
core was sold off.''
</P>
<P>
   Unterman said the family opted to merge largely because of
Tribune's extensive holdings in electronic media. The decision had
little if anything to do with the controversy over the newspaper's
profit-sharing arrangement with the downtown Staples Center sports
arena, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Diversification in media type was an issue in the Chandler
family's mind and a plus as an investor,'' Unterman said. ''I think
for every one of them, the No. 1, 2 and 3 reason was the fit and
the strategic importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Unterman said he and Willes were part of a small group of people
who knew of Tribune's initial approach last May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mark and I knew, but I don't think anybody else at Times
Mirror knew,'' said Unterman, now partner and CEO of Rustic Canyon
Group, a company that manages a venture capital fund.
</P>
<P>
   They told the attorney for the Chandler Trust, and then Willes
discussed it briefly in June with the board, which at the time
chose not to pursue it, Unterman said. At the time, Times Mirror
stock had more than doubled since the day Willes took over in June
1995, closing at more than $58 a share on the last day of trading
in May.
</P>
<P>
   Willes has said he was surprised when he heard about the recent
negotiations because he believed the paper could not be sold or
merged under the terms of the Chandler family trust.
</P>
<P>
   That impression made the offer last spring ''a difficult thing
to pursue,'' Unterman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't language in the trust that forbids it (selling).
There's a sense that they wouldn't do it,'' Unterman said. ''It
required unanimity of all the trustees, and there were some
trustees on record as saying they would never do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what changed their mind.
</P>
<P>
   A message left for Times Mirror on Tuesday was not returned, and
members of the Chandler family could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The family will continue to have a say in the Times' fortunes.
An expanded Tribune Co. board gives four seats to the Chandlers,
who also will have 40 percent of the membership on a new Los
Angeles Times board.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandlers likely concluded that the time was right to sell
because newspaper properties are in demand but might not be in the
near future, said John Morton, president of a Silver Spring, Md.,
media consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's greater risk that newspaper values will decline than
they will rise,'' he said. ''How that turns out depends on how the
Internet develops.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.timesmirror.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.tribune.com
</P>
</TEXT>
