<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, March 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nominations Clinched, Bush With Advantage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush holds a slight advantage among likely
voters in a new poll in the presidential race against Al Gore, as both
presidential candidates clinched their party's nominations in the southern
primaries Tuesday. Bush is also drawing more of the John McCain supporters that
both he and Gore are aggressively trying to attract, according to the CNN-USA
Today-Gallup poll released Tuesday. The Texas governor has 49 percent to 43
percent for Gore. Other recent polls have shown the race very close or with the
vice president slightly ahead, but many of them polled registered voters.
Narrowing the poll to likely voters often improves the numbers of the Republican
candidate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
2 US Women in Costa Rica Shot Dead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Two 19-year-old American women were found shot
to death near a Caribbean beach town in Costa Rica, security officials said
Tuesday. The bodies were found Monday along a highway near the town of Cahuita,
about 90 miles east of San Jose, the capital, said Jesus Urena, a spokesman for
the Public Security Ministry. Costa Rican officials identified the victims as
Emily Howell of Lexington, Ky., and Emily Eagen of Detroit. The women were
driving a sports utility vehicle when the attack occurred, said a police
spokeswoman. The officials said one had been shot twice in the head and the
other three times in the back, and that one was nude and the other
partially-nude.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Net Cited in Insider Trading Scheme
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nineteen people were charged Tuesday with illegally
pocketing more than $8 million from secrets traded in cyberspace chat rooms, an
insider trading case that prosecutors said was the first to use the Internet.
Two of main organizers pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit insider trading
and other charges. Richard Walker, director of enforcement for the Securities
and Exchange Commission, called the case ''one of the most elaborate insider
trading schemes in history.'' The Internet figured so prominently in the scheme
that U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White and the commission noted that the case was the
first ever alleging that the Internet was used to pass inside information.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., Britain Urge Open Gene Access
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shares in biotechnology companies hoping to profit from
the sale of genetic data were hammered Tuesday after the United States and
Britain agreed to openly share data from a groundbreaking project to decode the
human genetic pattern. The two governments are the leading players in the
nonprofit Human Genome Project, which plans to publish a full genetic map on the
Internet by 2003. The information, which President Clinton called ''the
scientific breakthrough of the century, perhaps of all time,'' would be
available free to scientists and researchers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Tosses School Voucher Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A judge threw out the nation's first statewide
school voucher system Tuesday, ruling that Florida's Constitution bars public
money from being spent on private education. Gov. Jeb Bush, who championed the
program, promised to find the money to keep it going despite what happens in
court. An appeal is certain. ''We'll raise the money,'' Bush said. ''This is the
first inning of a long drawn out legal battle.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Greek Stock Exchange Plunges
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Hundreds of angry investors chanting ''We want our
money back'' gathered Tuesday outside the Athens Stock Exchange after shares
took another plunge in a crisis that is growing increasingly political ahead of
elections. Riot squads stood ready to protect the exchange and stock brokers
fled out the back door of the building after the market's general index dropped
6.6 percent, or 320.90 points, to close at 4542.65 -- its lowest point since
August. ''I lost not only my money, but the money of my clients who will one day
kill me,'' said Lambros Yannoulis, a 57-year-old investment adviser with a major
insurance company who joined about 350 protesters. Others in the crowd chanted
''they are robbing us.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Wednesday following sharp drops on Wall
Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 230.79 points to 18,911.05 in early
trading. In New York, the Nasdaq fell 200.61, or 4.1 percent, to close at
4,706.63, its second-worst point drop in history. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed down 135.89, to 9,811.24.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mavericks Defeat Pacers 111-90
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Dirk Nowitzki scored 28 points -- 13 during a 15-0 run to open
the second half -- and the Dallas Mavericks beat the Indiana Pacers 111-90 on
Tuesday night. Steve Nash added 21 points and Michael Finley had 16 points and
11 assists to help the Mavericks to their second-largest margin of victory this
season. Rookie Greg Buckner had 10 points and 11 rebounds for the Mavericks, his
first career double-double.
</P>
