<HEADLINE> Bronx whiz-kid nearly achieves draw with world chess champ  </HEADLINE>
o0161nyc--
r n PM-NY--Kasparov-Internet Bjt   03-15 0575
PM-NY--Kasparov-Internet Chess, Bjt,570   
Bronx whiz-kid nearly achieves draw with world chess champ
AP Photos NYR 104-107   
By GEORGE WATSON   
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A burning desire to win enables Garry Kasparov
to be the world's finest chess player. It doesn't matter who the
opponent is -- or for that matter, how old the opponent is --
Kasparov, 36, is always seeking victory.
</P>
<P>
   When facing 30 young chess players during a worldwide Internet
chess tournament, the reigning world champ shuffled from one player
to the next and from computer screen to computer screen, which were
used by 20 of his opponents competing from other countries. His
face rarely displayed any emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But there was plenty of head shaking, chin rubbing and arm
crossing, and in those, parents of the children who were receiving
a drubbing found some solace. Those meant the children had made
moves that propelled Kasparov into deep thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's gotten a couple of head shakes,'' said Richard Zletz, of
Manhattan, about his 13-year-old daughter, Lauren. ''She's gotten
more chin scratches. Chin scratches are good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But 10-year-old Evan Alvarez's offer of a draw forced some
emotion out of Kasparov.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'Excuse me?''' Evan said later.
</P>
<P>
   Kasparov turned down the offer. The two continued the game. Evan
misplayed one of the final moves, and that was it. He had lost.
</P>
<P>
   The moment left Evan, who looked as though he had been punched
in the stomach, with a lesson learned: In the world of chess,
protocol discourages a lesser opponent from offering the draw,
which is the equivalent of a tie. Getting a draw with Kasparov
would have been quite a feat for the 10-year-old, given that the
world champ played the white pieces, enabling him to take the
enviable first attack move.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't do that -- it's a no-no,'' said Marley Kaplan, the
deputy director for Chess-in-the-Schools, a nonprofit organization
that brings chess to children at 160 schools in New York City.
''That made Kasparov mad.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Kasparov's other opponents was able to prevail. Viktoria
Zaks, 12, one of 20 competitors playing via computer, earned a draw
from Israel, where she lives.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, some of which was broadcast from the studio at
Times Square to a giant screen nearby, helped officially launch
KasparovChess.com. The Web site offers live coverage of
international chess matches and gives instruction on all levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many kids don't have teachers available, or even someone to
play against,'' said Elizabeth Elman, a spokeswoman for the Web
site. ''This really levels out the field.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the matches, Evan became one of Kasparov's 29
victims, all of whom were teen-agers or younger.
</P>
<P>
   Another Bronx opponent, Daniel Marriomon, had high hopes. He
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was beating him three-quarters of the way, and then I choked
up and lost,'' said Daniel, 10. ''I had him on the ropes for a long
while. It was like football: I was running 100 yards and I got
close, and then he tripped me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Daniel, Evan was left with what-ifs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a dead draw. I thought he didn't want to play,'' said
Evan, an honor student who placed second in the 1999 national chess
championship for his age division.
</P>
<P>
   David MacEnulty, Evan's chess teacher, acknowledged that his
pupil had erred.
</P>
<P>
   ''But, he is only 10,'' MacEnulty said. ''He hadn't played a
world champion before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0117 </TRAILER>
