<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Visit India, Pakistan  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When he visits India and Pakistan next week,
President Clinton will have a chance to try personal diplomacy to
persuade the world's two newest declared atomic powers to back away
from the nuclear brink. But getting progress on nuclear reduction
will be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hand was weakened by the Senate's refusal last fall to
ratify an international nuclear test ban treaty that the
administration has been pressing both India and Pakistan to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he wants to have maximum impact, he should not hinge the
trip on nuclear proliferation issues,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback,
R-Kan., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
Near Eastern and South Asian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said in an interview that he is deeply troubled that
both nations ''are doing missile testing for delivery systems.'' He
thinks the United States lacks the influence to change that
dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than emphasize nuclear politics, Brownback suggested that
Clinton would be better served by trying to ''move aggressively
forward'' in improving economic ties with India and use his stop in
Pakistan to urge a return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told India in a
strongly worded speech Tuesday that ''significant progress'' in
curbing weapons and exports of military technology is necessary for
improved relations between the world's two largest democracies.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling neighbors on the South Asian subcontinent have
been nettlesome to the United States for decades. During the Cold
War, India -- although it maintained a thriving Western-style
democratic system -- generally aligned itself with the Soviet Union
as a buffer against antagonist adversaries China to the northeast
and Pakistan to the northwest. Pakistan, with the warm-water
coastline that Soviet strategists coveted, kept tenuous friendship
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, both Pakistan and India stunned the world with
back-to-back series of nuclear tests, drawing automatic U.S.
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Many were waived in India's case, but sanctions on Pakistan were
intensified with the October coup that brought Gen. Pervez
Musharraf to power.
</P>
<P>
   Both Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Musharraf
reiterated last week that tensions over the disputed Kashmir region
would not lead to a nuclear war. ''There is no possibility,''
asserted Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last spring, the two countries narrowly averted a full-scale
war in Kashmir, which could have escalated to the nuclear level,''
CIA Director George Tenet said in a recent report to Congress.
''Recent changes in government in both countries add tensions to
the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani coup has made New Delhi reluctant to reopen peace
talks. Muslim Pakistan is suspicious of India's newly elected
coalition government, in which Hindu nationalists hold significant
sway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrives Sunday in India, the first visit there by a U.S.
president in 22 years, and will spend the week there except for a
side visit to Bangladesh and a stop in Pakistan on his way home.
</P>
<P>
   India, which enjoys a vast conventional military advantage over
smaller Pakistan, successfully flight-tested its newest
medium-range ballistic missile, the Agni2, in April.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Pakistan flight-tested both its Ghauri medium-range
ballistic missile and the Shaheen-2, a short-range missile. It
again tested the short-range missile last month.
</P>
<P>
   Because each country closely guards information about such
matters, it's hard to know how many warheads and missiles either
India or Pakistan has. But the Institute for Science and
International Security suggests that India has enough nuclear
material to build 40 to 90 nuclear weapons; Pakistan, between 22
and 43.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation of American Scientists has been distributing
high-detail satellite images showing nuclear and missile plants in
various countries. They planned to release one of Pakistan today.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, the program director, said the photographs show
Pakistan has laid groundwork for ''dozens of nuclear-tipped
missiles'' capable of striking Indian targets. Many of them are
clumped together, he said, and would be ''a tempting target for a
pre-emptive Indian attack.'' Pakistan is believed to have at least
30 medium-ranged China-built missiles.
</P>
<P>
   India may have up to 200 missiles, by some counts.
</P>
<P>
   India's ambassador to the United States, Naresh Chandra, told
reporters not to expect major breakthroughs from Clinton's visit or
for India to ask Clinton to ''carry a message'' to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass, a nuclear security adviser to former President
Bush, said Clinton can hope at best to make some progress toward
getting leaders of both countries to agree to limits on nuclear
exports and perhaps an informal agreement not to conduct further
tests.
</P>
<P>
   But ''these countries are not about to get out of the nuclear
business,'' Haass said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international
affairs for The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federation of American Scientists:
http://www.fas.org
</P>
<P>
   Institute for Science and International Security
http://www.isis-online.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
