<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Targets FCC Authority  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission's review
of industry mergers would be narrowed in scope and put on a tight
time schedule under legislation drafted by leading
telecommunication lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House Commerce
Committee's telecommunications panel, and other lawmakers have been
pushing for such language to curtail what they believe is the FCC's
overbroad jurisdiction to determine whether deals serve the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC evaluation is separate from the antitrust review
typically conducted by the Justice Department and Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At a Capitol Hill hearing Tuesday, some lawmakers accused the
FCC of using its review process to extract unrelated concessions
from parties to the deals.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are a remarkable exercise in arrogance,'' said Rep. John
Dingell of Michigan, the Commerce Committee's senior Democrat. He
said the FCC identifies potential harms that could result from a
deal, then gets the companies to concede to conditions unrelated to
those harms.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be a clear nexus between the conditions placed on
a merger and the predicted detrimental effects of the
transaction,'' Dingell said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation drafted by subcommittee member Rep. Chip Pickering,
R-Miss., would restrict the FCC to impose conditions on deals only
to bring them in compliance with FCC rules. The language spells out
that the commission is not to duplicate antitrust considerations
that the Justice Department or FTC have already addressed and sets
the commission on a tight schedule -- two to three months -- to
complete its review.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth, who frequently
criticizes the commission's approach to mergers, testified that the
agency is exceeding its narrow authority under the law to review
the transfer between companies of communication licenses.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the FCC review of the merger between Baby Bell
phone companies SBC Communications and Ameritech. As part of
securing approval in the fall, the companies agreed to a
wide-ranging set of conditions, including that they enter markets
they were not already in.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman Bill Kennard, in approving the SBC-Ameritech deal,
said it would help to realize a fundamental goal of a landmark 1996
telecommunications law, which was to promote competition.
</P>
<P>
   In prepared testimony, Kennard said the drafted legislation
would not give the FCC enough flexibility to achieve that end.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill is, in short, a recipe for making scrutiny of mergers
less public, less flexible and less likely,'' Kennard said. He
added that the FCC has set up its own task force to streamline its
review.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., also stressed that the public
interest standard over the years has helped to open monopoly
markets. The standard also has been used to ensure a diversity of
voices on the nation's airwaves -- even when a deal might not have
triggered traditional worries about concentration, said FCC
Commissioner Michael Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Powell also offered lawmakers some suggestions for improving the
process. He noted that the FCC review puts the onus on companies to
show how a deal would actively benefit consumers. By shifting the
burden to the commission, and adding timeline benchmarks, ''It
corrects a substantial amount of the problem,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee's antitrust panel, and Sen. Herb Kohl of Wisconsin, the
subcommittee's top Democrat, have introduced a companion measure
that would set a six-month limit for the FCC's merger review. That
bill is awaiting floor action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM-CT--Murder in Greenwich, Conn Bjt, 800  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Dorthy Moxley has waited nearly 25 years
to see her daughter's killer brought to justice. When the Kennedy
cousin accused in the killing faced Mrs. Moxley in court for the
first time, he told her, ''You've got the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel, now 39, was arraigned as a juvenile Tuesday in
the October 1975 killing of Martha Moxley. Both Skakel and Moxley
were 15 at the time of the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   In a simple, four-minute court appearance, Skakel heard the
charge read aloud and was advised of his rights. Skakel was charged
with being a juvenile delinquent ''based on an underlying charge of
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, he stunned the crowded courtroom when he walked
over to Mrs. Moxley, seated in the front row, and told her,
''Dorthy, I feel your pain, but you've got the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moxley did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll find out in court,'' Martha's brother, John, told
Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, John Moxley said Skakel's comment was ''just for
himself -- just theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think for 24 years, they've thought they're above the law,''
he said of the Skakel family.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to find out now,'' said Moxley, who was 17 when
his sister was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moxley said Skakel's remark to her sounded rehearsed and
made no difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really feel as though I know what happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict said trying a
25-year-old case would be difficult, but added: ''We did an awful
lot of work in the case; we developed an awful lot of evidence in
the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's defense lawyer, Michael Sherman, said Skakel's remark
to Mrs. Moxley was sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ''He truly meant that,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Michael Skakel has no idea who killed Martha Moxley. If he
did, he'd be the first one to tell the state's attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the case is in juvenile court, Skakel gets a
''reasonable cause'' hearing, when prosecutors must prove to a
judge that there is enough evidence to proceed to trial with the
case. That hearing is scheduled for June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skakel is the son of Rushton Skakel Sr., who is the
brother of U.S. Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   The Skakels and the Moxleys were neighbors in an exclusive
enclave in Greenwich, Conn. Martha was beaten to death the night of
Oct. 30, 1975, with a golf club later traced to a set owned by the
Skakels.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, who did not enter a plea during the appearance Tuesday,
has denied any involvement in her death.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's case was reopened after more than two decades when an
investigative grand jury was appointed in June 1998. The
appointment followed the publication of books about the case,
including one by former Los Angeles police Detective Mark Fuhrman.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, who gained notoriety during the O.J. Simpson trial for
his racist remarks, has been hired by ABC to provide commentary on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   He identified Michael Skakel as the likely killer in his book.
Prosecutors deny that Fuhrman's book had any influence on their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Before the court session Tuesday, Fuhrman blamed police mistakes
and deference to the wealthy Skakel family for the delay in making
an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''You walk into a house with a chandelier in the foyer that
costs more than your whole house, that's intimidating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of confidentiality laws surrounding juvenile cases,
Skakel's arraignment would normally have been closed to the public.
But Judge Maureen Dennis, acting on a request from five newspapers
and The Associated Press, last week agreed to open the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis found that Skakel had already effectively waived his
juvenile confidentiality rights, both because he is an adult and
because his name and the charges against him are already
well-known.
</P>
<P>
   Although the grand jury proceedings were closed to the public,
prosecutors have said in court documents that they were told by
former students at a private school and substance abuse center in
Poland Spring, Maine, that Skakel made ''admissions as to the
murder of Martha Moxley'' while a student there from 1978 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman called the alleged statements by former students
''garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They're old; they're inconsistent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was arrested in January after Judge George Thim -- acting
as a one-man grand jury -- ruled there was enough evidence to charge
him.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said he expects it will take at least a year for the
case to go to trial. He said he is confident the case will be
transferred to adult court.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Connecticut Judicial Branch Web site:
http://www.jud.state.ct.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
