<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers 96, Kings 91  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Arvydas Sabonis had 20 points and 16
rebounds as the Portland Trail Blazers, despite going scoreless for
the first 5:13 of the fourth quarter, beat the Sacramento Kings
96-91 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace added 19 points, Detlef Schrempf 16 and Scottie
Pippen had 10 rebounds for the Blazers, who won their third in a
row and beat the Kings for the 10th straight time.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber had 21 points and 11 rebounds before fouling out
with 15.5 seconds left, and Predrag Stojakovic had 20 points to
lead the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Portland led 74-68 to start the fourth quarter but turned it
over three times in the opening minutes and couldn't find the
basket. A free throw by Vlade Divac gave the Kings a 75-74 lead
with 8:05 to play, but Schrempf's 3-pointer put the Blazers back in
front 77-75.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis had three big defensive rebounds in the next few
minutes, and his 23-foot jumper made it 88-81. Two free throws by
Jon Barry pulled the Kings to 90-87 with 48 seconds left, but they
couldn't get closer.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had a season-high 59 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   In a wild third quarter, the Kings tied the game at 55, got down
by nine and then pulled close again as the Blazers picked up three
technical fouls -- one each on Sabonis and Wallace and another on
coach Mike Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy was not asked to wear a microphone by TNT, and it was
just as well. When Steve Smith failed to get the ball down low to
Sabonis and instead launched an airball, Dunleavy cursed and kicked
the scorer's table.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Barry drove for an easy layup to pull Sacramento
within 68-66.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams hit his first basket of the game, a 19-footer, to
open the fourth and cut the lead to 74-70. But the Kings could get
only a hook by Webber and three free throws in the next 6:37, and
Portland surged back ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was badly outplayed by Damon Stoudamire, who hit three
long jumpers, including a 3-pointer, early on to put the Blazers
ahead 15-12.
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished with just two points on 1-of-6 shooting,
including 0-for-4 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Delk, playing strong minutes in place of the erratic
Williams, had 12 points and five rebounds. Delk muscled past
Wallace for a layup to cut the lead to 49-48. Portland got a dunk
by Wallace and a finger roll from Schrempf to take a 53-49 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Sacramento hasn't won in Portland since a 105-102 victory
on Nov. 16, 1995. ... The Kings' Nick Anderson missed his third
straight game with a sore left knee. ... In his last two games
against the Blazers, Williams has four points, six assists and
eight turnovers. ... The Blazers have beaten the Kings 31 of 32
times at home. ... Wallace leads the NBA with 26 technical fouls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
