<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 US Women in Costa Rica Shot Dead  </HEADLINE>
By ERIC NUNEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A college student on a photography
project and a friend who was visiting her were shot death near a
Caribbean beach town in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Emily Howell of Lexington, Ky., and Emily Eagen of
Ann Arbor, Mich., were found Monday along a highway near the town
of Cahuita, 90 miles east of San Jose, the capital, said Jesus
Urena, a spokesman for the Public Security Ministry. Both were 19
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said one had been shot twice in the head and the other
three times in the back, and that one was nude and the other
partially nude. Credit cards, clothing and other belongings were
found near the bodies, Urena said.
</P>
<P>
   A sport utility vehicle that had been used by the women was
found burned Monday on a major highway just outside San Jose, said
judicial police spokeswoman Margarita Morales.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no arrests and no word of any suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Warren, dean of students at Antioch College in Yellow
Springs, Ohio, said Howell was a student there who had been in the
Central American nation since January on a photography project.
Eagen was a former student who was visiting her and had been in the
country 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   He said authorities were uncertain about the motive for the
attack. ''It appears to be a random, tragic incident,'' Warren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Howell's roommate was also in Costa Rica but was elsewhere when
the killings occurred, Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a horrible loss and cause for mourning for all of us,''
Warren said. Of Howell, he said: ''She was a wonderful person, very
warm, very caring.''
</P>
<P>
   Eagen's mother, Shirley Eagen, described her daughter's trip as
her ''fling'' before re-entering college as an education major in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no idea how they'd got where they were,'' she told the
Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family had researched Costa Rica and believed it
was safe. ''This could have happened anywhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Howell's family attended a private memorial service Tuesday
night. They declined any comment.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy said a consular official had gone to the area
to discuss the case with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The area is part of Limon province, where five slayings have
occurred so far this month. The region contains a depressed banana
industry and has beaches popular with tourists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
