<DOCNO> APW20000315.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State, city officials promise crackdown on phony firearms  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- State and city officials are targeting
the sales of mock firearms, promising to get decoy weapons out of
stores and cut down on the shootings they can cause.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a dark hallway or alley ... they can easily be mistaken for
the real thing and provoke the kind of bloodshed we have seen all
too often,'' Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale or possession of a realistic fake gun such as a cap
gun, cigarette lighter or water pistol, was prohibited about six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But concerns about the would-be weapons have resurfaced since
Hartford police officer Robert Allan fatally shot 14-year-old Aquan
Salmon. Salmon's companions were toting gun-shaped cigarette
lighters. The teen-ager was not carrying one of the fake weapons at
the moment he was shot, but police found one gun-shaped cigarette
lighter at the shooting scene and another in the car in which
Salmon was riding.
</P>
<P>
   The boys were suspects in an attempted mugging, and witnesses
said they saw the guns.
</P>
<P>
   Public Safety Commissioner Henry Lee has said the gun-shaped
lighter was so realistic, he could not tell it was a fake by sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Dr. Lee can't tell the difference, a police officer at 2
o'clock at night cannot tell the difference,'' said Chief State's
Attorney John Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Allan was cleared of state charges last month following a
10-month investigation by Bailey's office. Federal and departmental
investigations are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Hartford police Chief Deborah Barrows said her department
will be checking city stores to ensure fake guns are not being
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said his office will also try to keep the replicas --
many of which he said are made overseas -- from reaching Connecticut
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our primary focus is on the importers and distributors,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said the crackdown also involves the Internet.
Officials from eBay, the Internet auction site, have said they will
also watch for fake guns being posted for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal contacted the company after seeing a cigarette
lighter gun being sold on their website. eBay then pulled the
replica off the virtual auction block.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Blumenthal, eBay lawyer Robert Chestnut said the
Internet site will warn all sellers of tobacco lighters about the
replica firearms laws.
</P>
<P>
   Sale or possession of a realistic fake gun is punishable by a
6-month prison sentence and $1,000 fine. Using one to commit a
crime is a felony that could carry a 20-year prison term, Bailey
said.
</P>
<P>
   In order to be exempt from the law, bogus firearms -- including
water pistols -- must be a different color than a real gun,
Blumenthal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0132 </TRAILER>
