<HEADLINE> Lawsuit Against Jay Leno Dismissed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A lawsuit accusing ''Tonight Show'' host Jay
Leno of slandering a car designer has been dismissed, Leno's
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   However, an attorney for auto designer Claudio Zampolli, who
sued Leno in November 1999 for $150 million, has appealed. Tristram
Buckley is asking the state's appellate court to reinstate the case
and name a new judge.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges Leno damaged Zampolli's reputation by
calling him names during a 1998 classic car show in Los Angeles.
The suit claims Leno called Zampolli a ''crook'' and spread rumors
that Zampolli promised cars but never delivered them.
</P>
<P>
   Leno's attorney, Ronald Berg, said the suit was dismissed
earlier this month after Buckley, failed to follow court
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley contends the judge assigned to the case was biased in
favor of Leno.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single ruling he has made, irregardless of the law, has
been in Mr. Leno's favor,'' Buckley said. ''This is far from
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
