<DOCNO> APW20000315.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy Expected To Win 7th Term  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The last time Massachusetts Sen. Edward
Kennedy sought re-election, he faced one of the stiffest challenges
of his long political career. This time around, he may not even
break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's likely Republican challenger is Michael J. Sullivan,
district attorney in Plymouth County, Mass. He has little money or
name recognition despite a solid political background that includes
three terms in the Massachusetts House and two terms as district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kennedy got a real scare in 1994,'' said Jennifer Duffy, an
analyst for the Cook Political Report. ''He learned the lessons you
learn from that kind of experience. He raised a lot of money early,
he tended the home fires. He's been running for this election ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is Kennedy, 68, now appears to have among the safest
seats in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no one alive who can beat Ted Kennedy,'' said
Democratic political consultant Michael Goldman of Boston. ''And
Abraham Lincoln would have a problem if he were to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Most campaign watchers give Sullivan, 45, about the same odds as
the race's other two candidates: Libertarian Carla Howell, whose
mantra is ''Small government is beautiful,'' and Philip Hyde,
running as a ''Timesizer'' who says he can eliminate poverty,
racism, sexism, unemployment and homelessness by shortening the
work week to 30 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In 37 years in the Senate, Kennedy has made a name for himself
as a champion of progressive causes, from voting and civil rights
to raising the minimum wage and universal health coverage. But his
triumphs often were obscured by personal problems, most notably his
decision to leave the scene of a fatal car accident in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   During his 1994 re-election bid, Kennedy still was dealing with
fallout from the rape trial of his nephew, William Kennedy Smith.
Kennedy testified at the trial and acknowledged going to a bar with
his son, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, and Smith, who while there met the
woman who later claimed she was raped. Kennedy suffered politically
even though Smith was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was also up against the notion that the new Democrats had
taken over, and old liberal icons were a bit out of date,'' said
Paul Watanabe, a political science professor at the University of
Massachusetts, Boston. ''All of that seemed to indicate he was
potentially ripe for the picking.''
</P>
<P>
   The race was bruising. Republican candidate Mitt Romney spent
$7.6 million and attacked Kennedy repeatedly. Kennedy painted his
opponent as a heartless capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   It was a close race until Kennedy ran an ad blitz featuring
workers laid off from an Indiana company financed by Romney's
business. In the end, Kennedy beat Romney 58 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it doesn't appear Sullivan will have enough money to
mount a serious challenge. At the end of last year, Sullivan had
only $11,000 in his campaign war chest, compared to $3.5 million
for Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan believes he can make up for his lack of money through
free media coverage and retail politicking. He also hopes
Massachusetts voters are looking for a change after nearly four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's an opportunity to bring a new perspective, a new energy
to the United States Senate,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan touts his blue-collar credentials. He worked his way
through Boston College and Suffolk University law school, beginning
on the Gillette factory floor and rising to an executive position
before starting his private law practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Voters are at least open to the idea there's an opportunity to
elect somebody from the middle class that is much more impacted and
affected by the policies that come out of Washington, D.C.,''
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Republican Party Executive Director John
Brockelman said Sullivan's longshot status is par for the course
for the GOP in the state, which has an all-Democrat congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Running as a Republican in Massachusetts is always like having
one arm tied behind your back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brockelman insists there is reason for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   November's ballot contains a state income tax reduction
question. ''That is certainly going to energize Republicans and the
blue-collar Democrats and independents the Republicans need to
win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy will not comment on potential opponents, his spokesman
Will Keyser said. But Goldman, the Democratic consultant, said
Massachusetts voters don't buy the concept of a blue-collar
Republican. And Kennedy has made a career out of helping the poor
and middle class, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone in the state knows that Ted Kennedy can deliver,''
Goldman said. ''If you're voter, why the heck would you want to get
rid of someone like that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0202 </TRAILER>
