<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Fire Rockets at Israelis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas fired volleys of Katyusha
rockets toward Israeli military positions near the border in
southern Lebanon today, sparking airstrikes, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 rockets fired from up to seven areas in hills southeast
of the port city of Tyre slammed near the international border 10
miles east of the coastal border town of Naqoura, said Timur
Goksel, spokesman for a U.N. peacekeeping force in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said it will withdraw by July from a border strip in
south Lebanon it has occupied since 1985 as a buffer against
cross-border guerrilla attacks on its northern towns.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours after today's rocket attack, Israeli warplanes
pursuing the source of fire twice struck the hills, the spokesman
said from Naqoura, headquarters of the 4,500-member U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon. The force has been deployed in parts of the south
of Lebanon since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on casualties from today's violence
and it was not clear whether any Israeli position was hit or
whether any rockets landed in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed guerrilla group fighting Israeli
forces in southern Lebanon, claimed responsibility for ''heavy
rocket and gun attacks on enemy border positions.''
</P>
<P>
   It said in a statement issued in Beirut that its Islamic
Resistance military wing launched the attack in retaliation for
Israel's recent air raids and attacks on civilians in the south.
''The Islamic Resistance affirms its maximum readiness to deter the
enemy,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's rocket attack came two days after Israeli-backed
militiamen from the South Lebanon Army shelled the village of
Mansouri on the edge of an Israeli-occupied border strip south of
Tyre, killing a Lebanese army soldier at a checkpoint and a
Lebanese civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has in the past fired missiles on northern Israel to
retaliate for Israeli and allied militia attacks on Lebanese
civilians in the south. However, the guerrillas have since last
June limited their attacks on Israeli forces in the occupied
enclave in southern Lebanon or near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has promised harsh retaliation if guerrillas attacked
northern Israel. On Feb. 8, its warplanes destroyed three power
stations in Lebanon, causing widespread electricity outages, to
retaliate for military casualties in Hezbollah attacks in the
south. Seven Israeli soldiers and about a dozen allied militiamen
have been killed in guerrilla attacks in southern Lebanon since
Jan. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
