<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Pressured Over Cambodia Tribunal  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After taking a hard line on a proposed
tribunal to prosecute Cambodia's Khmer Rouge leaders, the United
Nations is under increasing pressure to compromise to reach a deal
in talks starting Friday in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has been at loggerheads with Cambodia for
months over international participation in a tribunal to judge
Khmer Rouge chieftains, blamed for the deaths of an estimated 1.7
million Cambodians during the group's radical communist rule in the
late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. blessing is crucial to Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen for
the tribunal to be viewed as legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations has withheld approval and demanded more
international control over the proceedings to ensure Cambodia's
corrupt and politicized judiciary isn't manipulated by Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan has made clear that any joint
tribunal meet minimum standards of international justice -- and a
senior U.N. official warned that the United Nations wasn't
interested in ''settling this at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, France and Japan have been urging Annan
to take a more flexible and creative approach in defining those
minimum standards, suggesting compromise proposals as a way to
break a the impasse, U.N.-based Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The three countries have also lobbied Cambodia to move closer to
the U.N. formula, but all concerned recognize that the United
Nations cannot impose a tribunal on the country, one Western
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a balance,'' said French Ambassador Alain Dejammet. ''We
have to look at what has been done with regard to Indonesia, with
regard to South Africa, and to try to find out something similar.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to moves by the United Nations to allow
Indonesia to proceed with its own prosecution of military officials
accused of atrocities in East Timor, and South Africa's own process
of finding justice for victims of apartheid, mainly through a Truth
and Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Annan has taken at least some of their suggestions
and advice to heart, particularly concerning the role of
international judges on the court, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   David Sheffer, the U.S. ambassador for war crimes, wouldn't go
into details about the proposals or negotiations, but said he
believed a deal could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think that the differences that remain between the U.N. and
Cambodia on these issues are resolvable,'' Sheffer said in a
telephone interview from his Washington office. ''But they do
require some very serious discussions between the two parties, and
we look forward to that actually taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Khmer Rouge were expelled from power by a Vietnamese
invasion in 1979, but remained a fierce fighting force throughout
the 1980s with the help of Thailand, China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas' power rapidly declined after the end of the Cold
War. Hun Sen orchestrated the collapse of the movement in the late
1990s by offering defection deals to several senior leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Critics fear that several defectors will escape justice if a
tribunal is left in the hands of an underdeveloped Cambodian
judiciary that has close links with Hun Sen's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   In his last letter to Hun Sen dated Feb. 8, Annan repeated the
U.N. demand for a majority of international judges and an
international prosecutor who could work independently of a
Cambodian prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats say Annan had already indicated a new willingness
to consider a U.S.-sponsored compromise that the Cambodians had
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ''super-majority'' formula, Cambodian judges would
have a majority on the court but would require a vote from an
international judge for any decision to convict or acquit.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 10 letter, Hun Sen said he was surprised by ''the gap
between the position raised in your letter and ours, which has been
already supported by a number of distinguished U.N. member states''
-- an apparent reference to the U.S.-sponsored super-majority
formula, which France has also supported.
</P>
<P>
   When Annan and Hun Sen met in Bangkok on Feb. 12, it appeared
the dispute was resolved. Both emerged after 30 minutes of talks
upbeat and expressing hope that the remaining differences could be
hammered out. Annan announced a team would go to Phnom Penh to try
to reach agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen told reporters that the two had overcome
misunderstandings sown through the media and a recent exchange of
letters -- a suggestion that Annan's Feb. 8 letter simply hadn't
reflected a possible U.N. compromise on the ''super-majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the judges, Annan's letter lists three other
''fundamental'' issues that must be worked out: an international
guarantee that those indicted be arrested, guarantees about limits
on amnesty, and prosecutorial independence -- considered to be the
key sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the U.N. delegation that left New York on Tuesday
for Phnom Penh is Hans Corell, the U.N. legal counsel who is
believed to have pressed hardest for the rigid line in U.N.
demands. But Annan has also dispatched a trusted aide, Shashi
Tharoor, in hopes of reaching a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffer urged all sides to ''keep their eye on the big
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The picture is that 1.7 million Cambodians were extinguished
during the Pol Pot era, and it remains our collective
responsibility to bring senior Khmer Rouge leaders to justice for
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Correspondent Chris Fontaine in Phnom Penh
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
