<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Satisfied With Nuclear Changes  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress created the National Nuclear Security
Administration last year to help streamline an Energy Department
bureaucracy blamed for security lapses and other problems with the
government's nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks after the semi-autonomous agency got going, it
came under fire from both congressional critics and department
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the department had interfered with the agency's
autonomy and had perpetuated unclear lines of authority. Department
officials said the law creating the NNSA gave some program managers
the idea they would be insulated from Energy Department oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ''This (NNSA) legislation was not ideal, in our opinion,''
Deputy Energy Secretary T.J. Glauthier told a House Commerce
subcommittee Tuesday. ''We want to make the best of what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the agency late last year in response to
allegations that lax security at the Energy Department and nuclear
weapons laboratories may have led to the theft of nuclear secrets
by China.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy came to a head last year when Wen Ho Lee, a
former scientist at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico was fired after being investigated for possible espionage.
</P>
<P>
   He was later indicted on charges he transferred top-secret
computer files to portable data tapes. Although Lee had been named
as a suspect in Chinese espionage, he has not been charged with
giving secrets to China or any other foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a Taiwan-born U.S. citizen, has pleaded innocent and sued
the federal government over news leaks about his case.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department resisted creating the semiautonomous
agency. Then it drew fire from critics by giving several of its
security and safety managers the same jobs within the new agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Heather Wilson, R-N.M., and several other Republicans said
Tuesday that ''dual hatting'' violated the law creating the new
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department appears to be violating the semi-autonomous
intent of the law in order to comply with its implementation,''
said Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla. Stearns later asked Glauthier,
''You're not breaking the law, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this is well within the statute,'' Glauthier
replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0218 </TRAILER>
