<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's key stock index fell on Wednesday, pulled
down by slumping technology shares. The U.S. dollar slipped against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 63.24
points, or 0.33 percent, to 19,078.60. On Tuesday, the average fell
48.09 points, or 0.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.80 yen in afternoon trading, down 0.34 yen
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and below its overnight level of 105.05
yen in late New York trading.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, big names in electronics and
telecommunications were prominent among retreating shares. An
overnight pullback by technology stocks on Wall Street provoked
selling in Tokyo, though the Nikkei gained back some ground in late
trading.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Tuesday, the tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite Index
fell 200.61, or 4.1 percent, to close at 4,706.63. That fall was
second only to a 229.46-point slide it suffered on Jan. 4. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average closed down 135.89, to 9,811.24.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed
on the first section gained 23.46 points, or 1.41 percent, to
1,605.43. The TOPIX closed up 23.82 points, or 1.5 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers picked up a wide range of stocks amid signs that Japanese
institutional investors had finished their customary selling ahead
of book closing for the end of the fiscal year on March 31, said
Hiroichi Nishi, a deputy general manager at Nikko Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar's slip came after Japanese
banks sold the greenback in a round of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar moved as low as 104.96 yen at one point in the
morning, but recovered some of its early losses as dealers bought
back the U.S. currency amid concern over possible yen selling by
Japanese monetary authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the Bank of Japan intervened on the foreign
exchange market in Tokyo in an attempt to stem the yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese government officials have said a strong yen could hurt
the country's already ailing economy by cutting into exporters'
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The yen has gotten a lift in recent sessions from data
suggesting the world's second-largest economy may be starting to
lift out of its slump. Machine orders and capital spending both
rose in the October-December quarter even as gross domestic product
shrank 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 102.12 yen, up from
101.22 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.8100 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.7950 percent. Its
price fell 0.6 point to 99.44.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Militia Has Little Option  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJIDIYEH CAMP, Lebanon (AP) -- On the rocky slopes beneath an
Israeli border outpost, South Lebanon Army militiamen learn to use
the semiautomatic rifles and well-worn tanks provided by their
Israeli allies.
</P>
<P>
   Training hasn't let up, officers say, even though Israel's plan
to withdraw its forces from southern Lebanon by July has made the
future of the 24-year-old militia uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The soldier works to the end,'' said Maj. Said Ghattas, who is
in charge of training at Majidiyeh Camp, about half a mile from the
Israeli border. ''You can't say 'I don't want to because Israel is
leaving.'''
</P>
<P>
   SLA members speak with bravado about following their general,
Antoine Lahd, whatever the course. But the options -- from fighting
on to fleeing the country -- look bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a day after the Israeli Cabinet's decision to
withdraw, the Supreme Court rejected a request for political asylum
from fighters in an Israeli-backed Lebanese militia.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials, however, say they are making plans to protect
the militiamen if a unilateral Israeli withdrawal goes through.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to act on Israel's
''moral and actual obligation'' to the SLA and said a commission
headed by his adviser on Lebanese affairs, Uri Lubrani, would
determine the needs of SLA members and recommend action.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA, active before allying with Israel in the 1980s, has not
indicated whether it would stop fighting after an Israeli withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not say anything until we see what happens in the
future,'' Raymond Abu Murad, chief spokesman for Lahd, told The
Associated Press in Marjayoun, 10 miles west of the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the militia's fate is whether an Israeli withdrawal from
the border zone accompanies an agreement with Syria, Lebanon's
neighbor and chief power broker.
</P>
<P>
   If Syria wants to, it could exert enough pressure to stop a
guerrilla campaign to end the Israeli occupation. With Syria's
approval, Israel also could win safety for the SLA.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement, many residents and some SLA militiamen
predict worse bloodshed in the form of revenge attacks by
guerrillas. Hezbollah, the main guerrilla group fighting Israel,
says it will not stop the guerrilla war until Israel has left every
inch of Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
   Ghattas said SLA fighters are ready to turn their guns over to
the Lebanese army if it moves in and ensures security in the area.
Lebanese government forces could throw SLA fighters into jail,
since under Lebanese law cooperating with Israel a crime.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no security, Ghattas said he is willing to fight on.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Israel moves out, we will take the orders from General
Lahd,'' he said. ''We are ready. We have armies, guns, tanks. We
are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The SLA has about 160 tanks, he said, including the dozen
45-year-old Russian T-55s and three American M-130s parked at
Majidiyeh.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 new members are in a two-month, weekends-off training
program, he said. SLA veterans also participate in weeklong courses
updating them on the latest Israeli information on Hezbollah
tactics and logistics.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA alliance provided Israel with a friendly force along the
border amid the chaos of Lebanon's 1975-90 civil war. The militia
also reduced Israel's dependence on their own troops to patrol the
border and protect northern Israeli towns from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many Lebanese, however, saw the militiamen as traitors who were
fighting their own people and serving as sandbags for their masters
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The late Maj. Saad Haddad formed the militia in the late 1970s
after leading his troops to take control of a border strip from
Palestinian guerrillas. With his back to the border, he sought --
and received -- Israel's help and was fired from the Lebanese army.
Lahd took over a revamped force after Haddad died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 Christian, Shiite Muslim and Druse fighters are part
of the SLA, out of belief in the cause, for economic reasons or
because they were coerced into the service. Hundreds have been
killed or wounded fighting alongside Israeli soldiers against the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Ghattas said he also is ready for what he considers the least
desirable option after an Israeli withdrawal -- leaving his hometown
and country. Israel, he is confident, will not to abandon Lebanese
who fought alongside its soldiers for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel knows all that we need -- money, passports, homes, any
country. But this is what I do not want,'' Ghattas said.
</P>
<P>
   If all the militiamen and their families were to leave that
would mean resettling around 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Gantous Abu Farhad, 24, said he joined SLA three months
after his brother and brother-in-law were killed in a Hezbollah
explosion in 1998, and has no plans to leave Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't come for the money or anything. I came because I want
to be a soldier,'' he said. ''I'm not afraid. ... I know we are not
losing. We are winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0230 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Prepare for Battle Ahead  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Their presidential nominations at last
secured, Al Gore and George W. Bush dug in for the eight-month
battle to November. Bush declared his mission is ''ending the
Clinton-Gore era'' while Gore warned that Bush would resurrect the
policies of his father that ''drove our economy into the ditch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also brushed off as a stunt Gore's latest challenge, his
promise to hold off on television ads funded by ''soft money'' as
long as Bush does, too.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a president who lost the White House in 1992 to
Democrats Bill Clinton and Al Gore, Bush cast his own Republican
effort as pay back for his father's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must face one more Clinton-Gore campaign,'' Bush told
cheering crowds at an Austin, Texas, community center. ''We will
confront their tactics one more time, and this time, we will
prevail and they will fail.'' His mission, he said, is ''ending the
Clinton-Gore era in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose late father was a longtime Tennessee senator with
unfulfilled White House ambitions, was equally personal in
describing himself as better prepared to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are two avenues leading from November of 2000. The path
that I want to lead our country toward continues our prosperity,
uses the surplus for constructive purposes,'' Gore told supporters
at a Tallahassee, Fla., high school gym.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other fork in the road leads off toward the right wing and
curves around back toward the approach that failed during the
Bush-Quayle years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush, the Texas governor, and Gore, the Democratic vice
president, celebrated Tuesday night after anticlimactic primaries
in six Southern states -- Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma,
Tennessee and Texas -- pushed each man well beyond the number of
delegates needed to win their parties' presidential nominations at
the national conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   An AP analysis showed Bush's delegate count would reach 1,093,
and Gore's would reach at least 2,530 -- far more than required by
each party.
</P>
<P>
   All suspense was drained from the primaries last week when
Republican John McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley bowed out of a
race that had spurred record-breaking voter turnout. Former
ambassador Alan Keyes remained on GOP ballots, but was not a threat
to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was low Tuesday but exit polls exposed general-election
vulnerabilities for both candidates: Gore's supporters were not as
motivated as Bush's, while Texas Republicans reported
disappointment with Bush's education agenda.
</P>
<P>
   After 2{ grueling months of virtually nonstop campaign travel,
Gore promised ''there will be no let up at all.'' He was headed
today to Pennsylvania, whose April 4 primary is now essentially
moot, to address an AFL-CIO state convention and attend a
fund-raiser in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to savor his victory and try to wipe out a
lingering cold by relaxing at the Governor's Mansion. A brief
vacation also was planned following a day trip Thursday to
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to campaign as hard as we did during the
primaries,'' Bush said on ABC's ''Nightline,'' adding: ''I'm going
to build the base.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made a feint at collegiality with an e-mail to Bush --
subject: ''Hello and congratulations'' -- to challenge him on the
ads, funded by unregulated contributions, that both parties plan to
use to help their nominees after the costly primary fights.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will take the first step by requesting the Democratic
National Committee not to run any issue ads,'' Gore wrote. ''It's
up to you and your party whether you want to start the ad war arms
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed the offer. ''If I believed him, I might be
willing to accept it. But this is a man who said he wanted to ban
soft money, and then turned around, announced he's going to go out
and raise $35 million of soft money,'' Bush told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, dismiss fascination with retired Gen. Colin
Powell as a potential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little early to talk about vice presidents, but there's
no question that a man of Colin Powell's stature would send a
strong signal to America that I know how to attract the best minds
in America. Of course, I'm going to talk to him. And I hope I can
count on his support,'' Bush said on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   In a hopeful sign for Bush, exit poll surveys by Voter News
Service for The Associated Press and the television networks
suggested that he ran stronger among Democratic voters than Gore
did among Republican voters. Just 6 percent of voters in Republican
primaries said they would vote for Gore in November; twice as many
Democrats said they would defect to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's home state of Tennessee, Republicans showed an intense
dislike of their native son with only 4 percent of those voters
saying they would vote for Gore in November.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, half the Republicans as well as half the Democrats
said Bush was more conservative as presidential candidate than
during his landslide re-election as governor in 1998. And, as Bush
tries to campaign on his education record, 40 percent Texas
Republicans said there have not been ''significant reforms'' in
Texas public schools during Bush's six years as governor compared
to 50 percent who said there have been significant reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0233 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chasm Between Ky. Cops, Mayor Grows  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CHAMBERS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- When the police chief honored two white
officers involved in the shooting death of an unarmed black
suspect, the mayor skipped the ceremony to show his disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Dave Armstrong didn't stop there. The next day, he fired
Chief Gene Sherrard, saying the commendations were ''insensitive''
and widened the chasm between the black community and the police
department. Both the mayor and the chief are white.
</P>
<P>
   If Sherrard's decision to honor the officers damaged relations
between blacks and the police, Armstrong's decision to fire
Sherrard has devastated the relationship between police and the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police officers and supporters marched to City Hall
in Sherrard's defense early this month after the chief was fired.
They plan another demonstration Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That should stop, that should not happen,'' Armstrong said.
''The citizens are speaking out -- unfortunately someone is not
listening or else they are trying to further divide the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the marches illustrate how out of touch police are with
blacks, who make up about 30 percent of Louisville's 269,000
residents. The police force is 16 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the uproar is a dramatic drop in the number of
arrests. Officer David James, vice president of the Louisville
Fraternal Order of Police lodge, has said police ''are consciously
afraid to make arrests because the mayor doesn't support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Rudolph, 18, was shot last May as he tried to escape in
a stolen vehicle. Police fired 22 rounds into the vehicle, saying
they feared Rudolph was going to run them down.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting sparked outrage in the black community. A grand
jury cleared the officers of criminal wrongdoing, but a city probe
found errors by police in the shooting and subsequent
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual police awards banquet, Officers Chris Horn and
Paul Kinkade were among several given the Exceptional Valor Award.
A police spokeswoman said the two were honored not for shooting
Rudolph but for surviving a risky situation.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony angered not only the mayor but the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation of Desmond Rudolph is not an isolated case in
Louisville, Kentucky. These are repeated incidents,'' said Dr.
Walter Malone Jr., a black minister who serves on the city's
Interdenominational Coalition, a group of ministers and other
advocates for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has also suggested that some officers engage in racial
profiling, a charge that prompted the Rev. Jesse Jackson and his
Rainbow Coalition to call for a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   George Osborne, a 43-year-old black resident, said he believed
Armstrong's comments about racial profiling -- where minorities are
singled out by police -- were correct.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it goes on for a fact. I've never had any problem with
them, but I know people who have,'' Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders and some on the city's Board of Aldermen have
renewed a drive for civilian review of the police department.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Swicegood, an attorney for the FOP, said Armstrong should
reinstate Sherrard.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's the one pouring gas on the fire,'' Swicegood said of the
mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0233 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Has Hard Road in the South  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore has his work cut out for him in the
South. A chunk of Democratic voters say they will support
Republican George W. Bush for president in November, but the bloc
of GOP voters willing to cross party lines to vote for Gore is much
smaller, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   About 13 percent of Democratic voters interviewed after leaving
the polls Tuesday in the six Southern states that helped Bush and
Gore clinch their parties' presidential nominations said they
preferred Bush -- twice the portion of GOP voters who said they'd
cross over to support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And more than 20 percent of Democrats said they had a favorable
view of Bush, the governor of Texas. Half as many Republicans had a
favorable view of Gore, the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews, conducted by Voter News Service, a consortium of
The Associated Press and the television networks, contained even
more good news for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Half of Bill Bradley's supporters said they'd pick Bush over
Gore in November. And in Louisiana and Oklahoma, Bradley backers
preferred Bush by a 3-to-1 margin. By contrast, just a third of
those who voted for Sen. John McCain in the GOP primary said they
would support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Bradley and Republican McCain dropped out of the race
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Bush and Gore enjoyed across-the-board support Tuesday,
particularly among partisans in their home states of Texas and
Tennessee, respectively. More than 90 percent of Democrats in
Tennessee and of Republicans in Texas said they would support their
favorite sons in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We voted for George W. Bush. He's our man,'' said Gertrude
Miller, 55, of Lubbock, Texas. ''We are pleased with what he's done
in the state of Texas and we look forward to what he can do for the
nation. Obviously we feel like we know him.''
</P>
<P>
   And 76-year-old Athaleen Watson, voting in Gore's hometown of
Carthage, Tenn., cast her vote for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who else?'' she said. ''I've voted for Gore for as far back as
I can remember... We've got good times and I'd like to see that
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, 16 percent of Democratic voters said they'd cross
parties to vote for their governor. But only 6 percent of Tennessee
Republicans plan to vote for Gore. In fact, eight in 10 Tennessee
Republicans have an unfavorable view of Gore, compared with just
two-thirds of Texas Democrats with unfavorable views of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were warnings for Bush in the exit polls from his
home state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush often points to his widespread support in Texas, where he
cruised to a second term as governor in 1998. But half of the
voters Tuesday, in both Democratic and Republican primaries, said
he has been more conservative as a presidential candidate than he
was in that Texas landslide.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush is running on his education record in Texas, many
Texans aren't convinced. About four in 10 GOP voters said there
have not been ''significant reforms'' in Texas schools under Bush,
while five in 10 said there have been. More than six in 10
Democratic voters agreed the schools have not been significantly
reformed under Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted at selected precincts in the six
states -- Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 6,297 voters in the GOP primaries and 5,312 voters
in the Democratic primaries had error margins of plus or minus 1.5
percentage points. Margins of error are larger for subgroups,
including individual states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
