<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police, NATO Take Over Serb Bridge  </HEADLINE>
By ELENA BECATOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Italian police and NATO
troops took control of a key bridge today despite Serb warnings of
trouble, a first step toward uniting this ethnically divided city
and reasserting international control.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 armed peacekeepers backed by armored personnel
carriers set up a cordon on the Serb-controlled north side of a
bridge linking the ethnic Albanian south bank of the Ibar River
with an ethnically mixed neighborhood called Little Bosnia on the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Troops ordered four Serbs who had been guarding the north end of
the bridge to leave, and they did so quietly. A crowd of up to 300
Serbs gathered around the cordon 250 yards from the northern end of
the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   More than two hours after the operation began, there had been no
incidents. One Serb man, who gave his name only as Vasile, said he
was outraged at the NATO action.
</P>
<P>
   ''They pretend they are trying to protect us but they are trying
to expel us'' from Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once access to Little Bosnia is secured, troops plan to take
full control of a larger bridge that has been the scene of
confrontation among Serbs, ethnic Albanians and peacekeepers since
the effective division of the city, which began soon after NATO
entered Kosovo in June.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs oppose unification because they claim NATO cannot protect
them against revenge attacks by the ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Ivanovic, a Serb official in northern Kosovska Mitrovica,
said he had been told of the plan Tuesday evening by French Gen.
Pierre de Saqui de Sannes. Ivanovic said Serbs cannot accept the
move and warned that it could spell trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The only civilians who would be allowed in the zone are those
who live there, Ivanovic said -- meaning Serb bridge guards would be
required to leave the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who used to live in the neighborhood are afraid
to return as long as the Serb guards remain there. The Serbs,
however, consider the guards their only reliable defense against
revenge-seeking ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ''This measure will create greater tension, and I think that it
will lead to a certain amount of conflict and I think it could lead
to the expulsion of Serbs or their fleeing the area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic said he was told that NATO's commander in Kosovo, Gen.
Klaus Reinhardt, and the chief U.N. administrator, Bernard
Kouchner, were expected here today to oversee the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have our army, we don't have our police. Therefore,
we aren't capable of resisting,'' Ivanovic said. ''We believe the
safety zone will become an area of insecurity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0237 </TRAILER>
