<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross' attorneys present evidence omitted from first trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- Evidence the state Supreme Court ruled
was improperly withheld from Michael Ross' defense before he was
sentenced to die was presented to jurors at the serial killer's
second penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The defense rested Tuesday after attorney Barry Butler read to
the jury a letter written by Dr. Robert Miller, a former
prosecution psychiatrist, in an attempt to show the existence of a
mitigating factor in Ross' life that would spare him the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't see how I could testify to psychopathology not playing
a mitigating role in the type of penalty,'' Miller wrote 13 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was sentenced to die in 1987 for the murders of four young
women in Eastern Connecticut and currently is serving two life
sentences for two other killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, which upheld Ross' capital felony
convictions, ordered the new penalty hearing after ruling the
exclusion of Miller's letter in the first trial prevented the
defense from possibly swaying the jury to impose a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Miller letter goes to the core of this case,'' Butler
said. ''The Supreme Court seized on this very document in their
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has attempted to build an argument that Ross suffers
a mental defect rendering him unable to control his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution disagrees, and argued Ross had no remorse in the
killing of the four women.
</P>
<P>
   If the defense can show the existence of a single mitigating
factor, Ross must be sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to end the case came as a surprise, because several
people on the defense witness list, including the Most Rev. Daniel
P. Hart, Roman Catholic bishop of Norwich, were not called to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   The court recessed until Friday, when rebuttal arguments are
expected to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Thomas P. Miano said the matter could go to
the jury for deliberation as early as Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
