<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First lady drew cash from Pakistanis, as president pondered visit  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Those who think they can gain White House
influence through a check to Hillary Rodham Clinton's U.S. Senate
campaign are wrong, the first lady says.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anybody thinks they can influence the president by making a
contribution to me they are dead wrong,'' Clinton said Tuesday
after a campaign event in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady defended her decision to take thousands of
dollars from Pakistani-Americans as negotiations were underway at
the White House over whether the president should visit Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser in question -- a $1,000-a-person dinner held Feb.
22 on Staten Island -- gave contributors a chance to spend two hours
pressing the first lady on why the president should visit Pakistan
and become involved in the dispute over Kashmir, a Himalayan
territory also claimed by India. It raised $50,000 for Mrs.
Clinton's Senate bid against New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a brief stopover in Pakistan was added to the
president's planned tour of South Asia that begins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had spoken with the president about visiting
Pakistan after the fund-raiser, the first lady said, ''I don't talk
about what I talked to the president about on any issue.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was nothing illegal about the fund-raiser, Scott
Harshbarger, president of the advocacy group Common Cause, said it
still feeds the perception that access can be bought.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we find troubling is that a group of Americans are being
told that the price of admission is $50,000 to have access to a
future U.S. Senator,'' Harshbarger said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raising event, Clinton said she hoped her husband
would visit Pakistan, her campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson
confirmed. But Wolfson stressed that the president has been saying
for more than a year he would like to visit Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has denied that the first lady played a role in
the president's choice to go to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The contentious relationship with India made the decision to
visit Pakistan a difficult one for the Clinton administration. The
world's two newest nuclear countries reached the brink of war last
summer. Tensions were heightened again last October by a military
coup in Pakistan and the Christmas-eve hijacking of an Indian
Airlines plane with what many in India believe was Pakistan's
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The February fund-raiser was hosted by Suhail Muzaffar, a Staten
Island businessman, and Asim Malik, a Long Island doctor, on behalf
of the Pakistani community on Staten Island and Pakistani-American
Physicians Political Action Committee, according to The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers told The Times they had pushed the event to an
earlier date so that it could take place before the president's
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought it went very well, in terms of the message and the
timeliness of it, especially in terms of the president's going to
the region,'' Muzaffar said.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance was Lanny Davis, a special counsel to the
president during the fallout from the 1996 fundraising scandals.
Davis, now a lobbyist for the Pakistani government, has urged the
president to visit Pakistan and said there was nothing unseemly
about the first lady's fund raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is there anything wrong with people concerned about issues to
raise those issues with a candidate?'' Davis said Tuesday. ''That's
about as shocking as finding gambling at Rick's casino.''
</P>
<P>
   News of Clinton's attendance at the fund raiser was first
reported in the Staten Island Advance and picked up by newspapers
in India.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson pointed out that the first lady has also taken donations
from Indian-American contributors largely opposed to the president
visiting Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just Clinton's ties to the president that are drawing
Pakistanis to support her Senate bid. Some are unhappy with
Giuliani's crackdown on taxi cab drivers and street vendors, many
of whom are Pakistani.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said little about Clinton's fund-raiser at a news
conference at City Hall on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever happened with Pakistan -- or didn't happen -- I don't
know. Somebody else can figure that out,'' the mayor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Pitch Perfect Game  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Roger Maris temporarily got an asterisk
when he needed more than 154 games to break Babe Ruth's home run
record. When the strike canceled the 1994 World Series, the Toronto
Blue Jays got to call themselves champions for another year.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of tainted baseball achievements, add this: The
Boston Red Sox pitched their first perfect game since Cy Young, but
they did it in an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care if it's spring training or not,'' catcher Joe
Sidall said Tuesday after six Boston pitchers combined on the 5-0
victory over the Toronto Blue Jays. ''We've got a lot of pride, and
we're trying to do the best we can. Everybody strives for
perfection, and to achieve it is an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez struck out six in three innings, then Fernando De
La Cruz pitched two innings and Dan Smith, Rheal Cormier, Rich
Garces and Rod Beck one apiece. Nomar Garciaparra homered and drove
in four runs for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, the perfect game -- 27 up, 27 down -- is
considered the ultimate baseball accomplishment. There have been 14
perfect games in the modern era, most recently David Cone's for the
New York Yankees last July 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox haven't had a regular-season perfect game since
Young pitched the first of the modern era on May 5, 1904. No Boston
pitcher has pitched a no-hitter since Dave Morehead in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no formal records kept for no-hitters in spring
training exhibitions. The last no-hitter in spring training was on
March 16, 1996, when California beat San Francisco 15-0.
</P>
<P>
   As baseball accomplishments go, this one was more like the home
run that went over the right-field wall off Jose Canseco's head
than Don Larsen pitching a perfect game in the 1956 World Series:
It was memorable, even noteworthy, but not important.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll take it,'' Garces said. ''It's kind of exciting.
Hopefully, it will happen in a real game.''
</P>
<P>
   The achievement inspired so little awe, in fact, that fans were
streaming out of the park in the late innings, and several of the
pitchers involved didn't know what they'd done until later.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no clue. Someone just told me,'' Cormier, who pitched
the seventh inning, said about 20 minutes after the game. ''It
would probably be more exciting if you were watching the whole
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Players don't always sit in the dugout for the whole game in
spring training. Starters who are taken out early run sprints in
the outfield, get treatment in the clubhouse and sometimes leave.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who threw nine innings of a perfect game in 1995
before allowing a hit to lead off the 10th, was talking to
reporters outside the Boston clubhouse when the last out was
broadcast on television.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pitched a perfect game!'' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Although many fans had left, those who remained stood and
cheered for the final outs. Beck knew something was going on
because Sidall celebrated every strike, but the reliever had to
wait until the last out in the ninth to find out what was up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm kind of embarrassed about that,'' Beck confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Woodward hit a fly ball to the warning track for the
second-to-last out. When Alberto Castillo struck out, ending the
game, Sidall pumped his arm and ran out to greet Beck -- and tell
him what he'd done.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pointed to the scoreboard and said, 'I think that's right,'
'' said Sidall, who caught a no-hitter in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Although a regular-season perfect game is usually celebrated
with a pileup on the mound, the Red Sox shook hands and headed back
for the clubhouse. Beck made sure Martinez got the game ball.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew what was going on. You see three eggs on the wall,
you're hoping for nine before it,'' manager Jimy Williams said,
referring to all the zeros on the scoreboard. ''You put a dozen
eggs on the wall, that's a pretty good indication that you've got a
pretty good chance to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rocker Pitches Perfect Inning  </HEADLINE>
By FRED GOODALL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- A standing ovation didn't surprise John
Rocker, who didn't have to throw a pitch to claim a personal
victory in his spring debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta reliever took another step to put a turbulent
offseason behind him, pitching a perfect ninth inning Tuesday night
in a 4-0 exhibition win over the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said his control could have been sharper, though he only
needed 13 pitches to retire Gregg Jefferies, Javier Cardona and
Robert Fick to finish a three-hitter by Braves pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Fans stood and cheered at the end, just as they did when he
sprinted to the mound from the right-field bullpen for the first
time since the World Series -- and the controversial magazine
interview that resulted in his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best thing I got out of the standing ovation was it
finally showed you people in the media that not everybody is
against me, the 25-year-old left-hander said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been running into nothing but positives ever since all
this stuff happened ... And yet every night I turn the TV on and
see how horrible a person everyone says I am. I don't see it in the
public when I'm out. Now maybe some people will say, 'Not everyone
is against him,' like the majority of the media is trying to make
it be.''
</P>
<P>
   The outing didn't attract the horde of reporters that Rocker's
arrival to spring training did two weeks ago. However, it was an
overwhelming hit at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   The game drew a record 10,078 to the Braves' spring training
complex at Disney World, including one young fan who held up a
''Rocker for President'' sign when the reliever entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   And while Schuerholz and manager Bobby Cox insisted the game was
like any other exhibition for the Braves, the only thing routine
about the night was Rocker's performance.
</P>
<P>
   He saved 38 games to help Atlanta win the NL pennant last
season, and it didn't look like missing two weeks of spring
training set him back far, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was disappointed with my control, pleased with my stuff,''
said Rocker, who threw three straight balls to Jefferies before the
Tigers outfielder took a called strike and then popped out to third
base.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the left-hander's last 10 pitches were for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told everyone I was going to come and throw 75 to 80 percent
to let myself get in shape first. I can't pitch like that. I tried
it. I can't do it ... My fastball was really good in the pen. My
slider was really bad in the pen. It was kind of reversed on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardona grounded to third before Fick struck out to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that from his perspective, it was difficult to consider
the outing anything but an opportunity to get ready for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He threw like we thought he was going to throw,'' the manager
said. ''It was his first time out, but it looked like his fifth. He
was outstanding. All of our pitchers were.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager also said the reception from the crowd, the largest
for a Braves home game since the team moved its spring training
camp to Disney in 1998, was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody's willing to give people a second chance,'' Cox
said. ''He's getting his second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fick, who struck out on a 2-2 pitch, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know what? People say things. People make mistakes. He's
not a drug addict. I've made mistakes. We all do,'' Fick said.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was suspended for all of spring training and the first 28
days of the season by commissioner Bud Selig after the reliever's
disparaging comments about minorities, gays and foreigners were
published in Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But an arbitrator allowed the pitcher to report March 2, cut the
regular-season suspension to two weeks and reduced a $20,000 fine
to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Rocker got a feel for what kind of crowd was in
the stands when he worked his way up the right-field foul line,
signing autographs and chatting with fans crammed against a
railing.
</P>
<P>
   Two amusement park security guards, dressed in black-and-white
striped referee's shirts, accompanied him and kept a group of
photographers and television cameramen out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Atlanta's regulars showered and left the complex by the
end of the game. Rocker finished a postgame workout before speaking
with reporters, he said, ''out of respect for Cox.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It just seemed like another night to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pitched 75 games last year -- 10, 15 spring training games.
Once again, the media is out here making a big deal out of it. It
was an inning of a meaningless spring training game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
