<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Talk Follows Angels' Edmonds  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Despite an offseason full of rumors, Jim
Edmonds is still where he's always been as a major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation had him playing in Seattle by now, or maybe Oakland
or even New York. But Edmonds remains the Anaheim Angels' starting
center fielder. At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody says I'm getting traded, but our front office says
I'm not,'' Edmonds said. ''Who do you believe? I've heard them say
I'll be in the opening-day lineup, but then I hear they're calling
everyone about me. I'm not naive. I know what's going on out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   With Darryl Strawberry suspended and George Steinbrenner growing
disillusioned with Ricky Ledee, the Yankees might be the most
likely team to acquire Edmonds at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's interest has cooled with the surprising play of
Terrence Long in spring training. Long is hitting .469 with 17 RBIs
in 32 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is hesitant to trade for the potential free agent unless
they can sign him to a long-term deal -- something Edmonds insists
he won't do for any team.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Yankees, who have the players and the
willingness to wait until after the season to talk contract.
</P>
<P>
   While Angels general manager Bill Stoneman has said he needs to
be ''overwhelmed'' to trade his starting center fielder, a scare
with rookie right-hander Ramon Ortiz could change all of that.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz was scratched from his start Monday with tightness in his
right biceps. The injury is not believed to be serious, although it
does raise questions. Anaheim already had a surplus of outfielders
-- with Garret Anderson, Tim Salmon and Darrin Erstad -- and a need
to shore up a shaky pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels could be going into the season with a rotation of
Ortiz, Ken Hill, Tom Candiotti, Kent Mercker and Jarrod Washburn --
a group that went a combined 22-30 last year.
</P>
<P>
   That has piqued their interest in New York's Ramiro Mendoza, 9-9
with a 4.29 ERA last season as he shuttled between the rotation and
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But Yankees manager Joe Torre is wary about parting with
Mendoza, who provides insurance for the rotation if rookie Ed
Yarnall shows he's not ready for the big leagues or if age catches
up to David Cone or Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as Mendoza proved in last year's playoffs against Boston,
the right-hander could be Torre's most valuable set-up man in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can we be a better offense team? Possibly,'' Torre said. ''But
at the expense of taking away from your strength. Then you have to
make a decision. Unless there is a gaping hole, I'm reluctant to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Strawberry gone, Ledee struggling and Shane Spencer
and Roberto Kelly unable to seize either the left field or DH job,
Torre doesn't believe there is a gaping hole in New York's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have enough bodies here,'' Torre said. ''I'm sure
we can cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   New York also might part with shortstop prospect Alfonso
Soriano. The Yankees have been giving Soriano time at second base
recently, which just happens to be one of the positions the Angels
would like to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds not only would fill an immediate need for New York as a
left-handed power hitter who averaged nearly 28 homers a year
between 1995-98, he also provides insurance if Paul O'Neill decides
to retire after the season.
</P>
<P>
   But getting him could create an ego clash in the outfield for
New York, where three-time Gold Glove winner Bernie Williams is
already entrenched in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is loyal and would prefer to keep Williams there, while
Edmonds, a two-time Gold Glove winner himself, expressed doubts
about changing positions earlier this spring. He has changed his
tune recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to happen,'' Edmonds said of a trade. ''But I'd
play third base if it meant I could win a World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0308 </TRAILER>
