<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan President Battles Rumors  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's president today denied rumors
that he is secretly urging supporters to dump his ruling
Nationalist Party's candidate and support the opposition's
presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a white Nationalist campaign jacket instead of his usual
dark suit, President Lee Teng-hui assured party leaders at their
weekly meeting that he still backs Lien Chan in Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''The more votes Lien gets, the more secure our country will
be,'' Lee said about his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   He urged supporters not to listen to rumors spread by what he
described as dirty tricks squads deployed by the two other top
candidates in the tight race, Taiwan's second direct presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's critics within his party have long suspected that the
popular president is closer to candidate Chen Shui-bian of the
Democratic Progressive Party. Chen has supported Taiwanese
independence, and many believe Lee secretly shares this view.
However, Chen has softened his stance on independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who will retire, easily won the island's first direct
presidential election in 1996. ''People are trying to judge whether
he is throwing his weight behind Lien or Chen,'' said Joseph Wu,
deputy director of the Institute of International Relations in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding the rumors, some close Lee supporters have endorsed Chen
in recent days, saying the candidate would be more likely to carry
on the ''Lee Teng-hui line.'' Many believe Lien may abandon crucial
parts of Lee's China policy, which insists the two sides should
discuss their differences as equals.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is Lee's hatred of independent candidate James
Soong, a former protege of the president who was expelled from the
party for running against Lien.
</P>
<P>
   Today, while Lee reaffirmed his belief that Lien would be best
able to deal with rival China, Soong told reporters at a news
conference that he would be the best negotiator with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not only the favored leader of the people here but also
the favored leader of this region,'' Soong said. ''Not only favored
by neighboring countries like (China) but also by the U.S. and
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, meanwhile, the Chinese Communist Party today
defended Beijing's right to use force to keep Taiwan from declaring
independence.
</P>
<P>
   A commentary in the People's Daily, the ruling party's flagship
newspaper, claimed a victory for Beijing, suggesting that it
successfully pressured pro-independence candidates to moderate
their stances ahead of Taiwan's election.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of independence ''recently have had to temporarily
pack up the banner of Taiwan independence'' because of ''strong
pressure from the Chinese government and Taiwanese voters' desire
for peace and stability,'' said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
   To steer voters away from pro-independence candidates, Beijing
has repeatedly threatened in recent weeks to attack Taiwan if it
declares independence or indefinitely rebuffs demands for talks on
unification.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan split amid civil war in 1949. But Beijing still
regards the island as part of its territory, to be united by force
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, Taiwan's slumping stock market closed 195.55 points,
or 2.2 percent, lower, despite buying by government-linked funds.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said nervous investors have been selling stocks
this week, fearing that post-election political changes could hurt
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Chen Shui-bian's Democratic Progressive Party,
http://www.dpp.org.tw
</P>
<P>
   Independent James Soong, http://www.soong.org.tw/global/
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist Vice President Lien Chan,
http://www.yes2000.org.tw/english/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
