<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Text Leaves Opponents Unmoved  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is hoping that
release of the full text of its sweeping trade agreement with China
will help round up the congressional votes needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say nothing in the 250 pages should persuade
wavering lawmakers to vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big news on the release of the trade deal with China is
what's not in it,'' House Democratic Whip David Bonior of Michigan
said Tuesday. ''There is nothing on worker rights, nothing on the
environment, nothing on human rights or democratization and no
strong enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials sent the text of the agreement Tuesday
to every member of Congress and released it to news organizations,
hoping to counter attacks from critics who argue that Congress
should not vote on a deal that voters could not see.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident that once people have reviewed the agreement,
they will see for themselves that this is a tremendous deal for
American workers, farmers and businesses,'' U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky said.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations last November, China offered to open its vast
market in return for U.S. support for China's membership in the
World Trade Organization. Under WTO rules, however, American
exporters cannot receive benefits of the reduced trade barriers
until Congress scraps its annual reviews of China's trade
privileges in the U.S. market and bestows low tariff rates
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents charged that the wording of the text released by the
administration raised serious questions about how enforceable
China's commitments were.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, various U.S. administrations have
negotiated deals to open China's markets to American companies only
to complain later that China did not live up to its commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have is the same mushy language we have had in the
past,'' said Scott Nova, director of the Citizens Trade Campaign,
one of the consumer groups joined with organized labor and
environmental organizations to fight the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials, however, argued that the deal reveals
specific language, including target deadlines, by which time China
has promised to dismantle a host of trade barriers that American
exporters have long complained about.
</P>
<P>
   ''To those who are concerned that these commitments by China
will not be honored, let me assure you that we are already
preparing for the most intensive enforcement effort ever mounted
for a single trade agreement,'' U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers said Tuesday in a speech to the American Electronics
Association.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration expects China's permanent trade status
to win Senate approval with little difficulty, the legislation
faces a difficult struggle in the House, where labor unions are
putting pressure on Democratic lawmakers to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has said the
administration will have to come up with 100 Democratic votes
before he will call up the measure for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior said he believed two-thirds of the 211 House Democrats
will oppose, which would give the president only 70 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Rules Committee Chairman David Dreier, R-Calif., said Tuesday
that release of the actual text should make the job of supporters
easier. But he agreed with Hastert that a full vote is impossible
until Republicans are assured of sufficient Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been holding a series of meetings with
lawmakers at the White House, but Republican leaders have
complained that he and Vice President Al Gore have not done enough
to round up Democratic votes.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky's office said Tuesday that a decision has not been
made whether to post the text on the Internet. It covers specific
tariff cuts and trade barrier reductions for more than 5,000
products and services.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Administration China trade site:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 0310 </TRAILER>
