<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Texans Seek Archer Seat  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Rep. John Culberson emerged from a field of eight
Republican candidates as the top vote-getter in the state primary
Tuesday for a chance to replace retiring House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Bill Archer.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson fell short of the majority needed for an outright
victory and will face businessman Peter Wareing in an April 11
runoff in the solidly Republican 7th District centered in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual GOP nominee is considered a shoo-in this November
against Jeff Sell, the lone Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who went to Congress in 1970 replacing future President
George Bush, was the only one in Texas' 30-member House delegation
not to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, actor Noble Willingham of ''Walker, Texas
Ranger'' fame won the GOP nomination to take on Democratic Rep. Max
Sandlin, who defeated a primary challenge from a plumber.
</P>
<P>
   And in Dallas, former Clinton White House official Regina
Montoya Coggins easily turned back a primary opponent and will face
Republican Rep. Pete Sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison was unopposed in her
primary as she bids for a second full term. Democratic Party
leaders pinned their hopes on Charles Gandy, who served one term in
the Legislature in the early 1980s. But Gene Kelly, a retired Air
Force lawyer who has lost six previous statewide bids, snared the
top berth in the April runoff and Gandy was in a tight battle for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republicans also approved a non-binding resolution
supporting voluntary student-led prayer at sporting events. The
referendum was approved 94 percent to 6 percent in early returns.
Republicans called it a way for voters to speak up before the U.S.
Supreme Court hears arguments March 29 in a closely watched Texas
case involving student-led prayers before high school football
games.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   --In Mississippi, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who is
seeking his third term, escaped a primary challenge. Troy D. Brown
Sr., an unsuccessful candidate for lieutenant governor last year,
will face national party committeeman Rickey Cole in the April 4
Democratic runoff. In the 4th Congressional District, District
Attorney Dunn Lampton beat off a primary challenge to face freshman
Democratic Rep. Ronnie Shows.
</P>
<P>
   --In Florida, two-term Orlando Mayor Glenda Hood easily won
re-election in a hotly contested race where the city's clogged
streets had become the central issue. In tiny Briny Breezes, an
oceanside mobile home park near Boca Raton, voters re-elected
77-year-old Mayor Robert Conkey, who spent $11 in his campaign. His
83-year-old opponent didn't spend a cent. No elected official in
the town has had any competition since 1977. And in Wilton Manors,
John Fiore, an openly gay city council member, was elected mayor of
the city north of Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
</TEXT>
