<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Urged on Extradition Laws  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Siblings of the woman killed by former
counterculture guru Ira Einhorn have asked Congress to reform
extradition laws to make it easier to return fugitives to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a few black-and-white things left in this world,''
Buffy Hall, one of Holly Maddux's sisters, said at a news
conference outside the Capitol on Tuesday. ''This very much
addresses the issue of bringing countries into line to do what is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn, 59, fled the country in 1981, shortly before his trial
in a Pennsylvania court. The former prominent anti-war activist in
Philadelphia was sentenced in absentia to life in prison for
Maddux's 1977 slaying. The Tyler, Texas, woman's corpse was found
stuffed in a trunk in a closet at Einhorn's Philadelphia home.
</P>
<P>
   After living in England, Ireland and Sweden under false names,
Einhorn was arrested in France in June 1997. France's high court
threw out an appeal in May, leaving it up to Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin to sign an extradition decree.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn has denied killing Maddux but blames her death on a
conspiracy involving ''large intelligence agencies.'' Under a new
Pennsylvania law, he would face retrial on his return.
</P>
<P>
   The family is supporting legislation that would penalize people
in the United States who knowingly provide money to fugitives to
help them remain abroad. The law also would ban military or
economic assistance to any country that the State Department
classifies as uncooperative in helping return fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   It also would require the State Department to submit annual
reports on extradition to Congress that provide details about the
number of criminals awaiting extradition to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials were not available for comment on
their position on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., the bill's sponsor, said it probably
would have no effect on the Einhorn case but would force countries
to cooperate and force the State Department to pay more attention
to extraditing criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he and Maddux's three sisters and a brother had a
''very positive'' meeting Monday with officials at the French
Embassy but said they had been given no timetable for Jospin to
sign the decree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
