<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demand outstrips capacity as new Stephen King story is publishedonline  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stephen King's latest story is definitely scary,
but not in the way he intended.
</P>
<P>
   The fright comes before you even read ''Riding the Bullet,''
which was published Tuesday only on the Internet. Web sites
including Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble.com were swamped by high
demand for the horror master's 66-page ghost story, and downloading
it was near impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the servers have reached 100 percent capacity and gone
over several times today,'' said Pat Eisemann, a spokeswoman for
Scribner, the co-publisher with King's Philtrum Press. ''Everybody
is pretty much crashing, and you can't get through.''
</P>
<P>
   The story went online at several book-related Web sites at 12:01
a.m. at a cost of $2.50, although Barnes &AMP; Noble made it available
for free on Tuesday and Amazon.com had no plans to charge for the
download.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press began trying to download ''Riding the
Bullet'' via Barnes &AMP; Noble and Amazon.com at 10 a.m. Tuesday and
had not succeeded by 3 a.m. today. Attempts to read the story using
Glassbook Reader, software that had to be downloaded first, were
met with, ''We're sorry. Due to overwhelming demand, we are
experiencing much greater load on our servers than normal. Please
try your download again later.''
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt posted on the Simon &AMP; Schuster Web site begins with a
college student learning that his mother has suffered a stroke. The
story is told in the first person and is set in Maine, King's home
state.
</P>
<P>
   King wrote the story while recuperating from near-fatal injuries
he sustained when he was hit by a van last June.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by his secretary, the best-selling
author of more than 30 books said he was ''very excited at the
possibility of a new market opening up.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''and as a dedicated and long-term Mac user, I am
surprised and a little unhappy at how hard it is for Mac users to
access the story, but thank God for the Palm Pilot, which is making
it accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisemann, the Scribner spokeswoman, said Mac users were not able
to access the story Tuesday but the problem would be fixed as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're finding out through this what some of the glitches
are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While many books are available on the Internet, few prominent
writers have chosen to publish online only.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stephen King's decision to publish his new short story in
electronic format is a concrete declaration that the e-book format
has arrived,'' said Steve Riggio, vice chairman of Barnes &AMP;
Noble.com. ''We see a time in the not too distant future when
virtually every book in print will be available in both physical
and electronic formats.''
</P>
<P>
   King was more cautious in his own statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''While I think that the Internet and various computer
applications for stories have great promise, I don't think anything
will replace the printed word and the bound book,'' he said. ''Not
in my lifetime at least. At the end of the day, I am still a great
fan of hard copy, as my longtime secretary and personal assistant,
Marsha DeFilippo, will attest.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.borders.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.simonandschuster.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.barnesandnoble.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0315 </TRAILER>
