<HEADLINE> Bourque Close To 400th Goal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A week ago, Ray Bourque's chances of getting 400
career goals before the end of the season were an afterthought.
Four games with the offensive minded Colorado Avalanche, and the
possibility doesn't seem so remote.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not after Bourque scored his 398th goal as the
Avalanche beat Anaheim 4-2 Tuesday night for their sixth straight
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought I would get there this year,'' Bourque, in his
21st season, said. ''I had five to go when I got here and I have
scored three in four games. That is not like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque scored his third goal for the Avalanche, 4-0 since the
March 6 trade that brought the defenseman to Colorado from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew what we were getting,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley
said. ''He is a proven all-around defenseman, he is a great passer
with a great shot, and so far no one has been disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   In other NHL games, it was Tampa Bay 4, Montreal 3; and Detroit
3, Nashville 2 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque has also helped improve Colorado's power play. During
the last 10 games, the Avalanche have produced five power-play
goals, three by Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have so many options on our power play now,'' Hartley said.
''If they want to take Ray's shot away, it leaves more room for
Milan Hejduk, Peter Forsberg and Joe Sakic to work down low.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Or they can give Ray time to tee it up like he did tonight,''
Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque broke a 1-1 tie with his 13th goal at 2:20 of the third.
He also added an assist. Sakic also set up a goal and has 16 points
in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic scored for the seventh time in as many games as the
Avalanche extended their lead in the Northwest Division to four
points over Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Tverdovsky and Ted Donato scored for Anaheim, winless in
three games (0-2-1). Dominic Roussel started in place of Mighty
Ducks goalie Guy Hebert, who was injured Saturday when hit by
teammate Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
Lightning 4, Canadiens 3
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Modin scored twice, and Vincent Lecavalier added his
20th goal as Tampa Bay ended a seven-game losing streak by winning
at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Linden scored an early goal, but broke two ribs and is
out for the season. Montreal is in a seventh-place tie with
Pittsburgh in the playoff race, just a point ahead of Carolina and
the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
Red Wings 3, Predators 2, OT
</P>
<P>
   At Detroit, Brendan Shanahan scored his second goal of the game
4:10 into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Fedorov also scored for the Red Wings, who moved within
two points of idle St. Louis for first place in the Central
Division. Detroit, on a season-best eight-game unbeaten streak
(6-0-2) also got three assists from Nicklas Lidstrom and two from
Tomas Holmstrom.
</P>
</TEXT>
