<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge calls Hamilton the 'gatekeeper' of the election fraud plan  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The political director for ousted Teamsters
President Ron Carey says he got so carried away in his desire to
free the union of corruption that he became corrupt himself.
</P>
<P>
   William W. Hamilton told U.S. District Judge Thomas P. Griesa
that his crimes were meant to help keep the union out of the hands
of those who had corrupted it in the past. Griesa sentenced him to
three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes when you try to do something you believe in deeply,
you do dumb things, you cross the line, you overreach,'' he said at
the Tuesday sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Griesa said his desire to do right did not absolve him of his
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge also said it would be ''unreasonable and
unmerciful'' not to credit Hamilton for his devotion to public
service and civil rights causes throughout a 30-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he somewhat reluctantly moved downward from
federal sentencing guidelines calling for a nearly four-year prison
term, as he is permitted to do for extraordinary public service.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was convicted of authorizing $885,000 in contributions
to four political organizations in 1996 in exchange for
contributions to Carey's 1996 re-election campaign. Prosecutors
said the amounts were staggering considering the union was nearly
broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hamilton did not initiate that concept but he agreed to
play a role in it and his role was crucial,'' Griesa said. ''He
was, in effect, the gatekeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 57, was convicted last November after a three-week
trial for embezzlement, mail and wire fraud and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he was thrilled in 1989 when the federal
government seized control of the powerful Teamsters union -- which
has more than one million members -- through a consent order meant
to separate union from mob influence.
</P>
<P>
   He said his trial and conviction had been a ''degrading and
humiliating'' experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am ashamed and deeply angry at myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial featured testimony from Richard Sullivan, former
finance director of the Democratic National Committee. He said
President Clinton's close friend and chief fund-raiser, Terence
McAuliffe, urged him and others to find donors for Carey.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we could get a $50,000 donor to Carey, ... he knew we would
get $500,000 from the Teamsters,'' Sullivan said McAuliffe told
him. The union is not permitted to use its money to fund elections
for union members.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats failed to produce a donor and the Teamsters did
not make a donation. McAuliffe was not charged with any crime and
his lawyer, Richard Ben-Veniste, said he cooperated with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Carey narrowly defeated James P. Hoffa in the 1996 Teamsters
election, which was overturned after investigators found Carey's
campaign improperly benefited from donations the union made to
organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 0328 </TRAILER>
