<HEADLINE> Newspaper: Charges to be filed against Allegheny executives  </HEADLINE>
phqjkb1 charges today against the director and two other former
officials of the bankrupt Allegheny health system, alleging misuse
of endowment funds, anonymous sources told The Philadelphia
Inquirer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former CEO Sherif S. Abdelhak is scheduled to be arraigned in
Pittsburgh today, according to two law-enforcement officials who
spoke to the newspaper on condition of anonymity. Former chief
financial officer David McConnell and former general counsel Nancy
Wynstra also are to be arraigned today.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what charges would be filed and whether they
would be felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the trio, who once led the state's largest health
system, did not return repeated phone calls Tuesday. Wynstra
declined comment when she was reached at home. Abdelhak and
McConnell could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Attorney General Mike Fisher would not confirm
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general filed a civil lawsuit last month against
Abdelhak, McConnell, Wynstra and five former Allegheny trustees
charging that they spent $78.5 million in restricted funds,
including medical endowments, before the system's Philadelphia-area
operations filed for bankruptcy in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In that lawsuit, Fisher accused Allegheny executives of
violating state law by diverting charitable assets to pay operating
expenses. Executives also may have used restricted funds to help
repay an $89 million loan to Mellon Bank and three other lenders.
At least five executives with ties to Mellon Bank were Allegheny
trustees; they have denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The former executives have been under investigation for more
than a year by state and federal authorities, including the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Investors say that even as Allegheny executives were skimming
from endowment funds, the executives received pay raises, bonuses
and lavish expense accounts.
</P>
<P>
   After Allegheny's collapse, eight of its Philadelphia-area
hospitals were sold to Tenet Healthcare Corp., the nation's
second-largest for-profit hospital chain. Drexel University took
over Allegheny's medical university, which includes MCP Hahnemann
School of Medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
