<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today as
investors awaited a pair of inflation reports due out later this
week. Technology stocks fell, extending Tuesday's selloff.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 32.57 at 9,843.81.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 52.12 at 4,654.51, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 2.03 at 1,361.18.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline compounded its 341-point loss in the past
two sessions. Yahoo! was off 6 13/16 to 161 15/16 today, and Ariba
lost 13[ to 267 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in those shares, which have been among the market's top
performers in 2000, suggested investors are taking profits from
their sharp gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies, which led the market's decline on
Tuesday after the United States and Britain agreed to share data on
genetics, regained some ground today. Human Genome Sciences rose 3
31/64 to 127.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle rose 4\ to 81\. The company, a leading maker of business
software, said after the close of trading Tuesday that
third-quarter profits soared 160 percent, easily surpassing
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks, which have dramatically underperformed the
Nasdaq so far this year, were holding up better today, but still
had trouble attracting buyers. Technology stocks helped push the
Dow into positive territory, with Intel rising 3 3/16 to 121 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said investors were reluctant to take major new
positions in the days ahead of the government's reports on the
Producer Price Index and the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The PPI, due for release Thursday, and the CPI, due out Friday,
are closely watched gauges of inflationary pressures. The Federal
Reserve is expected to take both reports under consideration when
it meets next Tuesday to discuss interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Many on Wall Street expect the Fed to raise rates. An increase
would be the fifth since last June, when the Fed began trying to
engineer a gradual slowdown in the economy to prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 141.37 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.80 to 566.19.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.0 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 2.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
