<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Exhibit Honors Quaker Relief  </HEADLINE>
By KEN KUSMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Horst Winkler stared into the photographs,
searching for an image that captured his own desperation more than
half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Was his among the expectant faces of hungry German
schoolchildren queuing for food distributed by Quaker relief
workers in the days after fighting had ended in Nazi Germany?
</P>
<P>
   ''I had forgotten about the Quakers after all these years, to be
honest with you,'' said the 69-year-old Winkler.
</P>
<P>
   But as he looked at the photo and a sampling of the worn metal
containers in which the children had received their food, the years
faded away. Winkler remembered the Quaker volunteers who provided
the sustenance that kept him, a younger sister and their mother
alive.
</P>
<P>
   His homeland hasn't forgotten, either. A German-sponsored
exhibit touring the United States recalls the kindness and relief
provided by Quakers, also called the Society of Friends, at a time
when others could not let go of the hatred forged by wartime
hostilities and the horrors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quiet Helpers,'' a collection of photographs, documents,
artifacts and news clippings, began a six-week run last week at the
Lilly Library at Earlham College in Richmond, Ind. It tells the
story of Quaker-run groups -- many of the volunteers practiced other
religions -- feeding the defeated German populations after both
world wars and helping victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The work earned U.S. and British Quaker groups the 1947 Nobel
Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, a car dealer who was 15 when World War II ended in
1945, said he emerged from the cellar where his family had holed up
for days without food wary of the GIs and other Americans the Nazis
had told him to fear.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers lounging around an armored personnel carrier offered
him bananas, and at a nearby school the American Friends Service
Committee set up a kitchen where he and his sister drank hot cocoa,
slurped lima bean soup and filled coffee cans with more food to
take home to their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had been starving for a year, more or less. We were all
just skins and bones,'' Winkler said. He came to the United States
in 1963 and now owns two Mercedes-Benz dealerships in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot possibly imagine the emotions we were under and the
conditions we were under. They were the enemy, and they didn't turn
out to be the enemy,'' he said. ''They were saints.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 500 U.S. and British volunteers served in Germany
after World War II, and about a dozen of them came to the First
Friends Meeting in Indianapolis for the exhibit's U.S. debut.
</P>
<P>
   The German Historical Museum in Berlin mounted the exhibit,
which traveled to 21 German cities over three years before making
its U.S. debut in Indianapolis. After Earlham, a Quaker-run
institution, it will travel to Dayton, Ohio; Seattle; San
Francisco; Washington, D.C.; Baltimore; Boston; Chicago;
Philadelphia and other stops over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-person unit from Britain's Friends Relief Service had been
among the first civilian relief groups to reach the liberated
Bergen-Belsen concentration camp near Hamburg. A video loop in the
exhibit includes Hugh Jenkins' description of finding the bodies of
many of the camp's 10,000 dead stacked like wood by the side of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, 85, who now lives in Washington, D.C., said the
experience was ''shattering.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was so much we had to do, we just concentrated on what
we were doing. That tended to insulate us a bit from the
circumstances in which we were working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Six teams of relief workers, including Friends, the Red Cross
and the Salvation Army, rescued about 25,000 people from
Bergen-Belsen, ferrying them by ambulance to a makeshift hospital.
They worked for weeks until authorities, worried about typhus and
dysentery epidemics, used flame-throwers to burn the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the items in the exhibit have never been displayed
before, and others come from collections at Quaker institutions.
They include a yellow Star of David the Nazis forced a Munich-born
Quaker child to wear because she had been classified as a Jew; a
gingerbread Christmas cookie cut into the shape of the
eight-pointed Quaker star was one of the thousands the AFSC
commissioned German bakers to make in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker beliefs and practices include peacemaking, living simply,
and seeking ethnic and sexual equality. The American Friends
Service Committee was formed in 1917 to provide conscientious
objectors with an opportunity to aid civilian victims during World
War I. Its latest relief efforts include aid to the victims of
flooding in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana is a stronghold of U.S. Quakerism with approximately
16,000 followers in the state, and provided many of the volunteers
who served in Germany.
------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: American Friends Service Committee:
http://www.afsc.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
