<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scythian Gold Tells Story of Nomads  </HEADLINE>
By THERESA BOWEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Across the flat grasslands of Ukraine, ancient
burial mounds stretch up to 100 feet high, preserving the gold
treasures of the nomadic Scythian warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these items are on display in Baltimore with ''Gold of
the Nomads'' at The Walters Art Gallery. The exhibition is the
largest and most all-inclusive collection of Scythian gold items
ever displayed outside of Ukraine, curators said.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts tell the story of the Scythian horsemen's culture
and lifestyle from the 7th through the 3rd centuries B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The gold, bronze and clay items have been preserved in the
Scythian tombs, called kurhans, which rest from 6 to 45 feet
beneath the ground and are covered by up to 100 feet of top soil.
The mounds span 300 feet in diameter at the base.
</P>
<P>
   ''While other nomadic tribes that at one time dominated this
region, such as the Huns and the Mongols, survive primarily through
tales of their ruthless conquests, the Scythians also left lavishly
provisioned tombs that have preserved one of the most complete and
stunning material records of any nomadic people,'' said Dr. Gerry
Scott III, curator of ancient art at the San Antonio Museum of Art
in Texas, where the exhibit made its U.S. debut in November.
</P>
<P>
   The nomads buried their dead with an elaborate combination of
ritual and ceremony, which varied based on the importance of the
deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists have found that the writings of 5th-century B.C.
historian Herodotus accurately describe the embalming, human and
animal sacrifice, and burial process reserved for group leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonies were less elaborate for common men and women, but
they were often buried with an arsenal of weapons, helmets,
shields, and cooking and storage pots.
</P>
<P>
   The Scythians prospered through trade with the Greeks, and
commissioned Greek and Scythian artists to craft gold jewelry and
plaques for battle and personal adornment during ceremonious
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   A bow and arrow case excavated from one kurhan is enveloped in
gold with Greek-like figures in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ''They borrow elements from other traditions to tell their
stories,'' said Dr. Ellen Reeder, deputy director for art at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art in New York, who curated the exhibit with
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Although the figures are influenced by Greek art and mythology,
they are adapted by the Scythians. For example, the ''prudish''
Scythians have clothed figures that would be naked in Greek art,
Reeder said. The scenes do not depict Greek stories; rather, the
Scythians have borrowed Greek figures to tell their own stories.
</P>
<P>
   ''These were cultures that were forming dialogues together,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scythian art illustrates the group's interest in movement,
evolution and the power of animals. The use of the eagle, spotted
and snow leopards, boar and the equivalent of a present-day elk
recall the animal depiction of Central Asia. A round, finial piece
depicts a leopard morphing into an elk-like animal.
</P>
<P>
   The only indication of the Scythians' love for beautiful items
during daily life were the raspberry-colored or royal blue fabrics
they wore as they roamed the plains, weighed down by 50 pounds of
equipment, including a helmet, shield and weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Reeder said Ukraine will be explored much more in the future,
and noted that many of her Ukrainian colleagues hope to embark on
partnerships with the United States. ''It has been called the
richest land on this planet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Excavations continue on the more than 40,000 kurhans that have
remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   ''America can be part of a frontier in archaeology,'' Reeder
said.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 170 objects in the exhibition have been compiled
from the Museum of Historical Treasures of Ukraine, Kiev; The
Institute of Archaeology of the Academy of Sciences of Ukraine,
Kiev; and the Ukraine State Historical Archaeological Preserve.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibit marks the first time since 1975 that some of these
items have traveled to the United States. It also includes more
recently unearthed artifacts available for display in the West only
since Ukraine gained its independence from the former Soviet Union
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gold of the Nomads'' is organized by The Walters Art Gallery
and the San Antonio Museum of Art. The exhibition will remain in
Baltimore through May 28, before moving to Los Angeles; Brooklyn;
Ontario, Canada; Kansas City and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The ''Gold of the Nomads'' exhibition is open Tuesdays through
Sundays from 10 a.m.-5 p.m. at The Walters Art Gallery, at North
Charles and Centre streets. Contact the museum at 410-547-9000.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet: www.thewalters.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1203 </TRAILER>
