<DOCNO> APW20000315.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Movie Buffs Find Rare Antiques  </HEADLINE>
By JESSICA FARGEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- After antique hunting for eight hours, Deb
Ginsberg promised her weary friend Marilyn Wagner that a stop at
Franx Antiques and Art would be the day's last.
</P>
<P>
   Wading through the vintage pictures and dusty vases, the two
women asked to browse through a back storage room of the Old Market
store, where a sliver of Hollywood's storied past had sat for 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   The movie buffs stumbled upon 50,000 authentic print blocks and
8,000 press plates used to print movie handbills from eras when
Marilyn Monroe liked it hot and The Mummy first made theatergoers
squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deb said, 'What do you think of these?''' Wagner recalls about
their find in November 1998. ''I picked one up and I just went
nuts. I said, 'This is it. You've found the perfect thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   An appraiser from Christie's Auction House in New York agrees.
He calls the uncovered collection the ''holy grail'' of movie
memorabilia, valued at $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just floored,'' says Rudy Franchi, a movie poster
consultant for Christie's who came to Omaha in disbelief after
hearing about the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured they had all been melted down for something because
nobody would think they had any value,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg and Wagner, who own a screen printing business, paid
less than $10,000 for the metal plates and small wooden blocks --
remnants of a time when Omaha's bustling printing houses made movie
advertisements for theaters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes plates and blocks dating from the 1930s
to the 1970s for 10,000 movies, including ''The Wizard of Oz,''
''The Godfather,'' ''Jailhouse Rock,'' ''Star Wars,'' ''Gone With
the Wind'' and ''A Hard Days Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Other popular titles include ''Casablanca,'' ''Dracula,'' ''How
to Marry a Millionaire,'' ''The Seven Year Itch,'' ''To Catch a
Thief,'' ''East of Eden,'' and Breakfast at Tiffany's'' and
''Sabrina,'' both starring Audrey Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   ''We started going through them and started realizing what we
had here was a very extensive history of motion pictures,''
Ginsberg says. ''Very extensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The antique store's owner, Helen Novak, revealed the stash of
movie goods to Ginsberg, a regular customer.
</P>
<P>
   Novak's husband bought the plates 25 years ago for less than
$1,000 from KB Typesetting Co. in Omaha. Novak knew the plates and
blocks were valuable, but still balks at the estimated $2 million
value.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had my use out of them,'' Novak says. ''We did sell some; we
even traded some. I certainly had no intention of sorting those
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Over several months, Ginsberg and Wagner loaded 400 boxes -- all
told weighing nearly 16 tons -- into Ginsberg's 1989 4-door Corsica,
and moved them during several trips from the store's back room to
their printing business 10 miles away in South Omaha. Many of the
boxes had not been opened in 25 years, Novak said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than sit on their rare find or sell off the entire
collection, they use the metal plates to restrike movie
advertisements the same way they were printed 60 years ago -- by
hand with a 1,700-pound 1938 Vandercock letter press.
</P>
<P>
   They sell the black and white reproductions for $50 framed and
matted on the online auction site eBay. Some of the blocks, made
when drive-in movies were the lifeblood of small towns, also are
popular sellers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure I could take the whole lot to Christie's and have a
wonderful day, turn myself into a millionaire over night and forget
it,'' Ginsberg says. ''But then what did I accomplish?''
</P>
<P>
   They have sold about 2,000 of the small wooden movie blocks,
magnesium-plated on the face side, for as high as $480 apiece. They
are selling the blocks that they have duplicates of, Wagner says.
People collect the blocks, ranging in size from 1-inch to 7-inch
squares, for paperweights, knickknacks or nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to brisk sales in the United States, they have
shipped off several hundred blocks and restrikes to buyers in
Brazil, Australia, Japan, France and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Wagner and Ginsberg say they have not heard of any
opposition to their enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a real purist might be a stick in the mud,'' says
Bruce Crawford, a local film historian. ''I think for some purists
it may be a problem, but for the majority of people they think it's
great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1204 </TRAILER>
