<HEADLINE> Allegheny health system executives charged  </HEADLINE>
By TODD SPANGLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Criminal charges were filed against the
director and two other former officials of the bankrupt Allegheny
health system, alleging they misused $52 million in charitable
endowments, the state Attorney General's Office announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested today were former chief executive officer Sharif
Abdelhak, former chief financial officer David McConnell and
general counsel Nancy Wynstra, said Attorney General Mike Fisher.
Each was charged with theft and other offenses, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelhak and McConnell were being arraigned today. Wynstra was
expected to surrender Monday, Fisher said. Lawyers for the three,
who once led the state's largest health system, did not immediately
return calls today for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general filed a civil lawsuit last month against
Abdelhak, McConnell, Wynstra and five former Allegheny trustees
charging that they spent $78.5 million in restricted funds,
including medical endowments, before the system's Philadelphia-area
operations filed for bankruptcy in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In that lawsuit, Fisher accused Allegheny executives of
violating state law by diverting charitable assets to pay operating
expenses. Executives also may have used restricted funds to help
repay an $89 million loan to Mellon Bank and three other lenders.
At least five executives with ties to Mellon Bank were Allegheny
trustees; They have denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The former executives have been under investigation for more
than a year by state and federal authorities, including the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Investors say even as Allegheny executives were skimming from
endowment funds, the executives received pay raises, bonuses and
lavish expense accounts.
</P>
<P>
   After Allegheny's collapse, eight of its Philadelphia-area
hospitals were sold to Tenet Healthcare Corp., the nation's
second-largest for-profit hospital chain. Drexel University took
over Allegheny's medical university, which includes MCP Hahnemann
School of Medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
