<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of March
19-25:
<TEXT>
<P>
   65 years ago: Shirley Temple starred in ''The Little Colonel''
with Lionel Barrymore and Bill ''Bojangles'' Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeanette MacDonald and Nelson Eddy starred in ''Naughty
Marietta.'' It was their first film together.
</P>
<P>
   50 years ago: ''All the King's Men'' won an Oscar for best
picture. Broderick Crawford and his co-star Mercedes McCambridge
also won Oscars. It was McCambridge's first film.
</P>
<P>
   45 years ago: ''Blackboard Jungle'' starred Glenn Ford, Sidney
Poitier, Anne Francis, Vic Morrow and Richard Kiley. The film's
soundtrack featured Bill Haley's ''Rock Around the Clock.''
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: Pink Floyd's ''Another Brick in the Wall'' topped
the U.S. chart for the first of four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: F. Murray Abraham won the best actor Oscar for his
role in ''Amadeus,'' directed by Milos Forman.
</P>
<P>
   And Huey Lewis and the News won five Bammies at the eighth
annual Bay Area Music Awards in San Francisco. Lewis was named best
musician and his band won for best group and best song, ''I Want a
New Drug.''
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Arista Records drew on some of the hottest names
in the recording industry to mark its 15th anniversary with a
concert to benefit AIDS victims. Performers included Daryl Hall &AMP;
John Oates, Whitney Houston and Patti Smith. The concert was held
at Radio City Music Hall in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: More than 1,000 fans lined up outside a Tower
Records store in Los Angeles where Elton John signed old and new
recordings, including his latest, ''Made in England.'' The store
stayed open after midnight to sell the album on its release date.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Curtis received one of France's top awards for excellence
in the arts, becoming a Knight in the Order of Arts and Letters.
''At last I'm French,'' said Curtis, who starred in the 1959 film
''Some Like It Hot.''
</P>
<P>
   And Paul McCartney capped a performance of his more highbrow
pieces with a rendition of the 1968 Beatles hit ''Lady Madonna,''
backed by the Brodsky Quartet. He performed at a benefit in London
for the Royal College of Music. The evening featured excerpts from
McCartney's ''Liverpool Oratorio.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: ''Star Wars'' director George Lucas donated $1.5
million to create a new digital studio at his alma mater, the
University of Southern California School of Cinema-Television.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be quite nice to be an assassin -- some kind
of government agent. That would be heaven. I'd love it. You go off
spying with a large AK-47. I always wanted to do it, but I was
never recruited.'' -- Actress Elizabeth Hurley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1231 </TRAILER>
