<DOCNO> APW20000315.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Devon Sawa  </HEADLINE>
By CAROL DEEGAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Devon Sawa is running late.
</P>
<P>
   He took a quick break from a daylong schedule of media
interviews at a Park Avenue hotel to look for wrestling action
figures at nearby FAO Schwarz toy store. But he's about to enter
the hotel when he gets a cell phone call from a publicist who is
trying to keep him on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Sawa, who lives in Los Angeles, is promoting his new film,
''Final Destination.'' This is film No. 13 for the 21-year-old
actor (''Idle Hands,'' ''SLC Punk,'' ''Wild America''), who isn't
the least bit superstitious.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't believe in premonitions, either, unlike the character
he portrays in James Wong's feature directorial debut, which also
stars Ali Larter and Kerr Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ''Final Destination'' is the story of a group of suburban high
school teens who are flying to Paris on a school trip. Alex
Browning (Sawa) gets a powerful premonition that their flight is
doomed. He rushes off the plane, followed by several classmates and
a teacher. The plane departs without them. Minutes later, it
explodes in midair.
</P>
<P>
   Alex and his friends have cheated death.
</P>
<P>
   But death isn't easily discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ''Final Destination'' was shot in Vancouver, British Columbia,
where Sawa grew up. He became interested in acting at 11 and did
theater, commercials and TV shows before getting his ''first
break'' in the 1995 film ''Casper.''
</P>
<P>
   1. What attracted you to the role of Alex Browning?
</P>
<P>
   Sawa: This is my first adult lead. .. first young man lead. They
sent me the script, and actually I was getting on a plane. So I
read the script on the plane and went to meet James Wong, who I
thought had very interesting ideas of shooting this movie. And then
I auditioned for him up in Vancouver and got the part, and that's
basically how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   2. There are some spectacular scenes in ''Final Destination.''
Were there a lot of special effects?
</P>
<P>
   Sawa: It was very draining emotionally and physically because of
the many special effects that we had. But it was fun, it was lot of
fun to do. We had everything from houses exploding to cars
exploding to people being hit by buses. ... You know that someone's
going to die right now, but it's very interesting to see how they
do it, and that's what makes it so suspenseful. I think James Wong
did an amazing job capturing the suspense of this movie.
</P>
<P>
   3. Did you ever imagine in your wildest dreams that you would be
in a film like this?
</P>
<P>
   Sawa: No. Never. But I love this film. I just saw it a couple of
days ago for the first time and I really enjoyed it. I really
enjoyed the final product. I think audiences will enjoy it, too.
</P>
<P>
   4. Is Devon anything like Alex or vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   Sawa: Alex and Devon are completely different people. The whole
premonition thing is something that I do not believe in. I don't. I
try to live life day by day. And take it with a grain of salt and
not think about what my destiny is or what I do right now is going
to affect something that will happen in five years. Or 10 years.
It's just something I don't like to think about. I like to just
take everything day by day.
</P>
<P>
   5. But if you had experienced a premonition like the one Alex
had, would you have gotten off the plane?
</P>
<P>
   Sawa: If it was as powerful as the dream that Alex had, yeah, I
suppose I would freak out, too. He really felt the plane go down.
He really lived it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Top Fives in TV, Movies, Music  </HEADLINE>
