<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Pat Metheny  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES J. GANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pat Metheny describes his music as
''polystylistic'' -- rooted in jazz but using different
vocabularies, including rock, orchestral and world music. The Pat
Metheny Group's ''Imaginary Day'' album garnered Grammys in 1998
for best rock instrumental and contemporary jazz performance.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 45-year-old guitarist has taken a vacation from
his larger ensemble to devote himself to other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Metheny realized a personal dream by recording an album of
guitar duets with his mentor Jim Hall. He composed a poignant score
for ''A Map of the World,'' the film based on Jane Hamilton's novel
and starring Sigourney Weaver. And ''Trio 99-00'' (Warner Bros.)
with bassist Larry Grenadier and drummer Bill Stewart mixes old and
new Metheny compositions with fresh rearrangements of John
Coltrane's classic ''Giant Steps'' and the Broadway tune ''A Lot of
Livin' to Do.''
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of Metheny's musical vision is evident in the new
400-page, 167-tune ''Pat Metheny Songbook,'' which documents his
career dating back to his debut 1975 trio album ''Bright Size
Life.'' Metheny is now touring with his trio and expects to
reassemble the Pat Metheny Group later this year for a new
recording.
</P>
<P>
   1. How did director Scott Elliott choose you for the ''Map''
score?
</P>
<P>
   Metheny: Scott is a very interesting director, who has a real
vision of what he wants to accomplish in every aspect of his work.
I think he had decided pretty early on that I was his only choice
to write the music. He said he just 'heard' it in his head. ...
Scott was able to describe to me in pretty vivid detail the role he
felt the music should play in the context of the film as a whole.
So many times, music is an afterthought in films, or they could get
any of 10 people and be happy. Scott was not like that in any way.
</P>
<P>
   2. How do you feel your music matches with the film?
</P>
<P>
   Metheny: The first thing I did was to read the book. I couldn't
put it down. I could tell that there were things going on in this
story that I could 'talk' about in a musical way. The fact that the
story takes place in a small Midwestern town, not unlike the town
that I grew up in in Missouri, was also appealing. From the
beginning, I heard guitar in my head as an active voice in this
score. That is kind of a first for me. In most of the other scoring
stuff I've done, there is barely any guitar in any of it. This was
a score where I could play a big part as a guitarist, something I
really enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   3. What appeals to you about the trio as opposed to the Pat
Metheny Group?
</P>
<P>
   Metheny: One of the big attractions about trio playing is the
mobility of it. ... When I tour with my regular band, which often
has as many as seven musicians, if we want to do a new piece, it
really has to be thought about, arrangements need to be written.
... With the trio, five minutes before we go onstage, I can
describe a new tune to Larry and Bill and we can walk out there and
play it just like that. The truth is I love both things.
</P>
<P>
   4. How would you compare this trio to your earlier ones?
</P>
<P>
   Metheny: This particular trio is probably most like my original
trio with Jaco Pastorius and Bob Moses (on 'Bright Size Life') in
the sense that I consider Bill and Larry to be basically
contemporaries of mine. ... The incredible stylistic range that
they both have matches my polystylistic tendencies as a composer
and improviser really well, which was also true in that first band.
When I played with older legendary musicians like Charlie Haden and
Billy Higgins or Dave Holland and Roy Haynes, I really tailored the
music to feature the things that I loved about their music as much
or more than any efforts I made to define my own way of playing.
</P>
<P>
   5. Do you see any common link between your trio record and the
''Map'' soundtrack?
</P>
<P>
   Metheny: Both records are intensely personal to me -- albeit in
different ways. The 'Map' soundtrack, because of its acoustic
nature and the emphasis on the development of just a few themes,
allowed me to explore some of the qualities that I discovered on
the record (with bassist Charlie Haden) 'Beyond the Missouri Sky.'
That is, making the acoustic guitar a much more prominent part of
my thing than it ever had been before. Playing in a trio, because
of the reduced instrumentation ... tends to result in personal,
intimate music. Even though these records are quite different ...
they complement each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1232 </TRAILER>
