<HEADLINE> Japan Nasdaq To Start in June  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's version of the Nasdaq Stock Market will
open June 30 with limited hours and local rules, organizers said
Wednesday, promising that a 24-hour schedule and trading of foreign
stocks will come within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Though its backers have touted Nasdaq Japan as a step toward a
global trading network, Nasdaq and Japan's Osaka Stock Exchange
said Wednesday they planned to start with the same hours and
trading systems as the Osaka market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares will trade from 9 a.m. to 11 a.m. in the morning and from
12:30 p.m. to 3:10 p.m. in the afternoon, said Hirotaro Higuchi,
chairman of the Nasdaq Association of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Nasdaq Japan will extend the trading schedule to
24 hours a day and introduce a system that will allow trading of
Nasdaq stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new market expects to obtain the government's approval for
its proposed listing standards in April, and will start taking
listing applications from companies in May, said Kyoji Kitamura,
president of the Osaka Securities Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Japan is meant to enable fast-growing Japanese companies
to raise money while making it easier for Japanese investors to buy
and sell overseas stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-based Nasdaq established Nasdaq Europe in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
