<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of Leading IMF Candidate  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Horst Koehler's experience with global
diplomacy and economic reforms have made the former German
government aide the top contender to head the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the discreet 57-year-old is the first German at the
helm of a major international financial institution, heading the
London-based European Bank for Reconstruction and Development since
1998.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of the European Union, United States and Japan,
he is now poised to extend Germany's reach in global finance as the
next managing director of the 182-nation IMF. The fund has not yet
scheduled a vote, but it is likely to come well before the end of
March.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler's supporters say his background with the EBRD makes him
an economic heavyweight capable of streamlining the
Washington-based IMF, which provides emergency loans to foundering
economies.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's first candidate, Deputy Finance Minster Caio
Koch-Weser, was rejected by the United States as too lightweight to
push through the reforms many believe the IMF needs. He had spent
most of his career at the World Bank, only joining the German
government last year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Koehler worked for more than a decade in the German
Finance Ministry under former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who once
called him ''a treasure'' and relied on him in global economic
diplomacy. He was Kohl's envoy at meetings of the Group of Seven
industrialized countries, helped draft the legal framework for
Europe's single currency and played a crucial role in German
reunification in 1990. He also negotiated Germany's financial
contribution to the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler moved to the Association of German Savings Banks in
1993, where he presided over reforms to help privatize Germany's
traditionally state-connected banks.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 1{ years, he has taken the lead in helping reform
former communist countries through the EBRD. That agency was set up
in 1991 to promote market economies in Eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler was born in present-day Poland in 1943, the seventh of
eight children. His parents were ethnic German farmers from Romania
who had moved to the small town of Skierbiezow in southeastern
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler's family moved again to Leipzig in communist East
Germany after World War II, then fled to West Germany in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Known to his colleagues as an opera and theater buff who
sometimes has a short temper, Koehler is married with two children
in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: IMF site: http://www.imf.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1308 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
