<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Under Fire for Oil Changes  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Even though he helped engineer a huge
increase in world oil prices, President Hugo Chavez is being
criticized at home for policies that some say could undermine the
long-term health of the world's second-largest state-owned
petroleum company.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 executives of Petroleos de Venezuela, known as
PdVSA, have resigned since Chavez took office more than a year ago
promising to do away with what he called the oil firm's ''gold card
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has scaled back plans to expand Venezuela's oil
production capacity, slowed a policy to open the oil sector to
private investment and filled the upper ranks of the
45,000-employee company with political loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's detractors say he's endangering the financial autonomy
of a company long considered an oasis of efficiency and good
management in a country notoriously lacking in both. His
appointment of Hector Ciavaldini, a former executive fired from
PdVSA in 1995, as the company's president has ''created confusion
and low morale,'' said Andres Sosa Pietri, a former PdVSA
president.
</P>
<P>
   To counter such criticism, Chavez often points to his role in
raising oil prices, largely by reversing Venezuela's long-standing
position as a ''quota buster'' in the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of the Chavez administration, Mexico and Saudi
Arabia agreed to join Venezuela in a March 1998 production cut to
boost oil prices that had reached 12-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world oil industry was teetering on the verge of
insolvency. World producers should give thanks to Mexico, Saudi
Arabia and Venezuela for rescuing them,'' said Antonio Szabo, an
oil consultant based in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The oil price increase has been a lifesaver for oil-dependent
nations that had been reeling from the effects of sagging prices.
The price of a barrel of Venezuelan oil is now at a nine-year high
of $28.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for the first time in memory, an oil-price boom has not
translated into an economic recovery in Venezuela, where the
economy shrank by 7 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   To Sosa Pietri, the price increase has been too high and too
fast, contributing to an overvalued currency that discourages other
exports and harms local manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has a perverse effect on the economy,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Oil Minister Alvaro Silva told The Associated Press last
week that the Chavez government agrees the soaring prices are not
healthy. He said he was sure OPEC nations would agree on production
increases at a March 27 meeting in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one wants to return to abrupt price changes, we all agree
on that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has pledged to put oil to work for the poor in this South
American nation of 23 million people. A PdVSA tanker provided
drinking water and a company airplane brought medicine to survivors
of recent flooding that killed thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also insist they remain committed to oil expansion,
albeit at a slower pace, and will capitalize on Venezuela's
comparative advantages: the largest oil reserves in the Western
Hemisphere, relatively low extraction costs and proximity to the
United States, which purchases most of Venezuela's oil.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge will be to attract oil investment in a politically
charged atmosphere characterized by Chavez's constant verbal
attacks on the private sector and a legal framework put into flux
by a new constitution pushed through by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Viergutz, an oil industry executive bidding to participate
in a pipeline project in Venezuela, said he's optimistic about
opportunities in the oil sector because of current prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Venezuelan oil industry, regardless of who is in the
government, is an extremely important provider of foreign reserves
and income,'' he said. ''No government is going to allow the oil
industry to decay.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: PdVSA site: http://www.pdvsa.pdv.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
