<HEADLINE> Clinton Holds Gun Control Rally  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton accused the National Rifle
Association of political skullduggery today as he welcomed fellow
Democrats and an improbable Republican to a White House pep rally
on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has been in a war of words with the NRA
for several days, said the gun group was threatening to retaliate
against members of Congress who voted against it on a gun measure
today.
</P>
<P>
   The House planned to vote on a bill urging members of a
House-Senate conference committee to begin reconciling two versions
of gun control measures passed last year.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, the bill would be only a recommendation to the
negotiators trying to write the compromise. The conference
committee has been idle since its inaugural meeting in August,
which Clinton said today is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't want this conference committee to meet,'' Clinton
said of the gun lobby. ''Why is that? They know the people aren't
with them, that's why,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the few Republicans who joined him today want the
committee to begin work because they, like the White House, want
some kind of action this year. Clinton said he did not ask the
Republicans, who included one of the leaders of the House
impeachment of the president, whether they support his gun-control
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The former impeachment manager, Rep. Jim Rogan, R-Calif., did
not speak at the East Room event. Rogan faces a tough re-election
fight in a changing district, and is considered the most vulnerable
of the 13 House members who outlined the case against Clinton to
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the NRA was
''harassing'' House members over today's planned vote, threatening
to count it as part of the NRA's rating system for lawmakers. Many
lawmakers prize their favorable ratings from the NRA, which is one
of Washington's richest and most powerful lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know how the NRA works. There's no denying the tactics
they use,'' Lockhart said today.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know how this White House works,'' NRA Executive Vice
President Wayne LaPierre said later. ''They try to demonize, they
attack those challenging them and they try to focus on anything
except what they are vulnerable on, and what they are vulnerable on
here is the complete collapse of enforcement of existing federal
gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, the NRA accuses the Clinton administration of
pressing for unnecessary gun control while failing to enforce laws
already on the books.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does a criminal have to fear from these guys?'' LaPierre
asked today. ''Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has challenged Congress to pass what he calls
''commonsense gun control'' before the April 20 anniversary of the
Columbine High School shootings in Colorado, although his plan
languished in Congress last year.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to impose background checks on sales at gun shows that
could take as long as 72 hours. Many congressional Republicans, and
the NRA, want any such checks to be instant or at least require no
longer than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''In all candor, I think taking a little time and a little
inconvenience to save a lot of lives is a good deal for America,''
Clinton said today.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants trigger locks to be required on new guns and
a ban on the import of large-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
