<HEADLINE> House GOP Looks At Russia Policies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accusing the Clinton administration of failed
policies towards Russia, House Republicans organized a task force
Wednesday aimed at solving security, law-enforcement and economic
problems with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the all-GOP group is Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., who
once ran a company that translated Pravda into English and in 1991
gave a speech in Russian to several hundred Soviet sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Cold War might be over, but Russia is still up to its old
tricks,'' Cox said at a news conference at which House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., announced the task force. Cox chairs the
House GOP Policy Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the continuing importance of Russia and U.S.-Russian
relations, the situation in Russia continues to deteriorate,''
Hastert said, ''even as Russia's proliferation efforts increase,
particularly to Iran, and its bloody war in Chechnya continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who was in Moscow last month, said
Russians appear willing to give up some of their freedoms to
maintain order, and acting president Vladimir Putin ''is probably
the perfect candidate'' to rule with an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot we don't know about Mr. Putin,'' said Goss,
House intelligence committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The task force includes Republican committee and subcommittee
chairmen who deal with economic, military and social issues
affecting U.S. relations with Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
