<HEADLINE> Judge faults inmate's lengthy solitary confinement, but reducesaward  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A drug-gang gunman who killed a New York
City policeman in 1988 had a $660,000 jury award reduced to
$237,500 for being locked up in solitary confinement for more than
four years.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Jonathan Feldman upheld a federal jury's finding
in February 1999 that inmate David McClary's civil rights were
violated by prison officials who kept him confined to a bare cell
for 23 hours a day from Nov. 20, 1989, to March 11, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   McClary, 34, is serving 25 years to life in prison for executing
a rookie police officer in the New York borough of Queens in
February 1988. Officer Edward Byrne was shot as he sat in a patrol
car guarding the home of a witness in a drug case.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling that the jury's damages for mental anguish were
excessive, the judge reduced them to the amount McClary originally
sought in a lawsuit against four prison officials. That translates
to nearly $120 for each of the 1,573 days he spent in solitary
confinement, plus $50,000 for emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Evaluating excessiveness in the context of an individual
spending four uninterrupted years in solitary confinement is no
easy task,'' Feldman said in a 36-page decision this week. Being
sentenced to isolation, he added, ''was potentially limitless, a
fact that exacerbated the damages he suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No punishment would be too great for him, therefore he doesn't
deserve any kind of judgment,'' Patrick J. Lynch, president of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, said through an aide Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials claimed that the notoriety of his crime made it
too risky to put McClary in the general prison population.
</P>
<P>
   McClary had refused to testify against Howard ''Pappy'' Mason, a
suspected drug kingpin charged with ordering the execution. Mason
was convicted in 1989 of racketeering charges for his role in the
officer's slaying, which set in motion a decade-long war on crack
cocaine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   McClary's time in solitary -- known as administrative segregation
-- was split between Attica, Southport prison in Elmira and Wende
prison in Alden, near Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The jury had found a prison official at Attica liable for
$10,000 in damages. But for the three years McClary spent in
solitary in Wende, $650,000 in damages were awarded against former
state prisons Commissioner Thomas A. Coughlin III and two officials
who worked at Wende.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said McClary has until March 24 to accept the new
amount of damages awarded or seek a new trial. McClary is
imprisoned at Shawangunk prison near New York, and his first parole
hearing is 13 years away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 1401 </TRAILER>
