<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaiser Aluminum Faces Fines  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN SAYRE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A federal safety agency on Wednesday proposed
that Kaiser Aluminum Corp. pay fines of $533,000 for an explosion
last year at its Gramercy, La., plant that injured 29 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration cited
Kaiser for 23 violations of safety regulations. The agency said the
explosion resulted from a faulty pressure relief system in several
large tanks and blamed on the plant's management.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also accused Kaiser of interfering with its
investigation into the July 5 explosion, which largely destroyed
the plant and also damaged homes and cars in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, which earlier denied all of the allegations and appealed
the citations, said Wednesday it will appeal the proposed fines as
well to the Federal Safety and Health Review Commission. If the
company loses on the administrative level, it can appeal to federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in a statement that although the fines were
only half of the maximum amount, the proposal was ''nonetheless
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant refined bauxite ore using a caustic solution to
produce alumina, which is the principal ingredient in aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, Kaiser announced it would spend $198 million to
rebuild and upgrade the plant, which is expected to be in full
operation during the first quarter of 2001. Kaiser said the rebuilt
plant would produce alumina more efficiently and cut air pollution
by 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The citations will have no bearing on the company's plan to
rebuild the plant, Kaiser said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the explosion, temporary workers were staffing
the plant. The United Steelworkers of America has been on strike
against Kaiser since Sept. 30, 1998. The company locked out union
members in January 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
