<HEADLINE> Blue Chip Stocks Rise Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks rose sharply today as investors
moved some of the money that has streamed out of the technology
sector this week back into long-forgotten industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 250.75 at 10,061.99.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 70.37 at 4,636.26, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 26.39 at 1,385.54.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip Dow, which has dramatically underperformed the
Nasdaq so far this year, rose today on the strength of old-line
industrial companies like DuPont, up 3 3/16 to 51, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, up 4\ to 76 13/16 and 3M, up 3[ to 82\.
</P>
<P>
   ''So much damage has already been done in these old economy
stocks,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP;
Co. ''We're finally seeing money coming into some of the bargain
stocks that have been created by the selling pressure of the past
few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip technology shares were mixed. Intel rose 4 15/16 to
122 13/16, but Hewlett-Packard fell 7 11/16 to 132 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech companies that dominate the Nasdaq were mostly
lower today, compounding the index's 341-point loss in the past two
sessions. Yahoo! was off 7 3/16 to 161 9/16 today and PMC-Sierra
fell 21| to 196].
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in those shares, which have been among the market's top
performers in 2000, suggested investors are taking profits from
their sharp gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq has been on a rocket ship, and I think investors
will work a bit harder to bring it down before it can start moving
higher again,'' Hogan said. ''The Nasdaq is in the midst of a
corrective process, which is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies, which led the market's decline on
Tuesday after the United States and Britain agreed to share data on
genetics, regained some ground today. Human Genome Sciences rose 2
31/64 to 126.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle rose 3[ to 80[. The company, a leading maker of business
software, said after the close of trading Tuesday that
third-quarter profits soared 160 percent, easily surpassing
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the market's continued volatility suggested that
investors were reluctant to take major new positions in the days
ahead of the government's reports on the Producer Price Index and
the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The PPI, due for release Thursday, and the CPI, due out Friday,
are closely watched gauges of inflationary pressures. The Federal
Reserve is expected to take both reports under consideration when
it meets next Tuesday to discuss interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Many on Wall Street expect the Fed to raise rates. An increase
would be the fifth since last June, when the Fed began trying to
engineer a gradual slowdown in the economy to prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Keller, chairman of the investment policy committee at A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, said he expects rising interest rates
to eventually take a toll on technology stocks, which have held up
far better than the broad market in the months since the Fed began
raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns prompted Keller to cut back on the firm's
exposure to stocks. Today, A.G. Edwards shifted its asset
allocation model to include 55 percent stocks, 35 percent bonds and
10 percent cash. Previously, the firm recommended 60 percent
stocks, 35 percent bonds and 5 percent cash.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 814.71 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 10.53 to
562.46.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
