<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Want Colleagues' Votes  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reps. Billy Tauzin and Mike Oxley each have
organized seven-figure fund-raising dinners, but the proceeds won't
be going to their re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the two Republicans are collecting money for colleagues
in hopes of retaining GOP control of Congress and solidifying
friendships in their quest to succeed retiring Rep. Thomas Bliley,
R-Va., as chairman of the powerful House Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to self-imposed six-year term limits for committee
chairmen, GOP lawmakers are jockeying to position themselves for
plum assignments that would become available next year if the GOP
remains in charge of the House.
</P>
<P>
   It's a race nearly as intense as the fight between Republicans
and Democrats for control of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like the bidding war is off and running,'' said Larry
Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics,
a nonpartisan research group that studies money and campaigns.
''Their dollars are probably the things that will propel one of
these two guys into the chairmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, a Democratic convert from Louisiana, and Ohio's Oxley
are sharing funds from their campaign bank accounts, raising money
for others through leadership political action committees they
formed and hosting dinners for the National Republican
Congressional Committee, the House GOP's fund-raising arm.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley chaired a first-ever $10,000-a-plate event in New York
City last January that brought in $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin takes his turn Thursday as organizer of the House GOP's
annual dinner in Washington, which is expected to raise a record
$5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's part of the drill,'' Oxley said of the fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce post is one of Congress' plum assignments. The
committee handles legislation for industries that touch ever facet
of Americans' lives from telephones, cable TV and the Internet to
airlines and drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Other soon-to-be vacant chairmanships also have spawned hot
races. Rep. Philip Crane of Illinois is battling House
Administration Committee chairman Bill Thomas of California to head
the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee. The current chairman,
Bill Archer of Texas, is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Other battles are likely for control of the International
Relations, Armed Services, and Banking and Financial Services
committees, whose chairmen must leave their positions in 2001
because of term limits imposed by House Republicans in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley and Tauzin provide a glimpse into how the battles are
waged.
</P>
<P>
   Through Dec. 31, Oxley had doled out $107,887 from his campaign
committee and leadership PAC to colleagues, while Tauzin
contributed $79,889.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Oxley was the featured guest at a
$1,000-per-person dinner for Rep. Paul Ryan of Wisconsin. And next
month, he headlines a fund-raiser for Rep. Greg Walden of Oregon at
the Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young concert in downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Tauzin is cooking up a ''cajun luncheon''
next week for Rep. Fred Upton of Michigan and staging a ''cajun
cookout'' for Rep. Anne Northup of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley, chairman of the Commerce Committee's finance and
hazardous materials subcommittee, played a key role in passing
legislation that broke down the Depression-era barriers against
banks, insurance companies and investment firms competing against
each other.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted one of the leading industry advocates of the bill,
Merrill Lynch chairman David Komansky, to co-chair the January
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, it helps to have a relationship with many of the
CEOs of some of the major financial companies in the country,''
Oxley said.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin also leads an important subcommittee --
Telecommunications, Trade and Consumer Protection -- which is
overseeing the deregulation of the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   He also has enlisted industries regulated by his committee:
Lodwrick Cook, co-chairman of the telecommunications company Global
Crossing Ltd., has a major role at Thursday's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Both lawmakers stress, however, their first task is to keep
Democrats from winning back the House. Otherwise, Rep. John
Dingell, the senior Democrat on the committee, will be presiding in
the chairman's seat next January.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm focused on one thing when it comes to fund raising,''
Tauzin said. ''I'll be saluting John Dingell if we're not going to
be in the majority. We'll worry about chairmanships later.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee: www.house.gov/commerce
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Oxley: www.house.gov/oxley
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin: www.house/gov.tauzin
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
