<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, March 15, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blue Chip Stocks Rise Sharply
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks rose sharply today as investors
moved some of the money that has streamed out of the technology
sector this week back into long-forgotten industrial stocks. The
Dow rose today on the strength of industrial companies like DuPont,
up 3 3/16 to 51, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, up 4\ to 76 13/16 and 3M, up 3[
to 82\. Blue-chip technology shares were mixed. Intel rose 4 15/16
to 122 13/16, but Hewlett-Packard fell 7 11/16 to 132 5/16. The
high-tech companies that dominate the Nasdaq were mostly lower
today. Yahoo! was off 7 3/16 to 161 9/16 and PMC-Sierra fell 21| to
196]. Biotechnology companies regained some ground. Human Genome
Sciences rose 2 31/64 to 126.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   New York (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
Dow Industrials:        10084.87 + 273.63
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1713  Declines 1240  Unchgd  469
NYSE Volume:         904,644,790
Most Active NYSE issue:         Compaq Computer 30]   +   ~  
S&AMP;P 500:         1389.53 + 30.38
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          998.11 - 17.40
NASDAQ Composite Index:       4636.51 - 70.12
Gold(final) -    $289.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Halts BP Amoco-Arco Merger Suit
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission said today it is
putting on hold legal action to block the merger of BP Amoco PLC
and Atlantic Richfield Corp., and planned to resume negotiations on
the $30 billion consolidation. The merged companies would become
second only to Exxon Mobil among the world's largest nongovernment
oil companies. Shares of both companies were up in afternoon
trading today on the New York Stock Exchange, Arco was up 3~ to
82~, while U.S. shares of BP Amoco were up 1 5/16 cents to 52.7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Aluminum Faces Fines
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- A federal safety agency today proposed that
Kaiser Aluminum Corp. pay fines of $533,000 for an explosion last
year at its Gramercy, La., plant that injured 29 workers. Earlier,
the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration cited Kaiser for 23
violations of safety regulations. The agency said the explosion
resulted from a faulty pressure relief system in several large
tanks and blamed on the plant's management. The agency also accused
Kaiser of interfering with its investigation into the July 5
explosion. Kaiser said it will appeal the proposed fines.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation Bill Goes To President
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking toward the rapid expansion of air
travel, the House today approved and sent to the president
legislation that would significantly increase spending on airport
safety and modernization. It also could mean higher taxes on
tickets. The bill, strongly supported by the administration,
authorizes spending of $40 billion over the next three years for
airport improvements and Federal Aviation Administration
operations. Available funds in fiscal 2001 would be $12.7 billion,
up $2.7 billion over this year.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills' Earnings Rise 9 Pct.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN VALLEY, Minn. (AP) -- Strong sales of yogurt and Hamburger
Helper mixes coupled with demand for Chex cereals used to make
snack mixes over the holidays helped boost General Mills'
third-quarter earnings nearly 9 percent. General Mills said today
that profits rose to $153.3 million, or 50 cents a share, in the
three months ended Feb. 28, compared with $141.1 million, or 45
cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. The performance matched
expectations of analysts. General Mills shares were up 1[ to 31} in
afternoon trading on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   Federal-Mogul To Close Warehouses
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- Federal-Mogul Corp. said today it will
close 25 North American facilities and cut 1,500 jobs in an effort
to improve the auto parts company's bottom line. In addition to
shutting 23 warehouses and two factories, the company plans to make
changes at 19 other facilities in North and South America and
consolidate 18 manufacturing and distribution operations in Europe
and Asia. Federal-Mogul has not yet decided whether those changes
would involve closing or downsizing plants or moving product lines.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Deficit at All-Time High
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's deficit in the broadest measure of
trade surged to an all-time high of $338.9 billion last year, more
than $100 billion higher than the deficit for 1998. The Commerce
Department said today that the deficit in the current account,
which measures not only trade in goods and services but also
investment flows and foreign aid payments, was up 53.7 percent from
the previous record, a $220.6 billion imbalance in 1998. The huge,
$118.4 billion deterioration in the current-account deficit
demonstrates dramatically that the one blot on an otherwise
remarkable U.S. economic performance is in trade.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Production Rises
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Industrial production at the nation's
factories, utilities and mines rose at a slower-than-expected pace
in February as the output of cars, carpeting and appliances fell
after posting strong gains the month before. The Federal Reserve
reported today that production increased by 0.3 percent last month,
weaker than the 0.5 percent gain many analysts were forecasting.
That followed a big 1.1 percent leap in production in January.
Operating capacity was 81.7 percent in February, the same as the
month before and slightly less than some analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   BMW May Dump Troubled Rover Brand
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Union leaders from BMW's money-losing
Rover division flew to Germany today amid reports that the Bavarian
automaker was on the brink of selling the troubled British venture,
jeopardizing thousands of jobs. Its shares soared in anticipation
of a sale. BMW's supervisory board meets tomorrow to consider
whether to sell Rover's passenger car branch, move it out of
Britain or close it altogether. News of a potential sale of the
division was also greeted eagerly by investors today, who pushed
BMW stock up 11.3 percent to the equivalent of $29.49 a share in
Frankfurt trading.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Leader Optimistic on Economy
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy remains on track to grow for the
first time in three years, Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said today
in a show of optimism despite recent data indicating the world's
second largest economy has slipped back into recession. Obuchi told
reporters today that recent gloomy economic data concealed several
bright spots, including positive trends in industrial production.
He insisted that Japan's economy will grow in the fiscal year
ending March 31, although he said it will be ''difficult'' to
achieve his government's 0.6 percent target for expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Nasdaq To Start in June
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's version of the Nasdaq Stock Market will
open June 30 with limited hours and local rules, organizers said
today, promising that a 24-hour schedule and trading of foreign
stocks will come within a year. Though its backers have touted
Nasdaq Japan as a step toward a global trading network, Nasdaq and
Japan's Osaka Stock Exchange said Wednesday they planned to start
with the same hours and trading systems as the Osaka market. Shares
will trade from 9 a.m. to 11 a.m. in the morning and from 12:30
p.m. to 3:10 p.m. in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ford To Offer Web-Ready Car Phones
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. and Sprint PCS Corp. plan to offer
mobile phones with Internet access in most Ford vehicles, beginning
with select 2001 Lincoln models due on the market in September.
Ford said today the deal provides the first factory-installed
mobile phone that can be removed from a vehicle and used as a
regular wireless phone. Sprint's wireless network will provide
service for the new Ford Rescu system, a safety and concierge
service similar to General Motors Corp.'s OnStar.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Business inventories: up 0.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production: up 0.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Jobless claims
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Housing starts
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Producer price index
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Consumer price index
</P>
<P>
   AP Financial NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN
</P>
