<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France To Crack Down on Laundering  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's ministers pledged Wednesday to crack down
on international money laundering as they adopted a sweeping new
bill aimed at tightening economic regulation.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill is passed in parliament, the government would win
new powers to oversee, and in some circumstances block, financial
transactions between France and problematic offshore tax havens.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also outlines tougher punishments for money
launderers, and would allow the government to shut down
unregistered shell companies in France.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou told reporters the government
should ''show an example'' in fighting money laundering. France is
currently seeking support among fellow members of the Group of
Seven leading industrial nations for tougher steps to curb
international money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The measures are part of broader legislation also designed to
tighten stock market rules, improve corporate governance and stamp
out unfair pricing in France's retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   Government ministers said the bill draws on lessons learned
during the often bitter hostile takeover battles that shook
France's banking, energy and retail sectors last year. It also
endeavors to strengthen the powers of ordinary consumers and
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes measures designed to keep employees better
informed of takeover bids, to speed up the processing of hostile
takeover bids and to curb belligerent advertising campaigns mounted
by companies involved in stock market takeover battles.
</P>
<P>
   France's business leaders have criticized the bill, saying extra
legislation would stifle small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Christian Sautter said, ''We want to set out
the economic rules of the game, not to hold back small companies,
but to make sure there is space for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, if passed, also would oblige companies to make public
previously secret shareholder pacts and would strengthen the
regulatory powers of the stock market watchdog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
