<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critic of Census Angers Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Postal Service wants one of the Census
Bureau's biggest critics to stop sending out its latest series of
fund-raising letters, claiming it violates federal law covering
deceptive mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Postal Service Inspector Attorney Thomas Sottile, in a letter to
the Southeastern Legal Foundation, said the mailings had to stop
because the envelopes implied a connection to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   The words ''IMPORTANT 2000 CENSUS MATERIALS ENCLOSED'' and ''BUY
U.S. SAVINGS BONDS'' appear in bold letters above the address label
on the group's mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Atlanta-based nonprofit foundation asks recipients
to sign a petition requesting the Census Bureau not to use a
statistical method known as sampling when compiling data from the
upcoming count. It also asks for a donation.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Glavin, president of the foundation, said Wednesday that
he had not received Sottile's letter, but called it ''moot'' since
the 250,000 mailings are already out to households.
</P>
<P>
   The mailings were first criticized last month by Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, D-N.Y., ranking member of the House Government Reform
Committee's census panel, for looking too much like a real
government mailing at a time when census forms were arriving in
mailboxes. Maloney supports sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service said it had not received any consumer
complaints about the letter. Glavin said the foundation usually
does not send out the same type of fund-raising mailings twice
anyway, and called Maloney's opposition a partisan attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1526 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
