<HEADLINE> Rep. Vento Returns From Cancer  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, 
V0508-----
r w *1153AP-Vento-Returns     03-15 0457
*1153 AP-Vento-Returns,0456   
Rep. Vento Returns From Cancer   
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Bruce Vento returned to Congress only a
month after having a lung removed because of cancer and said
Wednesday the welcome he received from colleagues was gratifying
but painful.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should have had a badge that said, 'No hugs, just kisses,'''
Vento joked, still smarting from a sore back after surgery. ''But
getting around that minor inconvenience of pain, it was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Vento, 59, announced earlier this year that he had malignant
mesothelioma, a rare form of cancer usually linked to asbestos
exposure. The Democrat from St. Paul, Minn., said he would not seek
re-election after 24 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Looking fit, Vento met with reporters in his office, which is
adorned with photos of national parks -- one of his passions -- and a
pennant of the 1987 World Series champion Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Vento said sharing the illness with the public has its
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hurts sometimes to be so transparent,'' he said. ''Most of
us, when you have a serious illness, you don't necessarily want to
lay it all out in front of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But the public outpouring -- Vento has received thousands of
cards, letters and phone calls of support -- has been encouraging.
''On balance, it's very helpful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vento said one of his remaining priorities is passage of
legislation that would make it easier for certain Hmong immigrants
-- a Laotian ethnic group -- to become U.S. citizens. The bill, which
Vento first introduced 10 years ago, would waive the English
language requirement for Hmong who were recruited by the CIA to
fight during the Vietnam War. Minnesota is home to an estimated
60,000 Hmong, about one-fifth of the 300,000 living in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for passage improved last month when Minnesota Gov.
Jesse Ventura lobbied House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., who promised his support. On Tuesday, Hyde said he
would name the bill after Vento.
</P>
<P>
   Vento, the father of three adult sons, said he would like to
continue public service after Congress and would prefer to work on
national park issues.
</P>
<P>
   He walks each day and plans to start biking again soon. Next
month, he will start chemotherapy and possibly radiation. He said
doctors have told him he has a 50 percent chance of living five or
more years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a pretty pragmatic sort of guy, a realist, I guess,'' he
said. ''We all know we're going to die, we just don't what's going
to get us. ... I've got parents that are in their 80s, and I
figured I've got 20 more years. But whether or not I get that now,
I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
