<HEADLINE> Spielberg To Take On Kubrick Film  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Steven Spielberg plans to pick up where the
late director Stanley Kubrick left off.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. announced Tuesday that Spielberg will write and
direct ''A.I.,'' an epic science fiction tale that Kubrick had been
planning before his death last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stanley had a vision for this project that was evolving over
18 years,'' Spielberg said in a written statement. ''I am intent on
bringing to the screen as much of that vision as possible, along
with elements of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg released no details about the plot. He and Kubrick had
been friends and Spielberg discussed the project extensively with
Kubrick, whose final film was last summer's ''Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A.I.,'' which is an acronym for ''artificial intelligence,''
is scheduled to start production in July. It wasn't clear how much
of the story Kubrick had assembled before he died on March 7, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
