<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Clamps Down on Radio  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) -- The government closed Liberia's two
leading independent radio stations Wednesday, saying they posed a
security threat to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss-funded Star Radio was shut down and its Internet service
disbanded, while broadcasts by Roman Catholic-run Radio Veritas
were suspended until its management agrees in writing to limit
itself to religious broadcasts, the government announced in a radio
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The government denied the move amounted to an attack on press
freedom, saying it took the action to prevent the country from
being destabilized by ''agents.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This trend is a design by detractors to open old wounds by
raising issues which threaten to reverse progress made in the
reconciliation efforts and to plunge the country back into civil
war,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia had a brutal civil war from 1989-1996, and President
Charles Taylor headed one of the most powerful factions. Since
being elected president in 1997, Taylor has frequently come under
fire from pro-democracy and human rights groups, which charge him
with heavy-handed tactics against his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Star Radio and Veritas, considered the country's most credible
and independent radio stations, frequently host phone-in shows
where callers sometimes express views critical of Taylor and his
government.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Veritas program, Catholic Archbishop Michael Francis
described Taylor as a demigod who could be criticized only at the
risk of being charged with sedition.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time Star Radio has had a run-in with the
Taylor regime. In 1998, Taylor temporarily banned it from
operation, saying it had been assigned its frequencies without
authorization. The government has also refused to grant it a
short-wave frequency.
</P>
<P>
   The stations' directors did not comment Wednesday, a public
holiday. But the main journalist association, the Press Union of
Liberia, denounced the move.
</P>
<P>
   ''Press freedom has come under vehement attack. The government's
action is outrageous, most unfortunate and disturbing,'' the union
said in a statement. Officials said they had called an urgent
meeting to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heavily armed police troops surrounded Star Radio's
offices and were preventing journalists from entering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1554 </TRAILER>
