<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USAID To Fly Aid to Ethiopia  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GODE, Ethiopia (AP) -- The U.S. Agency for International
Development plans to fly tons of emergency food aid into
southeastern Ethiopia after learning that 53 children under the age
of 5 died in this town last week, a senior agency official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths were just one symptom of a growing food shortage in
this region where drought has created a near-desert, killed
thousands of the livestock that people rely on for food and income
and left millions of people at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a crisis, and we have got to act fast to make sure more
people don't die,'' said Hugh Parmer, the agency's assistant
administrator. ''What really moved me to take action is hearing of
all those children dying. We have got to do something about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parmer is on a two-week tour of Ethiopia, Eritrea, Somalia,
Djibouti and Kenya to assess the needs of some 15 million people
threatened by food shortages. He told The Associated Press that
conditions are critical in the region. He said he wanted an air
drop of food to take place in the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Parmer visited a feeding center in Gode, 360 miles
southeast of the capital, Addis Ababa. There, 90 severely
malnourished children under age 5 are being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Regional authorities told him eight children had died in the
center since it opened two weeks ago. Another 45 died in camps set
up for the growing number of hungry, desperate people streaming
into town.
</P>
<P>
   Adan Mohammed said she spent 10 days walking 60 miles to the
center with her three children in hopes of receiving food. The
family's 200 cattle and sheep died in the drought.
</P>
<P>
   But the trek proved too much for her four-year-old daughter and
one-year-old son. Both died shortly after reaching Gode four months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Protectively cradling the tiny twin of the dead one-year-old in
her arms, Adan she said she had not seen rain for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know anything any more,'' she said. ''I just have to
wait for something from God.''
</P>
<P>
   According to local officials, the twice-yearly seasonal rains
have failed for the last three years in the Gode area, turning the
land into a near-desert.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the 460,000 people in the area, where
temperatures regularly soar above 105 degrees, are nomadic herders.
Ibrahim Haji Abdi, chairman of the regional emergency task force,
said drought had killed more than 50 percent of their sheep and
cattle and 20 percent of their camels, leaving them starving and
helpless.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's never been this bad, not since 1984,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A catastrophic drought in Ethiopia in 1984-85 resulted in a
major famine, the first one whose effects were seen around the
world on television.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are two months from serious crisis if considerably more aid
doesn't arrive,'' said David Eckerson, USAID's director for
Ethiopia. The agency estimates that 7.7 million people have been
effected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1608 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Rebel Helpers in UN's Sights  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council should impose
sanctions on countries that have helped Angola rebels evade a U.N.
ban on weapons and fuel sales and diamond exports, the chairman of
the U.N. sanctions committee said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Ambassador Robert Fowler made the recommendation in
presenting a report by an independent panel that visited 30
countries over six months to determine how UNITA rebels were able
to circumvent the sanctions and restart their war.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the Security Council to adopt the panel's 39
recommendations to beef up implementation of the sanctions and
punish those who have violated them. Among the recommendations was
a call for a three-year arms embargo against countries that have
supplied UNITA with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report details how rebels bought weapons from
Eastern Europe, primarily Bulgaria, and had them shipped via
African countries in exchange for gems.
</P>
<P>
   UNITA rebels said the report was based on ''speculations and
falsehoods,'' according to a statement faxed to The Associated
Press in Lisbon, Portugal, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government and UNITA -- a Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola -- have been fighting
since Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council imposed an arms and fuel embargo on UNITA
in 1993, a year before the United Nations brokered a peace
agreement between the rebels and Angola's government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, six months before the peace agreement collapsed, the
council expanded the measures to include a ban on rebel diamond
exports, which are estimated to have supplied UNITA with up to $4
billion since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The report accuses President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso and
President Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo of having helped UNITA leader
Jonas Savimbi with arms and fuel shipments.
</P>
<P>
   It says Rwanda allowed UNITA officials to operate in the
capital, Kigali, and to conduct guns-for-gems transactions with
arms dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The report also accuses Belgium of having such lax standards at
its Antwerp diamond market that rogue dealers were able to trade
UNITA gems with virtually no obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Angola, Belgian Foreign Minister Louis Michel
said Wednesday that the report failed to include new measures
announced by the government March 4 to tighten controls at the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The panel chairman, Anders Mollander, however, said Belgium
failed to submit the information in time to be included.
</P>
<P>
   France's deputy U.N. ambassador, Yves Doutriaux, welcomed the
report but said it deserved ''careful scrutiny'' because of the
seriousness of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Togo, Burkina Faso, Rwanda and Bulgaria have denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Office minister Peter Hain praised the report's
willingness to expose violators ''who should be ashamed of the way
they are inflicting catastrophe on their fellow Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel called for those countries deemed to be in breach of
the sanctions to be barred from holding senior positions within the
United Nations or other international or regional organizations --
and from playing host to U.N. or international conferences.
</P>
<P>
   That recommendation could have implications for Togo, which is
scheduled to take up the chairmanship of the Organization of
African Unity and be the site of this summer's OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler acknowledged that the report's direct implication of
heads of state, highly unusual in a U.N. report, ''makes everyone
nervous because, frankly, 'it's not done.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that the OAU had already set a new standard for
''acceptable behavior'' by declaring in July that coup leaders
would not be welcome in its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.un.org
</P>
</TEXT>
