<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Chips Soar; Dow Rises 300  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average soared more
than 300 points today as investors moved money that has streamed
out of the technology sector this week into long-forgotten
industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Dow rose 320.17, or
by 3.3 percent, to close at 10,131.41. It was the fourth biggest
point gain ever for the Dow, but wasn't close to a record in
percentage terms. The blue-chip index rose as much as 368.41 points
before slipping back a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors continued shedding technology shares. The
Nasdaq composite index fell 123.94 to close at 4,582.64, bringing
its loss for the past three days to 465 points, or 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a rare day,'' said Vernon Winters, chief investment
officer at Mellon Private Asset Management. ''A lot of money
managers have been forced to sell blue-chips to buy technology
stocks, and today, they're reversing course.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip Dow, which has dramatically underperformed the
Nasdaq so far this year, rose today on the strength of old-line
industrial companies like DuPont, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, and 3M.
</P>
<P>
   ''So much damage has already been done in these old economy
stocks,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP;
Co. ''We're finally seeing money coming into some of the bargain
stocks that have been created by the selling pressure of the past
few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip technology shares were mixed. Intel rose, but
Hewlett-Packard fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Even with today's dramatic gains, the Dow remains down about 13
percent in the year to date, while the Nasdaq is up about 13
percent. Weakness in some of the Nasdaq's top performers suggested
that investors are taking profits from their sharp gains this year,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq has been on a rocket ship, and I think investors
will work a bit harder to bring it down before it can start moving
higher again,'' Hogan said. ''The Nasdaq is in the midst of a
corrective process, which is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   PMC-Sierra, which had risen 143 percent in the year to date,
fell steeply. Veritas, a developer of storage-management software
that was up about 75 percent this year, also dropped back.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies, which led the market's decline on
Tuesday after the United States and Britain agreed to share data on
genetics, regained some ground today. Human Genome Sciences rose.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle rose. The company, a leading maker of business software,
said after the close of trading Tuesday that third-quarter profits
soared 160 percent, easily surpassing analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the market's continued volatility suggested that
investors were nervous in the days ahead of the government's
reports on the Producer Price Index and the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The PPI, due for release Thursday, and the CPI, due out Friday,
are closely watched gauges of inflationary pressures. The Federal
Reserve is expected to take both reports under consideration when
it meets Tuesday to discuss interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Many on Wall Street expect the Fed to raise rates. An increase
would be the fifth since June, when the Fed began trying to
engineer a gradual slowdown in the economy to prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Keller, chairman of the investment policy committee at A.G.
Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, said he expects rising interest rates
to eventually take a toll on technology stocks, which have held up
far better than the broad market in the months since the Fed began
raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns prompted Keller to cut back on the firm's
exposure to stocks. Today, A.G. Edwards shifted its asset
allocation model to include 55 percent stocks, 35 percent bonds and
10 percent cash. Previously, the firm recommended 60 percent
stocks, 35 percent bonds and 5 percent cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1620 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State senator announces his candidacy for U.S. Senate  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ARLINGTON, N.J. (AP) -- State Sen. William Gormley made his
long-anticipated U.S. Senate campaign official Wednesday with a bus
tour across the state and promises to cut taxes and protect Social
Security and retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic County Republican, the fifth to enter the primary
and the only one from southern New Jersey, started his campaign at
a senior citizens' center in Margate. He then swung north to Bergen
County, where he appeared with county Executive William ''Pat''
Schuber, five local veterans and Nicholas Mazzolla.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, he's a breath of fresh air,'' said Mazzolla, a
Republican who offered his front lawn for Gormley's announcement.
He said he favored Gormley's proposal to cut taxes for middle-class
households with incomes of $125,000 or less and to eliminate the
marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzolla, a 45-year-old physical education teacher with three
teen-agers, called Gormley's ideas ''common sense,'' a theme echoed
in the senator's own speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said the Mazzollas represent many middle-class families
who can be forced to choose between caring for aging parents,
putting their children through college and enjoying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''They hope to be able to pay the bills, put away some savings
and, yes, have some money left over for two weeks at the Shore,''
Gormley said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he would vote to dedicate one-third of the
federal surplus to protect Social Security and Medicare and another
third of the surplus to paying off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will vote for tax cuts. I will vote to ensure that your
medical decisions are made by you and your doctor and not a
bureaucrat at an HMO. I'll see to it, as best I can, that your
retirement will be secure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley is the best-funded GOP contender for the seat to be
vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg, with more than $1.5 million
raised by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   His closest competitor, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, had raised half of
that amount. Essex County Executive James Treffinger had less than
$600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The other Republican candidates for the Senate seat being
vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg are former state Sen. Brian T.
Kennedy and Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates are Jon S. Corzine and former Gov. Jim
Florio. The primary is June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley had been preparing his campaign for months, but said he
waited to officially announce until the presidential primaries were
decided, saying that contest was taking much of the state's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley is in his sixth term in the Senate representing most of
Atlantic County, including Atlantic City. In Trenton he is a
champion of the casino industry, which has given generously to his
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, Gormley also
wields influence over the selection of judges, prosecutors and
other state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination for
governor in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg decided not to seek a fourth term. Gov. Christie
Whitman initially said she would run for the seat and then changed
her mind, opening the party contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 1625 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid to Ecuador Withheld in Protest  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A key congressman has ordered a suspension of
almost $20 million in U.S. assistance to Ecuador to protest what he
considers unjust treatment of a Florida man serving an eight-year
prison term there on a 1998 money laundering conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves James Williams of Jacksonville, who waited
more than two years for his trial and now has waited more than a
year for his appeal to be heard by the Ecuadorean Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on Foreign Operations, ordered the aid
suspension. As the lawmaker who oversees House foreign aid
appropriations, he has the authority to discontinue assistance
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''For some time, I have been very concerned about the slow pace
with which Ecuador has afforded an American citizen due process in
its judicial system,'' Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My hope would be that this matter can be resolved sooner
rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecuadorean Embassy officials did not respond to a request for
comment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials have raised the Williams case
repeatedly with high-level Ecuadorean officials to protest the
delays. The department describes Ecuador's judicial system as
''slow, inefficient and cumbersome.''
</P>
<P>
   According to department officials, the major impact of the aid
suspension will be on programs that directly support the poorest
Ecuadorians, including family planning and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years after his arrest in Ecuador, Williams was
indicted in Tampa on grounds that he was involved in a drug
trafficking and money laundering scheme allegedly run by Jose
Castrillon, a Colombian who is awaiting trial in Florida on drug
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Mitrani, Williams' lawyer, expressed hope that Ecuador
will release him shortly so he will have the chance ''to have all
of the facts presented to an unbiased tribunal in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other flaws in Williams' December 1998 trial, he was not
allowed to confront his accusers, Mitrani said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Corrine Brown, a Democrat who represents Williams in
Congress, said his case has been one of the most frustrating she
has encountered as an elected official.
</P>
<P>
   ''For three years I have been unsuccessful in my attempts to
seek a fair judicial proceeding for Mr. Williams, both in Ecuador
and in the United States. ... I am hopeful that someday, Mr.
Williams will receive the due process he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has visited Ecuador three times to assist Williams. Five
other lawmakers and former President Carter have gone to Ecuador
and raised the issue with government officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest in September 1996, Williams ran
Caribbean Fisheries. He bought fish from small packing houses in
Latin America and sold them to restaurant wholesalers in the
southeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' wife, Robin, said Wednesday in a telephone interview
from Jacksonville that Castrillon was one of his 22 suppliers. She
maintains that Castrillon's fishing business activities, in
contrast to his alleged drug dealing, were legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   She has maintained for years that her husband's arrest in
Ecuador was sought by the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, an
allegation denied by DEA officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Williams, who returned this week from her 15th visit to
Ecuador, said her husband's 3{-year incarceration has been a
''frightful situation'' that has led to their financial
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   She said she and other family members have to provide him with
clothing, money, food and toiletries because the prison ''provides
nothing for inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This prison is a death sentence,'' she said. ''Jim has watched
people die because they can't get out for treatment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0161 </DOCNO>
