<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fannie Mae Allots $2 Trillion  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fannie Mae is launching a 10-year, $2 trillion
campaign to finance home purchases by minorities, women, new
immigrants and other underserved segments of American society.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae Chairman Franklin D. Raines said at a news conference
Wednesday the goal of issuing $2 trillion in home loans is an
essential step to narrow the persistent gap in home ownership rates
between whites and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many Americans have enjoyed substantial financial gains in our
current era of prosperity. But in homeownership, there remains a
significant divide between the haves and the haven't yets,'' Raines
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, formally the Federal National Mortgage Association,
is a government-chartered corporation that receives tax benefits in
return for supplying a steady stream of mortgage capital funding
for middle and low-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Raines said Fannie Mae next month will meet a similar $1
trillion goal issued in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That challenge, issued by then-Fannie Mae head James Johnson, is
being achieved eight months ahead of schedule. Raines said that in
1994, 55% percent of Fannie Mae's business was with the targeted
underserved populations.
</P>
<P>
   That figure has grown to 68 percent of Fannie Mae's business
today and Raines said he expects further increases as the new goal
is pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fannie Mae is a mission driven company,'' Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, however, is also a profits driven company that is
publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange. And in the past
year, the news from Wall Street hasn't been good.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of 1999, the stock has tumbled from the mid
$70's to around $55 per share today. But Raines said he will tell
shareholders that serving minorities, women and immigrants makes
good business sense as it helps fulfill the company's social
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tremendous opportunities exist in these markets,'' Raines
said. ''This is not about charity.''
</P>
<P>
   While the targeted populations Fannie Mae is seeking out have
higher loan default rates than Americans as a whole, Raines said an
automated underwriting system that screens applicant's credit
worthiness will help ensure only those who can afford home loans
will get them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't think we have to make a choice between making bad
loans and racking up numbers,'' Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   Raines said more than 10 million families in the targeted groups
have received home loans since 1994. Fannie Mae is now serving 31
percent more black customers and 26 percent more Hispanic customers
than it did seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, just 45 percent of blacks and 44 percent of Hispanics
own their own homes compared to 75 percent of whites nationally.
</P>
<P>
   With the surging national economy and rising property values,
the issue of home ownership and how to make it easier for Americans
locked out of the home buying market has been a top issue for
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the House Banking Committee approved ''The American
Homeownership and Economic Opportunity Act of 2000'' to lower the
required FHA mortgage down payment for teachers, police officers
and other uniformed municipal workers buying their first homes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to be voted on later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae: www.fanniemae.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
