<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislative majorities put forward their spending plans  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The majorities in each chamber of the state
Legislature on Wednesday advanced their spending plans for the
2000-01 fiscal year as the sparring began over the competing
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who dominate the Assembly unveiled a proposal they
said would cost $78.2 billion or about $1.3 billion more than
Republican Gov. George Pataki's spending plan. The Republican-led
Senate said the budget resolution it approved Wednesday totals
about $500 million more than the governor's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Though an $800 million difference between the Assembly and
Senate sounds huge, the two sides were perhaps $3 billion or more
apart in negotiations over the current state budget at this time
last year. Silver said Wednesday the Assembly spending levels are
in the ''ballpark'' with the other proposals this time around.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver also began the rhetorical sparring that typically
accompanies the approach of negotiations over a new budget. The
state's 2000-01 fiscal year begins on April 1 and the state has not
had a new budget in place on time since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Silver questioned how Senate Republicans could propose a series
of ambitious tax cuts and spending plans, and then only figure that
their resolution would cost a half a billion dollars more than
Pataki's.
</P>
<P>
   ''They spending so much and so much and so much, but they're
only spending $400 million more (than Pataki),'' Silver said. ''Or
is it $600 million more?''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said the Senate's resolution was ''smoke and
mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bruno had suggested that Silver was the one who
favors excessive spending as another legislative election
approaches this November. Bruno also criticized Silver for not
proposing deep-enough tax cuts to spur business.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bruno and Silver have said they want the differences
between the two chambers to be resolved in public conference
committees. It was unclear Wednesday when the first conference
committee would meet to resolve the first important question facing
the lawmakers -- how much money will be available to spend in the
2000-01 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   On some matters, the Senate Republican and Assembly Democratic
resolutions are on the same page, or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Each chamber has rejected Gov. George Pataki's proposal to
create a superagency encompassing some 40,000 employees currently
in the State Police, state Department of Correctional Services and
other law enforcement-related state agencies. Silver said the
Assembly did not ''see much'' in the way of cost-savings or
bureaucratic streamlining through the consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Each chamber also rejected a proposed increase in hunting and
fishing licenses and said the state should pay for the county
taxpayers' share -- to grow to $340 million -- of the new Family
Health Plus medical insurance program which goes into effect in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly and Senate put forward proposals on some programs
that are similar enough to suggest the two houses could fairly
easily work out differences.
</P>
<P>
   Both chambers' majorities, for instance, proposed expanding the
state's Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance Coverage program,
simplifying the rules and expanding the income eligibility
standards. Both favor raising the Earned Income Tax Credit, Tuition
Assistance Program awards and increasing revenue sharing and other
aid programs for localities.
</P>
<P>
   But the two chambers are further apart on cutting the state's
gasoline tax -- Silver wants a two-month suspension of the tax to
give motoring tourists a break this summer while Bruno wants to
rescind it permanently -- and the Senate also favors eliminating the
state's gross receipt tax on energy while the Assembly wants only
limited reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly plan does not provide for a hallmark of the
Senate's budget -- a proposed $2.5 billion road- and bridge-building
bond act -- while the Senate plan funds less than half the
Assembly's centerpiece ''LADDER'' program to pay for
pre-kindergarten programs and to reduce early grade class sizes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
