<HEADLINE> 'Sopranos' OK'd for Two More Years  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''The Sopranos'' will be singing for two more
years with its creator, David Chase, at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   HBO said Wednesday that the celebrated mobster series, midway in
its second 13-episode season on the cable network, will be back for
an additional 26 hours through the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   So will Chase, who will not hand off executive producing chores
in the series' fourth season, as had been an earlier plan.
</P>
<P>
   Starring James Gandolfini as New Jersey mob boss Tony Soprano,
the series has become a craze with viewers since it premiered in
January 1999. Last season it won four Emmys out of 16 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, it picked up three Screen Actors Guild
awards, while Chase won a Directors Guild of America award.
</P>
</TEXT>
