<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Probe examining pharmacies requesting drug switches  </HEADLINE>
phqjkb1jy2
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A Philadelphia federal prosecutor is
investigating whether drug companies are illegally pressuring
pharmacists and doctors to switch drug prescriptions in favor of
medication preferred by a patient's insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, drugmaker Schering-Plough Corp., of Madison,
N.J., and the nation's two largest pharmacy-benefits managers have
acknowledged receiving subpoenas seeking information about the
complex relationship between drugmakers, insurers, pharmacists and
the companies that manage drug plans.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed, and the companies involved -- which
include Merck-Medco Managed Care LLC and Rite Aid Corp.'s PCS
Health Systems -- say there have been no accusations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the practice of pharmacists recommending to doctors
that a prescription be changed to substitute a medication that is
preferred by the insurance plan. Pharmacists already regularly
suggest that doctors change prescriptions to switch to generic drug
brands.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal prosecutor in Philadelphia, Assistant U.S.
Attorney James G. Sheehan, said he was concerned with the millions
of dollars paid by drugmakers to prescription-drug plans and from
the plans to pharmacies to get preferential treatment for their
drugs. In one such program, a pharmacist gets several dollars to
ask a patient whether he is willing to switch medications and
several more dollars to seek authorization from the patient's
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you pay somebody to switch this patient this time, or to
switch everybody on this drug ... the likelihood that they will act
not in the best interest of the patient is significantly higher,''
Sheehan told The Philadelphia Inquirer in Wednesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and managers say drug switches, which became common in
the mid-1990s, do not compromise health and can help restrain
medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians, patients and pharmacists complain the switches
risk harm to patients, interfere with doctors' judgment and waste
time.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA reported 169 cases of ''adverse events'' in 1997 and
1998 due to drug switches. At least 10 cases resulted in
hospitalization; the remainder were substitutions to a different
medication that the doctor said did not work.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin D. Trichtinger of suburban Philadelphia said he or
his colleagues are asked at least once a day to authorize a drug
switch they believe would be harmful to a patient. He said two
recent cases involved patients with congestive heart failure who
were prescribed Coreg.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just didn't realize that there's a specific reason when
you go with Coreg,'' Trichtinger said. ''Actually, the likelihood
is that you'd probably kill them (if the drug was switched). I'm
not overstating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said some switches could amount to violations of federal
fraud or anti-kickback laws. He also is examining whether
drugmakers are complying with laws that require them to give
Medicaid and the Department of Veterans Affairs the same discounts
they give to private insurers and pharmacy-benefits managers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that there are situations in which physicians and
patients can benefit from neutral, objective information about
therapeutic alternatives,'' Sheehan said. ''But I think it's very
hard to get objective information when a pharmaceutical
manufacturer is paying for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 1703 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
