<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School district, parents reach settlement in abortion lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By JOANN LOVIGLIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A settlement has been reached in a lawsuit
filed by a suburban Philadelphia couple against a public school
guidance counselor they accused of advising their 17-year-old
daughter to get a secret abortion in New Jersey, lawyers for the
parents said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement agreement, which has been signed by both parties
and was accepted late Tuesday by the U.S. District Court in
Philadelphia, requires that the Hatboro-Horsham School District
issue and enforce regulations prohibiting school personnel from
advising or assisting any student in obtaining an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the regulation must specifically ban school
employees from advising students to cross state lines to avoid
Pennsylvania's parental consent requirement.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the American Center for Law and Justice, the Pat
Robertson-founded law firm representing plaintiffs Howard and Marie
Carter, said he was pleased with the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case was about stopping the school district from being in
the abortion referral business,'' said John Stepanovich, senior
counsel for the Virginia-based firm. ''We are confident that this
agreement will prevent future occurrences of the outrageous conduct
exhibited by school officials.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carters' lawsuit, filed in August, accused counselor William
Hickey of advising their daughter to get a secret abortion, telling
her it was the only option and helping her arrange and pay for the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Carter, then 16, became pregnant just before moving
from Murfreesboro, Tenn., to Hatboro, Bucks County, in January
1998. She learned of the pregnancy in April 1998, two months after
beginning classes at Hatboro-Horsham High School. She had the
abortion in May 1998 but told her parents about it a few weeks
later when confronted by Mrs. Carter, who found the teen's stained
clothing hidden in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   The Carters also accused the school district and Hickey of
violating Pennsylvania law, which requires girls under age 18 to
receive permission from a parent or guardian before having an
abortion. Hickey was accused of arranging for Stephanie to have an
abortion in Cherry Hill, N.J., where no parental consent is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing for us has always been making sure
this does not happen to another family in this district, and we
pray all school boards will adopt such a policy,'' the Carter
parents said in a joint statement. ''If even one girl is encouraged
to turn to her parents instead of a New Jersey abortion clinic --
and if even one baby lives because of this policy -- then it was
worth the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement agreement, the school district and
Hickey admitted no wrongdoing and the district will pay the Carters
$20,000 in damages. The court dismissed the lawsuit but will
continue to oversee the case to ensure that the terms of the
agreement are enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement may stifle the ability of counselors to counsel,
said Lisa Shelby, vice president for education and professional
development of Planned Parenthood Southern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ''It limits the ability of the child to get good, accurate info
that she or he may need in a crisis situation,'' she said. ''It's
one less trusted adult they can go to with knowledge and
information that may be critical to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hickey nor Hatboro-Horsham School District solicitor
Jack Duly returned calls seeking comment Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 1705 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
