<DOCNO> APW20000315.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Grim in Pakistan  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY GANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- More than 1,000 women were killed
last year in the name of honor in Pakistan, even if the
justification was as flimsy as a woman sitting next to a man who
was not a relative, a human rights report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of street children and child prostitutes has
increased in the last decade. Pakistanis grew poorer, and most
people remain illiterate. Half of all children didn't attend
school.
</P>
<P>
   The picture given by the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan was
one in which women, children, and religious and ethnic minorities
lived in dire circumstances through the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 people died each year in violence motivated by
religion or ethnicity, the report aid. Often the victims were women
suspected of breaking Islam's code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most frequent killers by far were brothers, followed by
husbands,'' the commission said in its annual report for 1999.
''More than 15 percent of the victims in (the eastern state of)
Punjab were minors.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent rights organization sharply criticized the
elected governments of the 1990s, and assailed the military
takeover last year.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Chairman Afrasiab Khattak said the panel had just one
message for the military government that seized power in October:
''Please restore democracy at the earliest.''
</P>
<P>
   The military ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, has rebuffed
international pressure to set a timeframe for a return to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the decade's end the fourth direct assumption of power by
the military looks resolved, like two of its predecessors, to stay
on until it has done its self-appointed cleansing tasks,'' the
report said. The army has ruled Pakistan for 25 years of its
52-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The rights commission criticized a new law giving the government
sweeping powers to detain corruption suspects for 90 days without
charging them or allowing them see a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf's adviser, Javed Jabbar, said the law was needed in a
country devastated by political corruption and a court system
unable to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately you have to weigh the human rights of 139.99
million people against the human rights of 50, 100 or 200 people
who are suspected to have misused their access to power or
credit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Pakistan ended the 1990s worse off than when the decade
began, the report said. Pakistanis are poorer, most people are
illiterate and half of all school-age children don't attend class.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fundamentalist activism targeted liberalism of all kinds,''
the report said. ''It rose in hateful denunciation of campaigners
for peace, for policies opposed to militarism and nuclearization
and for a more open and democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   This made women more vulnerable by opposing ''any assertion of
women's rights,'' the report said. ''It sanctified women's
subordination and battled in courts and legislatures -- often
successfully -- in support of customs like honor killing and the
parents' coercion of their daughters in the choice of their
spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least two cases last year, the Lahore High Court ruled
that killing for ''honor'' was not an offense. The military
government, however, has said it is.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't accept this concept of honor killings at all,''
Interior Minister Moinuddin Haider said recently. ''We won't have
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1709 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Settles Brain Cancer Suit  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The families of five former employees of BP Amoco
PLC who died of brain cancer after years working at one of its
research centers have moved to drop their lawsuits following
out-of-court settlements with the company.
</P>
<P>
   One case was dismissed Wednesday in Cook County Circuit Court
and four others are expected to be withdrawn next Tuesday after
being held over on procedural delays, attorneys for the families
said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements enable BP Amoco, which acknowledged last July
that the employees likely got brain cancer from their work at its
Naperville, Ill., research center, to avoid years of legal battles.
The company has now settled five of the six employee lawsuits
involving the most serious cases and is in negotiations to try to
settle the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But its legal problems from the mysterious ailments are far from
over. Company spokeswoman Vicki Kastory said there are still 16
lawsuits pending involving a total of 22 people affected by various
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just think it's the right thing to do to resolve these
issues so these families can begin to move forward,'' she said of
the settlements. The amounts were kept confidential under the
settlement agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The six Amoco employees in Naperville all developed glioma, a
rare malignant tumor. They worked during the same period in the
late 1970s and early 1980s at the center's Building 503. Five of
the six men worked on the third floor, which has since been closed
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Only one survives.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco has since been acquired by British Petroleum and is now
part of London-based BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   ''The settlements were fair amounts for all concerned,
considering all the circumstances,'' attorney Marios Karayannis
said Wednesday. His father, Nicholas Karayannis, died of a glioma.
''They provide an opportunity for closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Karayannis and other attorneys sought to have the five lawsuits
dismissed Wednesday. But while Circuit Judge Judith Cohen dismissed
the case involving the only living plaintiff -- Glen Hoff, now
seriously ill and living in Utah -- she held over the others because
of requirements under wrongful death lawsuits that would have
entailed the families learning of the other settlement amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on keeping the figures confidential, lawyers said they
will file new motions Tuesday to enable the cases to be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   California attorney Amanda Hess, who represents three of the
families, called the settlements ''bittersweet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If something good can come from this, it's much closer
scrutiny of the mixtures of chemicals that are used industrially,
which helps us understand the contributions to human cancer coming
from the workplace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Amoco announced the results of a three-year study
conducted by researchers from Johns Hopkins University and the
University of Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did find a consistent pattern that indicated the glioma
may be work-related,'' said Kastory.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we still don't have specific, conclusive answers about
what specifically caused the cancer, there is a consistent
pattern,'' she said. ''Our philosophy from the beginning has been
to address these concerns, and it's only the right thing to resolve
these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a special task force set up at the Naperville center
remains intact and the company continues to monitor the health of
people who work there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
