<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Peace Accord Shaky  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's feared former rebel
leader refused on Wednesday to recommit to the provisions of a
shaky peace accord that officially ended eight years of bloody
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament summoned Foday Sankoh to request that his rebel
Revolutionary United Front would rapidly disarm and demobilize, as
well as open up rebel-held territory to civilian government and
U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''No action is being taken by your fighters to disarm,'' said
Elizabeth Lavali, a representative of the majority Sierra Leone
People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh declined to commit to the seven-point resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am committed to the disarmament process, which I agree is
slow. But Foday Sankoh alone is not responsible for its slowness,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside parliament about 500 front supporters sang, danced and
beat drums throughout the three-hour session.
</P>
<P>
   The front, which was brought into a power-sharing government
last year after signing the peace deal, controls much of Sierra
Leone's eastern region.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh has promised to give the U.N.'s 6,000 peacekeepers
freedom of movement in the West African nation, but his soldiers
have continued to block their advance into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   Few rebels have handed in their weapons, as required by the July
accord. Cease-fire violations remain commonplace, and U.N.
officials have reported rebels looting villages, burning houses,
raping women and mutilating civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The front's rebels killed tens of thousands and cut off the
arms, legs, ears and lips of many more in a bid to gain power
through fear during Sierra Leone's civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
