<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan: He's the True Reformer  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush and Al Gore can't fix the
political system because their parties are in ''unholy matrimony
with special interests,'' according to Pat Buchanan, the latest
presidential candidate to claim he is the race's true reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Neither Beltway party is going to drain this swamp, because to
them it is not a swamp at all, but a protected wetland and their
natural habitat. They swim in it, feed in it, spawn in it,''
Buchanan says in remarks prepared for delivery Thursday in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time Republican presidential candidate is seeking the
Reform Party nomination. Buchanan, a former aide to President
Nixon, ranks well behind the presumptive major-party nominees --
Democrat Gore and Republican Bush -- in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   His speech comes amid a frenzy of activity by both Gore and Bush
to portray themselves as political reformers; the
nominees-in-waiting hope to attract voters who flocked to GOP
primaries in support of failed Republican candidate John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the fray, Buchanan said as president he would seek to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ban unlimited, unregulated donations from corporations or
unions. Bush has made a similar proposal. Gore, like McCain, says
he would extend the ban to individual ''soft money'' contributions.
</P>
<P>
   -- Require congressmen to raise half of their donations from
their home states or districts.
</P>
<P>
   -- Increase the limit on individual contributions to candidates
from $1,000 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pass a law giving states the power to impose congressional
term limits and restrict the Supreme Court's right to reverse the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   -- End the congressional pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make it easier for third-party candidates to get on ballots.
</P>
<P>
   -- Allow people to register and vote on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush, Gore, McCain and failed Democratic candidate Bill
Bradley are all guilty of fund-raising excesses.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to fund-raising calls Gore made from the White House
in 1996, Buchanan said, ''Where was his conscience? Where was his
sense of respect for the White House?''
</P>
<P>
   He accused Bush of shying away from campaign finance reform out
of fear that changes would hurt the GOP. ''The true test of who is
a reformer is results,'' Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said. On
education and health care, ''Governor Bush has taken on the special
interests'' in Texas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said that if Gore is part of a
Washington swamp Buchanan ''is the candidate of the dark lagoon:
Anti-choice, anti-gun reform, anti-mainstream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1718 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY's GOP governor makes major gun control proposals  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Amid congratulations for taking a stand that
puts him at odds with some members of his party, Republican Gov.
George Pataki said Wednesday he wants New York to lead the way in
creating the equivalent of a DNA database for handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's ballistics fingerprinting proposal would require
dealers and gun manufacturers to send to a state lab a test bullet
and shell casing from every handgun they sell within the state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also proposed requiring safety locks to be sold with
every gun; raising the age for handgun ownership from 18 to 21;
banning the sale of assault weapons, and requiring instant
background checks to be made of gun buyers at flea markets and gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''These proposals are just a common-sense approach,'' Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I greatly applaud the governor's courage in reaching out
across the divide in his own party and in saying to them, 'We need
support for gun control effort,'' said Richard Aborn, a member of
New Yorkers Against Gun Violence. ''This takes New York a major
step forward and thrusts it clearly in the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City Police Commissioner Howard Safir said he was
endorsing the proposals on behalf of the NYPD and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. ''The federal government has to step up to the plate and
follow the governor's courage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed ballistic fingerprinting in his State
of the Union message.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for U.S. Senate in New
York against Giuliani, said Wednesday that Pataki's proposals sound
''like a good step forward'' but added: ''I would like to see the
Republicans in Washington have the same openness towards gun safety
measures.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Republican majority in the state Senate, led by
Joseph Bruno, has refused to approve bans on assault weapons and
mandating trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno sounded peeved Wednesday that Pataki had not given him a
head's up on the proposals when they spoke the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki expects an uphill fight to get the legislation passed.
''I don't believe this is going to sail through. None of them do.
It's a dramatic change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor shrugged off the political fallout from other
Republicans. ''I'm not concerned about the politics here, I'm
concerned about the policies,'' he said. ''And the policies are
going to make our streets safer.''
</P>
<P>
   He also defended the GOP's record on crime, saying ''the root
cause of violent crime is the violent criminal. That's been the
philosophy of my party.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki noted that many of his proposals are supported by GOP
presidential candidate George W. Bush, including raising the age
for handgun ownership and banning assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether more than a small fraction of gun crimes in
New York could be solved with ballistics fingerprinting of weapons
sold here. In New York City, 94 percent of the guns used in youth
crimes and 85 percent of the guns used in adult crimes come from
out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki acknowledged that other states would have to create
similar legislation to maximize the effectiveness of ballistics
fingerprinting but said he was certain an in-state measure would
''have a very positive impact'' anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's Democratic Gov. Parris Glendening has also proposed
ballistic fingerprinting in that state.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Calls placed to New York State's three gun manufacturers,
Remington in Illion, Dan Wesson in Norwich and Kimber in Yonkers,
were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman from Remington's North Carolina headquarters,
Abe Deffenbaugh, called Pataki's proposals ''hollow rhetoric. ...
It's certainly not going to deter criminal misuse. The trigger
locks can be removed with a simple key. The ballistics
fingerprinting is not a sure-fire method. The criminal only has to
alter the inside of the barrel to put a new fingerprint in.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that although Pataki's proposals are directed at
handguns, ''I believe that this is an attempt at precedent-setting
type legislation'' for other types of weapons sold elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
