<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Campaign Eyes Fla.  </HEADLINE>
By BRENT KALLESTAD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- With political problems of his own, Florida Gov.
Jeb Bush has been distracted from helping his older brother become
president. Democrat Al Gore sees it as an opportunity to swoop in
and win the delegate-rich state that's suddenly in play.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush's top two priorities have been sidetracked -- one on
public school vouchers, the other on redoing affirmative action.
And dealing with those issues could limit his ability to campaign
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republicans' presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and their traditional constituencies, tired of being
bystanders in the state's new GOP majority, have initiated lawsuits
to thwart the Florida governor's pet programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they can stop the Republicans here, they figure there is no
way the Republicans can win the White House,'' said Lance
deHaven-Smith, a political science professor at Florida State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush presidential campaign has been counting on Jeb Bush to
deliver Florida's 25 electoral votes in November. And the governor
is still popular, communicating daily with scores of citizens via
e-mail and using his Spanish fluency to reach thousands of Hispanic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are an awful lot of true and hard supporters of Jeb
Bush,'' acknowledges state Democratic Chairman Charles Whitehead.
''And I'm sure they're energized to go to the polls and vote for
his brother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whitehead said the decision was made a couple of weeks ago
that Vice President Gore would go after Florida in the general
election regardless. Gore came to Tallahassee as vote results came
in Tuesday to let Democrats know he wasn't conceding Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gore doesn't have much choice, said Al Cardenas,
chairman of Florida Republican Party. ''If you're in Gore's shoes
and know you have to win two of the four big states to win the
election, you have to take a look at Florida,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore isn't wasting any time trying to take advantage of what
could be the opening he needs to compete in the Sunshine State -- a
state he and President Clinton carried in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One possible tactic this year: pick Florida's senior senator,
Bob Graham, as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have to pick up part of the South to win,'' deHaven-Smith
said. ''Who else are they going to get?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Democrats have plenty of concerns in Florida. Despite
their registration advantage of about 500,000 voters, far more
Republicans went to the polls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only 586,404 Democrats showed up despite a controversial ballot
issue in heavily Democratic Broward County, compared with 715,627
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''You absolutely cannot have that happen in the fall,''
Whitehead said. ''We need to take a hard look at that
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are hopeful of regaining the U.S. Senate seat being
vacated by retiring Republican Connie Mack, but it won't happen if
Bush ignites the Republican base.
</P>
<P>
   So the best strategy could be keeping Florida's governor off the
campaign trail. He was taking a personal day Wednesday and
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   When his older brother was nailing down the GOP presidential
nomination Tuesday with a sweep of six Southern states, including
Florida, a state judge was ruling Florida's school vouchers program
unconstitutional. Vouchers allow parents of students at poorly
performing public schools to attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative was the centerpiece of Jeb Bush's successful 1998
gubernatorial campaign and his first legislative session a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Also, during the opening of the Florida Legislature last week,
about 10,000 protesters marched on the Capitol against Bush's plan
to eliminate racial and gender preferences in university admissions
and state contracting. The demonstration overshadowed Bush's State
of the State speech in which he outlined his administration's
successes and goals.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials also have tried to link Bush's
so-called ''One Florida'' with George W. Bush's defense of the
Confederate flag during the South Carolina primary fight last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to take the negatives from both so it looks
more damning,'' deHaven-Smith said. ''There is a real strong effort
to link Jeb and George.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
