<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Bank Profited From Medicare  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Chicago bank found a creative way to make
$12.5 million handling Medicare money, but regulators have put a
stop to it.
</P>
<P>
   Highland Community Bank is one of 20 banks across the country
that act as intermediaries between the government and contractors
who process Medicare bills from doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1999, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. noticed that
Highland was withdrawing Medicare money from the U.S. Treasury
sooner than necessary to pay claims.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent investigation by the Health and Human Services
Department Inspector General found that since 1993, the bank had
been routinely withdrawing Medicare dollars a day earlier than
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Highland was able to earn $12.5 million in interest on the money
by lending it out to other banks overnight, HHS Inspector General
June Gibbs Brown told lawmakers on a House Government Reform
Committee panel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, during one 11-day period, the bank withdrew
hundreds of millions of dollars in excess of Medicare's immediate
billing obligations, earning over $700,000 in interest on it,
auditors found.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that when ordered to stop, the bank's officers
complied, saying they had ''believed that withdrawing funds a day
early was a 'perk' of maintaining Medicare accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Highland officials could not be immediately reached for comment
Wednesday. No charges have so far been filed against the bank, but
the government is seeking return of interest that would otherwise
have accrued to Medicare's trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are continuing to review the situation. We are looking at
whether similar types of activities have occurred with other banks,
and once we have completed our review, we will determine how to
proceed,'' said IG's office spokeswoman Alwyn Cassil.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing in the Government Management subcommittee
scrutinized Medicare's $13.5 billion in overpayments last year
because of errors and fraud, which Brown's office reported last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Medicare administrator Michael Hash said Medicare is
currently taking steps toward better oversight of financial
operations, including hiring private experts to monitor billing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
