<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Crumbles on OPEC Output Talk  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crude oil prices plummeted 3 percent Wednesday, taking gasoline
futures with them, on growing rumblings from within OPEC that the
producing nations will substantially raise output in two weeks to
feed an oil-starved world market.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, soybeans retreated after two days of
strong gains and cocoa rose.
</P>
<P>
   Oil's latest tumble means it has fallen 11 percent since topping
out at $34.37 in after-hours trading March 8 -- the latest and
perhaps last in a series of nine-year highs on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. West Texas Intermediate crude for April
delivery fell 97 cents to $30.72 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Leading producers Venezuela and Saudi Arabia touched off the
decline, dropping hints that the widely expected production boost
to be decided on at OPEC's March 27 meeting could top a combined 2
million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   That may not immediately meet growing world demand, but it
should be enough to reverse the alarming decline in dwindling oil
stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   In data that contributed to the price slippage Wednesday, the
Department of Energy reported that U.S. crude stocks rose last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is just feeling that the rally of last week was
overdone, and they feel pretty confident that OPEC is going to
raise production,'' said Phil Flynn, energy analyst for
Chicago-based Alaron Trading Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Next week they could still worry that the amount is not
enough. But right now the bears really seem to have the momentum,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's trading will provide a key test, he said, as
investors determine whether the price holds or crashes below the
$30 barrier it just hurdled Feb. 14 for the first time since the
Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Among other energy commodities, April unleaded gasoline fell
3.51 cents to 93.28 cents a gallon, April heating oil fell 1.97
cent to 71.71 cents a gallon and April natural gas rose 5.7 cents
to $2.866 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, April Brent crude from the North Sea fell 81 cents to
$27.53 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans paused from a rally on the Chicago Board of Trade as
investors took profits. Drought concerns, however, continued to
hang over the market and the correction was only a mild one.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans gave back a quarter of their 20-cent gains of the
previous two days. Market-watchers said forecasts for light showers
across the Midwest on Thursday supported the price rise.
</P>
<P>
   May soybeans fell 5 cents to $5.25 a bushel. Grains retreated
similarly, also falling nearly 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cocoa prices pushed as high as $900 a ton, up some 19 percent
from last month's 24-year lows, in the continuation of a seasonal
rally that comes after the big West African harvests are done.
</P>
<P>
   May cocoa settled up $15 to $898 a ton, the highest closing
price in two months on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1734 </TRAILER>
