<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Seeks Cleaner Diesel Fuel  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A draft government proposal to require much
cleaner diesel fuel has unleashed an intense lobbying campaign,
pitting the oil industry -- which calls it too costly -- against
state environmental officials who argue it will prevent thousands
of cancers.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency proposal, which is being
reviewed at the White House, would require a 97 percent reduction
in the amount of sulfur in diesel fuel as well as improved
pollution controls on diesel engines and large trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The new requirements, which would not take effect until 2006,
are expected to be proposed formally in about a month. EPA
Administrator Carol Browner, who has called diesel emission
reductions essential for cleaner and healthier air, will likely
want a final rule before she leaves office early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that the particulates associated with diesel do
represent a threat to public health and the environment,'' EPA
spokesman David Cohen said Wednesday. He emphasized that the
proposal is in its early stages and the agency will ''work
collaboratively with all the parties'' in developing a regulation.
</P>
<P>
   He provided no details of the preliminary EPA proposal being
reviewed by the White House Office of Management and Budget. Other
government and industry sources said it would cut sulfur emissions
from 500 parts per million to 15 parts per million and require new
pollution trapping devices and other technology in diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing refiners, oil companies, trucking companies
and other parties affected by diesel supply and costs have asked
Browner to withdraw the rule, arguing it will be costly and require
technology that may not be available.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody really knows for the most part how we would achieve
this. It would get extremely expensive to get down to those cost
levels,'' said Urvan Sternfels, president of the National
Petrochemical and Refiners Association.
</P>
<P>
   And because heating and diesel fuel come from the same refinery
stream, the extremely low sulfur requirement also will cause
problems in distribution, raising the prospects of supply problems
for both types fuels, maintained Sternfels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state pollution control officials, along with the
American Lung Association and several environmental groups,
countered Wednesday by asserting that the stringent diesel emission
rules are long overdue and necessary to protect public health.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials produced a study that maintains that toxic
chemicals in diesel exhaust from trucks and buses over a lifetime
cause at least 125,000 people to get lung cancer, and that health
costs far outweigh any additional fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''These (diesel) fumes are putting us at risk of cancer, a risk
that can be almost completely eliminated with modern pollution
controls,'' said William Becker, executive director of the State
and Territorial Air Pollution Program Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the rule stepped up their lobbying on the issue
this week, taking advantage of the uproar over soaring diesel
prices and gasoline prices and concern about future diesel supplies
because of low oil inventories. Diesel prices have jumped from a
nationwide average of 96 cents a gallon a year ago to more than
$1.50 a gallon, according to the Energy Department, with prices in
some areas as high as $1.86 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Browner, nine groups including representatives of
the oil industry, refiners and trucking industry, urged that the
proposal be withdrawn, calling it ''a blueprint for future
shortages of diesel and home heating oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Schaeffer, vice president at the American Trucking
Associations, said the regulation would require fundamentally new
diesel engine technologies that could double the price of an engine
on top of booting diesel prices.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies said they agreed that diesel emissions should
be reduced, but only to 50 parts per million. ''We're suggesting a
reduction of 90 percents instead of 97 percent to go into effect in
2010,'' said Sternfels.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials declined to discuss the proposal in detail, nor to
give any cost estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State and Territorial Air Pollution Program
Administrators: http://www.4cleanair.org
</P>
<P>
   American Trucking Associations' Green Truck site:
http://207.153.210.7
</P>
</TEXT>
