<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Panther Faces Tough Re-Election  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Former Black Panther Bobby Rush's 1992 election
to Congress from Chicago's South Side crowned his evolution from
gun-toting urban guerrilla to graying, soft-spoken mainstream
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a year after suffering overwhelming defeat in a run for
mayor, the four-term congressman faces the fight of his political
life in Illinois' March 21 primary -- a challenge from fellow
Democrats who say he has squandered the legacy of a seat that
symbolizes black political achievement in America.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st District, home to the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Louis
Farrakhan, encompasses stately mansions near the University of
Chicago, crumbling high-rise public-housing slums and tracts of
middle-class bungalows.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the district has been a springboard for black
leaders onto the national scene.
</P>
<P>
   The first black congressman of the 20th century -- Republican
Oscar DePriest -- was elected here in 1928. Later came Rep. William
Dawson, the first black chairman of a major House committee. And
another 1st District congressman, Harold Washington, went on to
become Chicago's first black mayor in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Rush wanted to follow his hero's path from Congress to City
Hall. But Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley trounced him last February
with 72 percent of the vote, even winning some predominantly black
wards.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rush is facing a contest in which there is little
disagreement on top issues: bringing economic prosperity to the
South Side, lowering prescription drug costs and addressing racial
profiling and police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rush's opponents -- state Sens. Barack Obama and Donne
Trotter and retired police officer George Roby -- are assailing the
incumbent on leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ''His vote can always be counted on,'' said Trotter, a 12-year
state legislator and health care administrator. ''But where is his
initiative?''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, 53, angrily disputes that charge, citing accomplishments
such as ensuring minorities get half the contracts in a plan to
tear down public housing and securing funds to connect inner-city
schools to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also touts his seniority -- he's poised to chair a powerful
subcommittee if Democrats regain control of the House, and is quick
to note that President Clinton and GOP House Speaker Dennis Hastert
visited the impoverished, crime-ridden Englewood neighborhood at
his request.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been a workaholic on behalf of my constituents,'' Rush
said. ''The fact is, I've been a leader, an effective leader, for
the past 35 years in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a journey of twists and turns. Rush went from the Army
to the Student Non-Violent Coordinating Committee to founding the
Illinois Black Panthers. He led the Panthers' sickle-cell anemia
testing program but also encouraged blacks to take up arms,
spending six months in jail on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rush went mainstream in the 1970s and '80s, rising through
Democratic Party ranks to become a Chicago alderman. In 1992, he
ousted incumbent Democratic Rep. Charles Hayes and was seen as a
rising star in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In the current battle to unseat Rush, the congressman could
prevail if his challengers split the anti-incumbent vote. The
tragic shooting death of his son last fall -- and his father's death
last month -- also have generated sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Obama's resume is impressive: three-term state senator, civil
rights lawyer, first black president of the Harvard Law Review,
head of a successful 1992 voter-registration drive.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're only interested in votes, or for that matter
bringing money back to the district, stick with the status quo,''
Obama, 37, said during a candidate forum at Trinity United Church
of Christ. ''But if you're concerned about long-term leadership for
our community, I think I'm you're guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotter, 49, is a product of old-fashioned Democratic ward
politics who took Carol Moseley-Braun's state House seat after she
left in 1988 and was elected to the state Senate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not just going to be a freshman in the Congress,'' Trotter
told a neighborhood association meeting. ''I'll be a transfer
student.''
</P>
<P>
   Roby, 53, the fourth candidate in the race, has spent less than
$1,000 on his campaign and is not expected to be a factor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
