<HEADLINE> U.S., North Korea Plan More Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a week of talks in New York, U.S. and
North Korean officials agreed that another round of discussions
will be needed to complete arrangements for a visit to Washington
by a high-level North Korean official, the State Department said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman James P. Rubin said the atmosphere at the talks was
constructive and businesslike. The two sides also agreed to
schedule talks on American concerns over North Korea's missile
program and on implementation of the U.S.-North Korean 1994
agreement governing Pyongyang's nuclear activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the respective delegations were Ambassador Charles
Kartman for the United States and Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye
Gwan of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials had indicated before the New York talks that a
senior North Korean official would visit Washington around the end
of March as part of a process leading to a more productive
relationship. Officials said Wednesday it was not clear whether
that timetable still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said North Korea also reconfirmed at the New York talks
that American inspectors will be allowed to make a followup visit
to Kumchang-ni, the North Korean site that some U.S. officials
believed was a nuclear weapons production site.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. inspectors toured the site last May and found no evidence
of any such activity but requested permission for a return visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
