<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet provided fresh breeding ground for illegal stock tips  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- John J. Freeman found anonymity and eager
listeners when he entered an Internet chat room as ''TheBren,''
offering an inside edge in the stock market with secrets stolen
from desks and garbage cans at two brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
   But around the corner in cyberspace lurked the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the FBI and federal prosecutors, all ready to
pounce on what they would call the first insider trading case ever
to be born on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by unusual trading activity just prior to the
announcement of some mergers and acquisitions, the cybersleuths at
the SEC went to work to see how many people Freeman had enticed to
trade on his secrets.
</P>
<P>
   What they found led Tuesday to the unveiling of insider trading
charges against 19 people and guilty pleas by two of them,
including Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   William Baker, SEC associate enforcement director, said
Wednesday it was not surprising that insider trading had reached
the Internet, in this case an America Online chat room where
Freeman and two co-defendants met as they all complained about an
investment which was going poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a group here at the commission devoted exclusively
to surveilling the Internet for fraud,'' Baker said. ''It's clearly
one of the top priorities for the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to see an increase in the number of cases
involving fraud on the Internet. Whether we'll see a lot of insider
trading cases involving the Internet remains to be seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At any time, more than 100 employees of the SEC trained as part
of a special cyberforce nationwide are assigned to sporadically
check the Internet for possible violations of securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   They visit chat rooms. They read message boards. They watch what
companies say.
</P>
<P>
   When they find something interesting, it is forwarded to the
Office of Internet Enforcement, a unit of 11 employees, mostly
lawyers, who help build cases to pursue with civil lawsuits,
criminal charges, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman's scheme was found when the Innermarket Surveillance
Group at the American Stock Exchange noticed unusual trading
involving the companies prior to their public announcements and
notified the SEC, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The case unveiled Tuesday actually involved only three people on
the Internet. But as it often does, the inside information was
passed along to friends, family and even stockbrokers, who in turn
told others.
</P>
<P>
   The scam was made possible by Freeman, a 34-year-old Brooklyn
man who was a graphic artist by day and did temporary word
processing services for companies at night.
</P>
<P>
   From May 1997 to June 1998, Freeman worked at Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co. Inc. and from October 1998 to January 2000 at Credit Suisse
First Boston Corp., where he learned secrets because he had to
create documents reflecting mergers.
</P>
<P>
   During the temporary jobs, Freeman learned of 23 different
merger and acquisition transactions but did not know the names of
the companies involved because they were referred to in code.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman used information which was not coded such as market
sector, historical stock prices, names of officers and geographic
location to figure out the names of the companies, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also examined documents from printers, the desks of coworkers
and the garbage to learn what he needed, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with the inside information, he directly tipped off at
least 10 people, allowing them to make trades and profit just
before announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Among those told was a waiter at a New York restaurant where
Freeman had once waited tables. The waiter, authorities said,
earned at least $285,000 on the information.
</P>
<P>
   Also told was a retired New York City school teacher who used to
be a frequent patron of the restaurant. He earned more than
$445,000 with the illegal information, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Freeman continued feeding the tips through
instant chats with his Internet friends -- a Bowling Green, Ky.,
insurance agent and the Charleston, W.V., vice president of a laser
printing company.
</P>
<P>
   But as his friends and acquaintances made millions of dollars,
Freeman made only between $70,000 and $110,000 in kickbacks from
those he tipped because he worried that the markets were too risky,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The money was often sent to him inside birthday cards. But cash
was not always the reward. Authorities said one man, who earned
illegal profits of more than $445,000, rewarded Freeman with three
to four cases of wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
