<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Chair Victim of Credit Fraud  </HEADLINE>
By TED BRIDIS, AP Technology Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Of all the credit card numbers in all the
world, a thief stole one belonging to a top federal regulator of
the credit card industry.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Federal Trade Commission disclosed Wednesday
that someone stole his official government credit card number in
1998 and ran up charges buying items from catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky recounted the experience at a national
conference on identity theft, which are white-collar crimes
involving thieves who pilfer personal details about victims to gain
access to their bank and credit accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky, who said he ''felt violated,'' caught the disputed
charges after reviewing the billing statement from his FTC-issued
credit card. He called the appropriate officials and filed an
affidavit, and the bill was expunged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky acknowledged that his case was handled quickly and
easily, unlike some victims who fight for years to contest disputed
charges and repair damage to their credit reports.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he was chairman of the trade commission, which
regulates part of the credit card industry, ''may have had
something to do with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the charges eventually were traced to the northeastern
United States but wasn't sure whether criminal charges ever were
filed. He said it wasn't clear how his FTC credit-card number had
been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, Pitofsky urged the credit industry to improve
its high-tech efforts to detect patterns of fraudulent purchases
and to allow consumers to report cases of identity theft to all the
appropriate companies and agencies with a single telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky also acknowledged Wednesday that the FTC may be unable
to regulate the compliance of U.S. companies exchanging personal
information about European citizens under an agreement with the
European Union announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, American companies that agree to ''safe
harbor'' guidelines would be allowed to exchange data with the 15
EU member countries, which have strict controls over how personal
information about their citizens is handled.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitofsky said the FTC ''may need additional resources''
before it can begin its watchdog role of ensuring that U.S.
companies comply with the safe harbor guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a question whether we have the resources to take that
on,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
