<HEADLINE> Israeli Youth Rally Against Haider  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- About 3,000 Israeli teen-agers rallied against
the inclusion of Joerg Haider's far-right party in Austria's
government and warned that it could encourage racism and hate in
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's anti-foreigner Freedom party won 27 percent of the vote
in Austria's Oct. 3 election. The party joined the government Feb.
4, though Haider himself remained outside and later announced his
resignation as party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to kill Jewish people everywhere,'' said Erez Dahan,
17, from the Tel Aviv suburb of Givatayim. Haider denies any
anti-Jewish intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The program looked more like a rock concert or football rally
than a political gathering. Teen-agers, their shirts plastered with
''No to Haider'' stickers and carrying anti-racism signs, chanted
off-color slogans combining Haider's name with a selection of
unprintables.
</P>
<P>
   Rock singers and dance troupes alternated with officials
speaking from a podium at the convention center. All had the same
message -- though Haider himself is not a part of the Austrian
government, his ideology is a threat to minorities all over.
</P>
<P>
   A film showed grisly scenes from Nazi concentration camps as the
announcer described the upsurge of extremist, racist and neo-Nazi
movements in the United States, France, Russia, Yugoslavia and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at the rally and at a smaller, more solemn ceremony
earlier at the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial warned that Haider's
ideology, springing from the home of the founder of Nazism, Adolf
Hitler, could lead to similar results if it is not stopped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
