<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retailers Warn Parents on Quilts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven major retailers agreed Wednesday to join
a federal government effort to educate parents about the risks of
using fluffy pillows, quilts, comforters and other soft bedding
materials with younger babies.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 900 baby deaths each year attributed to Sudden Infant
Death Syndrome may actually be caused by suffocation from soft
bedding, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the federal government has issued warnings about the
dangers of soft bedding. But in-store displays and advertising
campaigns featuring plush comforters or fluffy pillows have been
standard in the industry. That may confuse parents who then use a
similar set-up at home, not realizing it can be deadly, said Ann
Brown, CPSC chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parents and caregivers will no longer get a mixed message on
how to create a safe sleeping environment for their baby,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Babies ''R'' Us, IKEA, JC Penney, Kmart, Lands' End, Sears and
Target have agreed to change crib displays in their retail stores,
catalogues, commercial advertising and websites.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this spring, cribs in those stores will no longer be
made up with pillows, quilts and comforters. Instead they'll
feature tight fitting bedclothes and thin blankets. Retailers also
will include soft bedding warnings in their catalogues, store
displays, and inserts that accompany baby blankets and quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, babies featured in crib ads will be pictured
sleeping on their backs with their heads uncovered, a position
which has been shown to reduce the incidence of SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Consumer Product Safety Commission:
http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
