<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI on hunt for freed rapist, Corrections head to testify athearing  </HEADLINE>
By JOY RUSSELL PEREZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Federal authorities on Wednesday obtained an
arrest warrant for freed rapist Raymond Alves, allowing FBI
officials across the country to assist in the manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   Alves, now a federal fugitive, became the focus of a nationwide
manhunt since his release last Thursday from the Southern State
Correctional Center in Cumberland County after serving less than
half of his 47-year sentence for rape and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Alves told various prison officials before his
release that he was heading to Florida or Arizona and intended to
obtain a handgun, according to the federal warrant filed Wednesday
in U.S. District Court in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have demanded to know why they weren't
notified of his release beforehand, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Alves, 58, is wanted on charges of giving a false address to
corrections officials upon his release from prison and for failing
to notify authorities of his whereabouts, which is required because
he is a sex offender. Authorities said he had given them a false
address in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Alves had served 23 years of a 47-year prison term for raping a
teenager in Fair Lawn and throwing a second teen off a Clifton
bridge in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Alves was last seen checking into the Capri Inn motel in Little
Ferry on Thursday evening and checked out early Friday morning,
said Bergen County Prosecutor William H. Schmidt on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to caution the public that Alves could return back
to Camden, Bergen, Atlantic or Passaic counties,'' Schmidt said.
''He should be considered armed and dangerous. He's had a certain
(sexual) deprivation for a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and state lawmakers have called for a
review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee in Trenton will meet Thursday for
a hearing to discuss Alves and his unexpected release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Corrections Department Corrections Commissioner Jack
Terhune is expected to testify at the hearing, according to a
department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County prosecutors have also launched an investigation
into six unsolved murders to search for evidence linking them to
Alves. Schmidt declined to discuss the investigation or evidence
linking Alves to the unsolved murders.
</P>
<P>
   The Star-Ledger of Newark reported in Wednesday's editions that
a confidential memo sent by Bergen County officials to the state
Parole Board in 1995 detailed evidence linking Alves to three
Bergen County teens who were killed between April 1969 and June
1970.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also said that Alves bragged that he had raped and
killed more than a dozen women.
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo, written by Capt. Robert Scanlon, an
investigator with the Bergen County Prosecutor's Office, the teens
had worked with Alves at Executive Cleaning Service of Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Blase, 18, was last seen at the Hackensack bus station. A
law enforcement official told the newspaper that Alves was driving
a taxi in the area that night.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Blase and Denise Falasca, 15, were found in Saddle
Brook the day after they were strangled.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of Donna Albright, 13, who vanished in June 1970,
were found under a Camden Street building when it was demolished in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon's memo also named Alves as a suspect in the 1967 death
of Darlene Polizzi, 20, who was friends with both Alves and his
former wife. Polizzi, who lived across the street from Alves,
disappeared from her home and has not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also cited the 1967 murder of Mary Ann Della Salla, 17,
who disappeared while walking home from work past Alves' home, and
the 1966 death of Janet Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, 19, was found strangled and stabbed to death in the
bathroom of her home the day after her wedding, which Alves and his
wife attended.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist who approved Alves' release concluded that he
had no violent past and was unlikely to commit another crime.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen and Passaic authorities have said had they known about
his impending release, they would have sought to have Alves civilly
committed as a violent sexual predator under Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Terhune, Schmidt said, ''I've known Jack for a long
time. He's a professional law enforcement official and I know he's
probably upset that a criminal is free.
</P>
<P>
   ''He needs to look at what's going on and it appears that it's
obvious to us that there's something that needs to be fixed,''
Schmidt said. ''I'm critical because I'm spending countless
man-hours and woman-hours for something that we shouldn't be
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
