<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential Campaign Ads on Hold  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The political airwaves may be a little
quieter, at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has pledged to hold back Democratic Party
ads until the Republican Party fires the first shot. Meanwhile, the
Republican National Committee has yet to even select an admaker,
and RNC officials say they'd prefer that the Democrats went first
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, Gore has been challenging Texas Gov. George W.
Bush to forgo the unregulated soft money that the political parties
use to run ads promoting their candidates and knocking down the
opposition. These ''issue ads,'' which stop short of telling people
who to vote for but leave no doubt, can be paid for with unlimited
donations from wealthy donors, corporations and unions.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Gore made his cease-fire proposal to Bush. In
an e-mail, he promised the Democratic National Committee would
refrain from running ads as long as the RNC and other outside
groups did so.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's up to you and your party whether you want to start the ad
war arms race,'' Gore typed. ''If you are willing to do the right
thing, we can change politics forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied with an e-mail of his own Wednesday. He did not
respond to Gore's challenge on soft money, taking the opportunity
to instead slam Gore for his 1996 campaign fund-raising excesses.
As for campaign finance reform, he wrote: ''I'm afraid your own
record does not inspire confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp continued to push its case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush is ... stalling the American people on what
should be a slam dunk answer to Gore's challenge to ban soft
money,'' said spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Gimmicks aside, strategists in both parties say that Democrats
have a financial interest in postponing the party ad wars. The
Republicans are expected to have considerably more money to spend
on ads, so a cease-fire works in the Democrats' favor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Bush campaign and the RNC are in a much healthier
financial shape and so Gore is trying to limit everybody's free
speech,'' said Mark Miller, executive director of the Republican
Leadership Council, a moderate GOP group that has been supportive
of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Still, RNC officials say they have always planned to wait for
the Democrats to hit the airwaves first. And with McCain still
battling little more than a week ago, the party was waiting to see
who its nominee would be before choosing a firm to produce the ads,
said one official.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring and summer of 1996, the Democratic National
Committee ran a barrage of ads criticizing GOP nominee Bob Dole
that wounded him as the campaign moved into the fall season.
Observers have been waiting to see what the parties will do this
year and if their ads will be as effective.
</P>
<P>
   Ads are also expected from the candidates themselves. And
outside groups across the political spectrum are planning campaigns
for their issues.
</P>
<P>
   In his e-mail, Gore asked that Bush persuade supportive groups
to hold their ads, and he told reporters that he would do the same
among Democratic-leaning groups.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to control the individual plans of a myriad
political groups, even if the candidates wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Leadership Council has ads already made and is
ready to air them, though it has not said when they will begin.
Miller noted that in August each candidate will get about $70
million for the fall campaign, meaning there will be lots of
candidate ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most opportune time to run commercials on our issues that
we care about would be from now until the convention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bush camp says it won't call off RNC ads as long as the
AFL-CIO labor organization plans to run pro-Democrat ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''The DNC is small potatoes compared to Washington labor
bosses,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer. ''They're the backbone
of Al Gore's campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Gore campaign: http://www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign: http://www.georgewbush.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
