<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Fire Rockets at Israelis  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah guerrillas on Wednesday fired
rockets at Israeli posts in southern Lebanon, the last active
Arab-Israeli war front. Some of the missiles reportedly hit
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel retaliated with airstrikes at the source of the attack,
and the Lebanese government condemned the bombing raids and
rejected the possibility of Israel keeping some posts in southern
Lebanon even after a planned July withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian-backed guerrillas said in a statement that their
Islamic Resistance military wing launched the morning attack in
response to Israel's recent air raids and shelling of civilians in
the south.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Israeli-backed militiamen shelled the village of
Mansouri on the edge of an Israeli-held border strip south of Tyre,
killing a Lebanese army soldier at a checkpoint and a Lebanese
civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's fighting started when guerrillas fired about 30
rockets from hills southeast of the port city of Tyre. They hit
about 10 miles east of the border town of Naqoura, said Timur
Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. peacekeeping force in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether any Israeli position was hit, but an
Israeli security official said the guerrillas fired mortars as well
as rockets, and that some of the mortars fell just inside Israel,
near the coastal village of Zarit.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries or damage, but residents of Zarit went
into shelters, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours after the Hezbollah rocket attack, Israeli
warplanes twice struck the hills, Goksel said. The Israeli jets
returned in the early afternoon to strike at suspected guerrilla
positions in the highlands of Iqlim al-Tuffah, a guerrilla
stronghold facing the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate information on any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss condemned the Israeli attacks
and said ''Israel wants to carry out a redeployment of its forces,
rather than a withdrawal from Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoss also warned that the anti-Israel ''resistance will continue
as long as there is an inch of Lebanon's land under occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We say again that Israel cannot intimidate or terrorize us
with its vicious attacks. Rather, these attacks will only
strengthen adherence to our right and our position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has promised harsh retaliation if guerrillas attack its
northern towns. On Feb. 8, in retaliation for military casualties
from Hezbollah attacks, Israeli warplanes destroyed three power
stations in Lebanon, causing widespread electricity outages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
