<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School spending guides offers lessons in money and education  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Money isn't everything.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Township, a suburban Gloucester County town, spends
about $5,300 a year on each student, the third lowest in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Saddle River, a wealthy Bergen County town, is the top spender,
dedicating more than $17,000 to each pupil.
</P>
<P>
   But, if state tests are any indication, Harrison parents are
getting a big bang for their buck. Harrison fourth-graders posted
better scores than the highest spender in the state.
</P>
<P>
   These are just two of New Jersey's 581 school districts covered
in the state's massive comparative spending guide, an 883-page
report that compares everything from teacher salaries to how much
districts spend on administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Education released the guide on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Saddle River spends more than three times
as much as Harrison, more Harrison kids passed the state's new
fourth grade test.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the district's fourth-graders passed the
language arts portion of the test -- a section that most
fourth-graders found troublesome, regardless of how much their
districts spend. About 58 percent of Saddle River students passed
that section.
</P>
<P>
   Students in both towns posted nearly identical scores on the
math and science portions of the test.
</P>
<P>
   Saddle River and Harrison have some things in common -- and some
significant differences -- offering lessons in why some districts
spend more and others get by on less.
</P>
<P>
   Both Saddle River and Harrison have one elementary school. They
are both mostly white, English-speaking communities. They both have
committed parents who are involved with the school.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some major differences. Saddle River is a tiny
district, with about 150 students, compared to Harrison's 1,100.
Saddle River is located in one of the nation's most expensive
areas, while Harrison is in affordable southern New Jersey. And
Saddle River is an old, established town. Harrison is a growing
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Geography and demographics both play a role in the most obvious
cost difference between the two districts -- salaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Saddle River, the average teacher earns $61,500, compared to
just $35,168 in Harrison. Saddle River administrators pull in
$98,000, while Harrison administrators make $66,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're talking about one of the highest cost-of-living
counties in the nation,'' said Ed Richardson, a spokesman for the
New Jersey Education Association, the state's largest teachers
union. ''Gloucester County, and most of South Jersey, does not even
approach that.''
</P>
<P>
   Older communities, like Saddle River, also tend to have teachers
who've been around awhile. And so they earn more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in a growing situation,'' said Patricia Hoey,
superintendent in Harrison. ''Our percentage of newer teachers may
be higher.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant difference that fuels the spending
disparity is the size of the districts, said Dennis Murphy, the
Saddle River superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason our cost per pupil is so high is because we have a
small population,'' said Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   So why not merge with a neighboring district?
</P>
<P>
   ''They're a very proud community and they like their children to
attend a neighborhood school,'' said Murphy. ''And Saddle River is
a wealthy community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saddle River also spends a higher percentage of its total
spending on administration, 16 percent compared to Harrison's 9
percent. Harrison spends a larger percentage of its total dollars
in the classroom -- 56 percent compared to Saddle River's 52
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy again blames that disparity on the size of the district.
Just because a district has less students, doesn't mean there is
less administrative work, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoey said her district has learned to be more efficient,
knowing it cannot raise more tax dollars to fund programs.
</P>
<P>
   She said the district stresses teacher training and taps into
foundation grants to fund it. And that pays off in higher student
scores, she said.
</P>
<P>
   'We're running an efficient system,'' said Hoey. ''People are
doing their job here.''
</P>
<P>
   The spending guide also shows that teacher salaries are, on
average, declining slightly around the Garden State. From the
current year to the 1998-99 school year, they have dipped about 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The median teacher salary in districts that serve students in
kindergarten through eighth grade is roughly $45,000 this school
year, compared to $45,600 last year. The median salary for high
school teachers is about $54,400, down from last year's $55,000
annual salary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a whole lot of people retiring out of the ranks of
veterans,'' explained Richardson. ''They are being replaced by
people on the lower end of the salary guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher salaries ranged from $80,410 in Pascack Valley Regional
in Bergen County to about $34,000 a year in Swedesboro-Woolwich in
Gloucester County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
