<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Kemet Corp., up 5{ at 74
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to report fourth-quarter earnings at least
40 percent above analysts' estimates of 52 cents a share. Kemet,
which makes equipment for the computer and electronics industries,
said it has improved manufacturing efficiencies and has seen growth
in demand for its products.
</P>
<P>
Enzo Biochem Inc., up 3\ at 80\
</P>
<P>
   The company received a patent covering methods for editing and
correcting certain abnormalities in genes. Enzo's technology
involves making small insertions or deletions of genetic material,
rather than traditional methods which require the insertion of an
entire new gene.
</P>
<P>
Southwest Securities Group Inc., down 3} at 39
</P>
<P>
   The financial services company hired Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. to
advise it on strategic alternatives. Investment brokerage Raymond
James &AMP; Associates cut its rating on Southwest to ''market
perform'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Intel Corp., up 2 5/16 at 120 3/16
</P>
<P>
   Intel plans to acquire Giga A/S, a unit of Denmark's NKT Holding
A/S, for about $1.25 billion in cash. Intel expects the deal to
help it boost production of semiconductors used in data and
telephone networks.
</P>
<P>
Oracle Corp., up 1| at 78|
</P>
<P>
   The business software company said late Tuesday it earned $763
million, or 25 cents per share, in its fiscal third quarter,
compared with $293 million, or 10 cents a share, in the year-ago
period. Analysts had expected Oracle to earn 10 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
E.piphany Inc., down 61 15/16 at 187
</P>
<P>
   E.piphany will acquire closely held Octane Software Inc. for
$3.19 billion in stock to bring together two companies that make
software for communication between businesses and customers over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
LHS Group Inc., up 12] at 52
</P>
<P>
   Sema Group PLC has agreed to acquire LHS Group, a maker of
billing and operations support software, for $4.7 billion in stock.
Sema shareholders will own 73 percent of the new company, while LHS
shareholders will own about 27 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
