<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Retorts on Campaign Finance  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore rallied union backers
Wednesday with a warning that their Republican foes would ''stop at
nothing'' to win in November. George W. Bush sent him a cyberspace
retort to the campaign finance challenge Gore e-mailed the previous
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important for Americans to know whether the current
campaign finance laws have been obeyed and enforced. So I challenge
you to clear the air on some serious charges,'' Bush wrote in his
own e-mail to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he asked the vice president to press the White
House to release ''all records and photographs'' relating to
now-closed investigations of Gore's 1996 fund-raiser at a Buddhist
temple and his fund-raising phone calls from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm afraid your own record does not inspire confidence,'' Bush
chided.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor added that if Gore is so keen on banning
''soft money'' donations to political campaigns, his speech to the
union group would have been a perfect place to urge the banning of
labor contributions not specifically approved by union members.
Bush has said it would be ''unilateral disarmament'' for the
Republicans to agree to ban soft money from corporations while
similar donations flowed to the Democrats from big labor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, addressing the Pennsylvania AFL-CIO convention, looked
ahead with a devilish tone to Bush's nomination at the Republican
National Convention this summer in Philadelphia, where Mayor, John
F. Street is a Gore supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, I know the city is going to do the superb job it always
does for any group, but I just want you to make sure that's as
close as (Bush) gets to the White House,'' Gore instructed some
1,000 cheering union workers and leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who's going to fight for the working people?'' Gore called.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are!'' was the crowd's reply.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized his support for organized labor's agenda,
including a $1 increase in the minimum wage and tougher enforcement
of laws against union busting. He made just one passing reference
to campaign finance reform, the issue he has trumpeted with great
fanfare since Bill Bradley, a Democrat, and John McCain, a
Republican, dropped from the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, not quite taking a day off at the Texas Governor's
Mansion, took note of the omission from afar. In his e-mail, Bush
said the AFL-CIO meeting ''would have been an ideal setting to
display your sudden interest in campaign finance reform and to
demonstrate your own seriousness on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Signaling that he will match Gore stunt for stunt in this
campaign, Bush closed his electronic message with this zinger:
''Thank you for your e-mail. This Internet of yours is a wonderful
invention.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been a subject of jokes -- some gentle, some not -- for
his claim to have been instrumental in inventing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He zoomed to Philadelphia from Tallahassee, Fla., where he had
celebrated the Tuesday primaries that clinched the Democratic
presidential nomination. While Bush stayed in Texas, Gore made good
on his promise to have ''no letup'' in the intensity of his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After the labor convention, a $75,000 campaign fund-raising
lunch, a school-safety forum and a Pittsburgh rally packed Gore's
schedule. At the Philadelphia-area vocational school, he argued for
stronger gun-control measures, including mandatory trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said school violence ''is actually going down but the
horrific examples of violence are getting worse.'' Help for
''stressed-out'' parents could help, he said, including raising the
minimum wage, expanding the Family Medical Leave Act and demanding
equal pay for women.
</P>
<P>
   To increase school safety, he recommended more school counselors
and psychologists, metal detectors in schools that want them,
reduced class sizes and renovated school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   He also had critical remarks for the head of the National Rifle
Association, who has been trading harsh words with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore planned another full day of campaign events in Washington
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to win, we have got to understand the other side is
going to throw everything they've got plus the kitchen sink.
They're manning the barricades they're trying to funnel
unprecedented money into the campaign. They're going to stop at
nothing,'' Gore told the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The labor federation -- with its leafleting, canvassing and
get-out-the-vote push -- was instrumental in carrying Gore to
victory over Bradley in the Democratic primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore asked union supporters to keep fighting, dangling the
prospect of Democrats not only keeping the White House but
reclaiming control of Congress from the Republicans, including
House Majority Leader Dick Armey and Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very close to getting the Gingrich group -- Armey and
Delay, all that crowd -- out of the leadership of the Congress,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich, the former Republican House speaker from Georgia,
left Congress in 1998 but the Gore campaign aims to keep him as its
symbol of the GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
