<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Launches Budget Fight  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans moved Wednesday toward pushing a
2001 budget through the House Budget Committee that envisions a far
smaller tax cut than George W. Bush wants, exposing the conflicting
political needs of Bush and GOP lawmakers in this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee, has made a
five-year, $483 billion tax cut a defining issue of his campaign in
a bid to rally conservatives to his cause.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional Republicans would limit their cuts to between
$150 billion and about $240 billion. That reflects a desire to
avoid another veto fight over taxes with President Clinton and to
satisfy internal demands for more spending for defense and some
domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Underlining the differences between the two sides, Republicans
on the budget panel sidestepped an effort by Democrats to force
them to vote on putting Bush's tax cuts into the budget. And from
campaign headquarters in Austin, the Texas governor's spokeswoman,
Mindy Tucker, distanced Bush from the House GOP package.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it's possible to meet basic needs, fund priorities
and return money to the taxpayers without increasing spending as
rapidly as this proposal contemplates,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   But she also said Bush ''does recognize the pressure Congress
currently has with a Democrat president who is pressuring them to
spend money on bigger government. That will not be a problem with a
President Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has contrasted himself with the GOP-run Congress before.
Last year, he accused Republicans of trying to ''balance their
budget on the backs of the poor'' with a plan to squeeze savings
from working families collecting the earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the Bush campaign ''has not directed Hill activities
in any way'' while Republicans were writing their budget.
</P>
<P>
   But one top House GOP official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said of the Bush campaign, ''They wanted as big a tax
cut as they could get.'' This official said that given Clinton's
demands for a smaller tax cut, ''We've stretched it as far as we
could stretch it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich,
R-Ohio, fought and lost a battle with House GOP leaders to make
room in the budget for Bush's tax proposal. Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, is currently waging that same fight in the Senate Budget
Committee, where Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., plans votes on a
budget like Kasich's next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to spotlight the divergence between Bush and
congressional Republicans, Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., tried
forcing the budget committee to vote on whether to accept Bush's
tax cuts in full.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said Bush's tax cut would not fit into the GOP budget
because it is so big that it would eat into Social Security
surpluses, something both parties have vowed to avoid. Bush's
proposal, which wouldn't begin until 2002, would consume $73
billion in Social Security funds through 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush tax plan is ''being put out there in the presidential
campaign as a piece of high fluff,'' said McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   But he was outmaneuvered when by voice vote, Republicans amended
McDermott's amendment to instead call for unearthing federal waste,
fraud and abuse and using the money for tax cuts and debt
reduction. No direct vote on the Bush tax cuts was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that from 2001 through 2005 -- the years their
budget covers -- Bush's tax cuts total $300 billion, not far from
the maximum size of their plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not walking away from the Bush tax cut and neither are the
Republicans on this committee,'' Kasich said. ''We can't get all
the way there with this president.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's $1.82 trillion federal budget is a blueprint for
spending and tax legislation Congress will work on later this year.
</P>
<P>
   As the budget panel worked on the plan, Democrats tried
repeatedly -- and unsuccessfully -- to shrink the tax cut, beef up
the Social Security and Medicare trust funds and boost spending for
debt reduction and education. The votes were mostly party line.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts in the GOP budget are about $50 billion deeper than
Clinton has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   It would provide $307 billion for next year's defense budget, $1
billion higher than Clinton's plan. Its $290 billion for domestic
programs ranging from parkland purchases to bureaucrat's pencils is
nearly $30 billion less than Clinton prefers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and congressional Republicans would set aside all
$977 billion in projected Social Security surpluses through 2005
for debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
