<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mo. Sues Kraft Foods Over Dumping  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- The state of Missouri is suing Kraft Foods,
alleging a subsidiary of the consumer products giant illegally
dumped 4,600 tons of hot dog casings and endangered public
waterways.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed Tuesday by state Attorney General Jay Nixon
seeks civil penalties of up to $10,000 for each day of violations
and reimbursement of the costs to restore any damaged waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft spokeswoman Cathy Pernu has said the company offered to
remove the casings and pay a settlement, but that offer was
rejected by the state. She did not immediately return a call
seeking comment on the lawsuit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Revenue also has asked Kraft Foods to
return $1 million in tax rebates it received for recycling waste.
</P>
<P>
   ''From my perspective, they were dumping waste and taking a tax
break for recycling,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said Columbia Foods Co., which makes Oscar Mayer hot
dogs, dumped used cellulose casings on a central Missouri farm
under contract with the owners. The site southwest of Columbia
drains through a creek into the Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said Tuesday his office has not found a ''significant
movement into the waters of the state at this point,'' nor has
damage to the streams or the river been detected. But filing the
lawsuit gives the state more freedom to test for damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is, I think, of paramount importance for us to move and
move quickly, not to wait until 30 tons of grease and sludge move
their way into Perche Creek or the Missouri River,'' Nixon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
