<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Exec Objects to Art Sale Plan  </HEADLINE>
By RAF CASERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- An EU executive threatened Wednesday to
torpedo a hard-fought plan to grant artists the right to claim
royalties on the resale of their work.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Ireland, Austria and the Netherlands -- all of which do
not offer royalties on the resale of artistic works -- long opposed
an EU-wide approach, but in the end said they were ready to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, the European Commission mounted a new
threat, objecting to a 15-year transition period for the measure to
take full effect across the 15 European Union nations.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a meeting of European Union internal market
ministers, EU spokesman Jonathan Todd said the executive considered
the 15-year grace period too long. As a rule, such periods -- which
give governments time to bring their laws into compliance with EU
rules -- rarely exceed 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission's move is highly unusual and could kill a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the EU's complex voting rules, if the Commission sticks to
its objection on Thursday, EU governments must endorse the measure
unanimously rather than by a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   EU governments have been haggling among themselves for years
over the issue of granting artists royalties each time their works
are resold, with Britain putting up the fiercest resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has said if the royalties become mandatory, London's art
market will flee to New York or Switzerland, where there are no
royalties in place.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal on the table, painters and sculptors would share
in the wealth their works generate long after the original sale,
similar to the way musicians and writers earn royalties from use of
their work.
</P>
<P>
   Artists would receive resale royalties based on a sliding scale
from 4 percent on sales of up to $50,000, to just 0.25 percent on
the portion of the sale price of a work that ends up being worth
more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The royalties would keep flowing during the artist's life. Heirs
would be able to claim them for a period of 70 years after the
artist's death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1811 </TRAILER>
