<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Soars on Buying Spree  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American consumers' buying spree of foreign
goods from TVs to cars last year led to an immense increase in the
trade deficit -- up more than 50 percent to a record high of $338.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit in the ''current account,'' which measures not only
trade in goods and service but also investment flows and foreign
aid payments, grew by 53.7 percent from the previous record, a
$220.6 billion imbalance in 1998, the Commerce Department said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, investors didn't appear to pay much attention to
this or other economic reports out Wednesday. The Dow Jones stock
average soared to its fourth-biggest point gain ever as investors
moved money that has streamed out of the technology sector this
week into long-forgotten industrial stocks. The Dow closed up
320.17 at 10,131.41. The Nasdaq, meanwhile, fell 124.01 to close at
4,582.62 as investors continued to shed technology shares. That
brought the index's loss for the past three days to 465 points, or
9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty $118.4 billion deterioration in the current account
deficit is the one bit of tarnish on an otherwise sterling,
record-breaking U.S. economy, which celebrated its ninth year of
uninterrupted growth in March.
</P>
<P>
   While all categories measured showed deterioration in 1999,
America's deficit in goods widened the most -- by $100.2 billion to
$347.1 billion -- as U.S. consumers snapped up TVs, cars and other
merchandise flowing into the U.S. from overseas' producers.
</P>
<P>
   With plentiful jobs, rising incomes, low inflation and stock
market gains, Americans feel wealthy and in the buying mood,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ''U.S. consumers have a strong appetite for everything,'' said
Gerald Cohen, economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Economists predict the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates
next week for the fifth time since June to slow the red-hot economy
and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The bloated deficit, economists said, is actually a testimony to
the robust state of the U.S. economy compared with other countries,
particularly foreign economies that are continuing to recover from
a global financial crisis that struck in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperous consumers are helping the United States rapidly
gobble up imported goods as demand from overseas' economies for
U.S. exports, while picking up, continues to lag.
</P>
<P>
   And, while America enjoyed surpluses in the services category,
which measures such things as airline travel, in 1999 the surplus
shrank to $79.6 billion from $82.7 billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is the pace car in the economic race in the
global economy,'' said Tim O'Neill, chief economist for the Bank of
Montreal and Harris Bank. ''Because of that, U.S. consumers are in
a position to buy a lot from abroad and foreigners will want to
invest in the United States because the economy is so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the U.S. market's attractiveness to overseas
investors, the deficit in investment earnings widened to $24.8
billion in 1999, more than double the $12.2 billion deficit of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 deficit was the first one in investment income since
the early part of the 20th century but the sharp widening in 1999
was evidence, economists said, that it won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   An unbroken string of current account trade deficits over the
past 24 years has transformed America from the world's largest
creditor country to the largest debtor nation and foreigners are
now earning bigger returns on the investments they have purchased
with the dollars earned in selling their goods to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy could face dangers at some point, economists
warn, if the huge increases in the trade deficit continue and
foreigners suddenly decide they no longer want to hold
dollar-denominated assets. A sudden rush for the exits could send
American stock prices and the value of the dollar plunging.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, ''over the long term the deficit could become a
serious problem, but a lot of people shrug that off because the
economy is doing so well,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, managing
director of the Economic Strategy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, the trade deficit has created headaches
for the Clinton administration and Congress, which face pressure
for new trade barriers to help domestic industries combat the flood
of cheaper-priced imports. The swollen deficit figures are also
certain to be cited by foes of Clinton's policies in the upcoming
battle in Congress to grant China permanent normal trade relations
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports:
</P>
<P>
   -- Industrial production grew by a modest 0.3 percent in
February, after soaring the month before, as gains in the output of
semiconductors and computers were offset by declines in car and
home appliance production, the Federal Reserve said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Businesses boosted their stockpiles of goods on shelves and
backlots moderately in January, but with sales climbing at an even
faster rate, supplies fell to the leanest level on record, the
Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The trade report:
http://www.bea.doc.gov/bea/rels.htm
</P>
<P>
   Fed's industrial production report:
http://www.bog.frb.fed.us/Releases/G17/Current/default.htm
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department's web site:
http://osecnt13.osec.doc.gov/public.nsf
</P>
</TEXT>
