<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Pentagon Reports Said Incomplete  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two Pentagon reports on how former Soviet
states are spending some military aid have been late, incomplete
and inaccurate, fogging the question of whether the money is being
misused, the General Accounting Office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, was asked to study
Pentagon performance in 1997 and 1998 in providing an annual
accounting for money given under the Cooperative Threat Reduction
program.
</P>
<P>
   The program, for which Congress has appropriated $3.2 billion
since 1992, is to help the former Soviet Union destroy weapons on
mass destruction, safely store and transport weapons marked for
destruction and cut the risk of their proliferation. And the
Pentagon is to report each year by Jan. 31 on assistance provided,
where the assistance was given and whether the assistance had been
used for the intended purpose .
</P>
<P>
   But the 1997 report was submitted to Congress 16 months late and
the 1998 report 10 months late. This ''denied Congress timely
information'' on whether ''assistance was being diverted or
misused'' at times when lawmakers were considering whether to
approve further appropriations, GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The delays ... were primarily due to DOD's prolonged review of
the draft reports and the relatively low priority its officials
placed'' on their deadline, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   GAO also said defense officials ''did not provide complete and
fully accurate information'' in the two reports and listed the
following examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- Failed to list more than $27 million in assistance given in a
three-month period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   -- Listed only one form of assistance, representing only 19
percent of the program's expenditures, rather than all assistance
provided.
</P>
<P>
   -- Contained either ''insupportable or overstated estimates'' of
the percent of equipment the Pentagon audited.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report was released late in the day and a Pentagon
official did not immediately return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the GAO said that when its asked for Pentagon comment in
compiling its report, military officials generally agreed with the
report. The Pentagon acknowledged better procedures were needed to
meet the deadlines, GAO said..
</P>
<P>
   ''DOD also stated it believes our report implies DOD does not
have big confidence ... that assistance is being properly used and
that this implication is unwarranted,'' the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd D. Spence, chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said the GAO findings raised questions on the Pentagon's
ability to ensure that Russia and other former Soviet states are
using the funds as intended.
</P>
<P>
   ''The House Armed Services Committee may need to consider other
ways to ensure that we receive the information needed to perform
our oversight role,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1821 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
