<DOCNO> APW20000315.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Core Voters Turn Out for Bush, Gore  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The voters who turned out to help George W.
Bush clinch the GOP presidential nomination were mostly Protestant
or evangelicals, white, Republican and over age 50. For Democrat Al
Gore, they were more likely to be women, black, Catholic and also
middle aged.
</P>
<P>
   They are the most dependable voters, those who go the polls
under any circumstance to back their candidates even, as was the
case Tuesday, when the race has been virtually decided.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some still wanted to have their say.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's already decided so the vote doesn't really make a
difference,'' 59-year-old Kathleen Dickson of Sanford, Fla., said
at a voting precinct Tuesday. ''But I want to make sure that I get
my say for George Bush. I vote because I have that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that Republican voters in Florida, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas overall had an
overwhelmingly favorable view of Bush, the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Those with unfavorable views of Bush, about one in 10, were not
likely to cross over and support Gore, the vice president. More
than half said they would vote for Bush or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth of voters in Democratic primaries had an unfavorable
view of Gore and a majority of them, six in 10, said they would
vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That difference is likely a reflection of Bush's overall
popularity in the conservative region.
</P>
<P>
   But Julia Abramson, a Democrat from Oklahoma City, said there
was no question about which candidate would get her vote in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a Democrat and I voted for Al Gore,'' she said. ''He's for
women's rights and in favor of education, Medicare and Social
Security, and I think those things are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed Bush running very strong in the Southern
primaries as well as in Utah and Colorado, which voted several days
earlier. Gore's support, meanwhile, was more spotty.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taggert, a silver-haired man from Oklahoma City, who
breathed with the aid of an oxygen bottle, said he voted for the
governor of neighboring Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a Republican and I want a change in the White House,''
Taggert said. ''I would like to have a nice, clean, honest
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted by Voter News Service, a
consortium of The Associated Press and television networks, at
selected precincts in the states of Florida, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas. The poll of 6,297
voters in the GOP primaries and the poll of 5,312 voters in the
Democratic primaries had error margins of plus or minus 1.5
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
