<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at Core Bush, Gore Voters  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A look, based on exit poll data, at the voters who
backed George
W. Bush and Al Gore in primary elections last week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH VOTERS: Predominantly Protestant or evangelical, white,
Republican, conservative and age 50 or older.
</P>
<P>
   GORE VOTERS: More likely to be women, also over age 50, about
evenly split between moderates and liberals. Included a good mix of
blacks, about a fourth of the vote, and Catholics, about a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENTS: This crucial bloc of votes seems up in the air for
both Gore and Bush, with about two-thirds voting for Bush in the
GOP primaries and two-thirds voting for Gore in the Democratic
primaries. Many of the remaining independent voters backed
challengers John McCain and Bill Bradley, even though they have
dropped out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   GORE vs. BUSH: Voters in the Republican primaries in the last
week were heavily for Bush, with his support ranging above eight in
10 voters in Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee
and Texas, as well as the Western states of Colorado and Utah. Gore
got the support of more than eight in 10 voters in the Democratic
primaries in Florida, Mississippi and Tennessee, as well as
Colorado and Utah. In Louisiana, Oklahoma and Texas, his level of
support ranged from two-thirds to three-fourths.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted Tuesday by Voter News Service, a
consortium of The Associated Press and television networks, at
selected precincts in the states of Florida, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas. The poll of 6,297
voters in the GOP primaries and the poll of 5,312 voters in the
Democratic primaries had error margins of plus or minus 1.5
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
