<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Pressured on Safety Spending  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- ''Appalling'' safety hazards in New York and
New Jersey train tunnels should become a top priority as Amtrak
decides how to spend limited capital improvement funds, a
government watchdog testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mead, inspector general at the Department of
Transportation, said a train accident in tunnels connecting New
Jersey to New York City under the Hudson River, or New York City to
Long Island under the East River, could be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion before the House Appropriations subcommittee on
transportation highlighted the pressure on Amtrak to spend money on
existing problems even as it tries to grow its business to meet an
Oct. 1, 2002, deadline for financial self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are lots of competing needs, and they're all
important,'' said Amtrak President George Warrington.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the congressional hearing took place hours after
an Amtrak train derailed in Kansas, injuring 29 people.
</P>
<P>
   Mead held up a picture of a spiral staircase, 10 stories tall,
wide enough for only one person, which would have to accommodate
people fleeing a tunnel accident as well as rescuers trying to
reach it from above.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you had a serious tunnel fire, the existing systems they
have for evacuation aren't ones you or I would like to contend
with,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated it will cost $654 million to address fire and
safety issues in the tunnels and in New York's Penn Station.
Amtrak, the Long Island Railroad and NJ Transit, which use the
tunnels, have spent about $150 million so far to address the
problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., the chairman of the subcommittee, was
swayed. ''This really ought to be (priority) number one,'' he said,
pointing to the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Scheinberg, associate director for transportation issues
at the General Accounting Office, said Amtrak is spending most of
its annual funding from Congress to maintain equipment rather than
to invest in new equipment or better tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ''This means Amtrak is not spending the federal appropriation to
make investments needed to improve its competitive position in the
market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheinberg added that two years have elapsed since Amtrak last
had a multiyear plan for how to spend its capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Warrington defended how the railway spends its money and said
there is too little to go around.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel like dogs fighting over table scraps,'' Warrington
said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposed 2001 budget includes $521 million
for Amtrak, plus an additional $468 million to help the railway
expand passenger service. But the extra $468 million may be shot
down in Congress because it would come out of federal gas tax
money. Many members of Congress say all the gas tax money should go
to the states.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation passed in 1997, Amtrak has until the end of
fiscal year 2002 to wean itself from federal operating subsidies or
face possible liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from past practices, Amtrak officials have
decided to pursue expansion rather than cuts in order to reach
financial health. Last month the railway announced plans to add new
passenger routes, expand into package delivery and maintain
unprofitable routes.
</P>
<P>
   Warrington all but guaranteed that Amtrak will meet its deadline
for self-sufficiency. But Scheinberg told the subcommittee she
doubts Amtrak can meet the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said Amtrak may meet the deadline but only if there are no
further delays in the much-awaited ''Acela Express'' high-speed
service between Washington and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That service was originally scheduled to begin at the end of
1999; the consortium building the trains now promises to deliver
the first train in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1826 </TRAILER>
