<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Appointees Win in GOP Primary  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Two minority appointees of Gov. George W.
Bush won Republican primaries, assuring them of taking office in
November and bolstering Bush's effort to broaden his party's
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Railroad Commission chairman Michael Williams would be the
first black elected in a statewide, non-judicial race in Texas.
State Supreme Court Justice Al Gonzales was Bush's general counsel
and secretary of state before Bush appointed him to a Supreme Court
vacancy last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared in television commercials for both men before
Tuesday's primary. Both often appeared on stage with Bush during
speeches televised in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Recent national polls show Bush and Vice President Al Gore
virtually even in the presidential race. Each is trying to expand
his party's traditional base of support and win over independent
voters. For Bush, that includes attracting blacks and Hispanics who
traditionally vote for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''He believes it is important to broaden the base of the
Republican Party by reaching out to new faces and new voices,''
said Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a longtime ally of the Bush family. The governor's
wife, Laura, and his father, former President Bush, were keynote
speakers at Williams' fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you're seeing the party that does welcome the variety
that we have in Texas, the diversity,'' said a Bush supporter, Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas. ''That's what Texas is, and Governor
Bush helped make this possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was appointed assistant U.S. education secretary
for civil rights by President Bush in 1990, said he would
enthusiastically work on the younger Bush's presidential campaign
if asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales said electing a Hispanic to the Texas Supreme Court was
politically important to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he understood that there would be a message sent by my
election,'' Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who speaks Spanish, won nearly half of the Hispanic vote
during his successful 1998 re-election campaign -- a rare level of
support for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hailey, spokesman for the Texas Democratic Party, said
regardless of the victories of Williams and Gonzales, blacks and
Hispanics in Texas are not turning Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in predominately Hispanic counties voted in far greater
numbers-- sometimes more than 20-to-1 -- in the Democratic primary
than the GOP primary, Hailey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1904 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Aid Group's Future Debated  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD N. OSTLING, AP Religion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Delegates from the National Council of Churches
are meeting to debate whether the organization's international
welfare agency -- the Church World Service -- should take control of
its own finances.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for the troubled church council. The World
Service, a major aid group, accounts for 88 percent of the
council's projected $71.3 million income this year.
</P>
<P>
   The council is a federation of 33 Protestant and Orthodox
denominations representing 100,000 local congregations. Delegates
are to meet Thursday and Friday in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Patrick Mauney, an Episcopal Church executive who
chairs the Church World Service governing committee, said one
source of friction is that some donations intended for the aid
group ''have been used for purposes other than what was designated,
to cover other costs in the National Council of Churches.''
</P>
<P>
   The aid group also recently agreed to pay a special assessment
of $1,453,000 to help the council meet its estimated deficit of $4
million for 1999. And the council raised its fee for administrative
services this year from 6.3 percent of the aid group's income to
8.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Page, director of the Church World Service, complained
that council officials unilaterally hiked the fee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process was not followed. There was a feeling that trust
was broken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Page who proposed last year that the group take charge of
its own finances, and the governing committee unanimously approved
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland meeting is the first for Rev. Robert Edgar, who
took over as general secretary of the National Council of Churches
on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar, a former Democratic congressman, argues against changing
control of the Church World Service, saying the council is
improving its administration and that it would be wasteful to have
two finance offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, we are one institution,'' he said. ''The issue is
fixing what was broken, not artificially pulling things apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1909 </TRAILER>
