<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Peace at Critical Stage  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Colombia's second-largest guerrilla
group said that it could quickly reach an agreement with that
country's government over an army withdrawal from a northern
enclave to allow peace talks to be held there.
</P>
<P>
   But Pablo Beltran of the National Liberation Army, or ELN, said
his organization was losing patience and faith in discussions with
envoys of President Andres Pastrana that have dragged on for more
than year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've reached the point at which the government has to either
take it or leave it,'' Beltran, a member of the group's 5-man
command council, said Tuesday of the proposed troop pullout from a
northern ELN stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no intermediate solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   More meetings with government delegates were expected this
weekend in the Venezuelan capital, where left-leaning president
Hugo Chavez has given safe haven and presidential bodyguards to the
rebels, who are inspired by Fidel Castro's Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Beltran said he saw only a ''50-50 chance'' that Pastrana
would agree to grant the ELN a demilitarized zone similar to one in
southern Colombia established to allow peace talks with a larger
rebel faction, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to maintain pressure for such a zone, the group has
stepped up bombings of electrical energy towers -- causing
electricity rationing for millions of people -- and staged
disruptive highway blockades.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it hijacked an Avianca airliner, abducting its
passengers and crew and kidnapping hundreds of worshippers from a
Catholic mass -- raising money and grabbing attention at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that hostage releases or other humanitarian
concessions could be part of a deal to create a
troop-and-police-free zone in three rural towns in the northern
state of Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN wants to use the region to hold parallel talks -- one set
with the government and another with labor, peasant and human
rights groups aimed at generating an agenda for social change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
