<HEADLINE> U.S. Gives Missile Frigate to Poland  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- America's flag came down and the Polish flag
was hoisted aboard the USS Clark on Wednesday as the ship embarked
on a second career in the Polish navy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being turned into scrap, the 20-year-old
guided-missile frigate was transferred to the fledgling NATO member
as part of an effort to upgrade Poland's fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Sailors hauled down the Clark's commissioning pennant and the
American flag and the Clark's American crew walked off the ship
during a ceremony at the Norfolk Naval Station. The Clark's
American skipper, Cmdr. Albert F. Lord Jr., then turned the ship
over to its Polish commanding officer, Cmdr. Marian Ambroziak.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's red-over-white striped flag was hoisted and the Polish
crew came aboard the ship, re-christened FRR 272.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark is the first of two U.S. Navy ships scheduled to be
transferred to Poland, which joined the NATO a year ago. At 445
feet long, it becomes the second-largest ship in the country's
navy.
</P>
<P>
   With a primarily Baltic fleet, Poland now needs bigger ships
that can handle operations in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's American sailors and its new Polish crew have sailed
together three times since early January in preparation for the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark became the second U.S. ship given to Poland. The
country received a U.S. submarine during World War II, Ambroziak
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 1932 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers More Mozambique Aid  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Criticizing congressional cuts in foreign aid,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright appealed Wednesday for money
to help get U.S. forces out of Kosovo and said the administration
may ask for emergency funds to assist flood victims in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time after time, we have gone to the cupboard, but the
cupboard has been bare,'' Albright said, decrying Republican plans
to cut 13 percent from what she said already is a lean foreign
affairs budget.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee last week slashed civilian
assistance for Kosovo and debt relief for Mozambique, Bolivia and
other poor countries from an emergency budget request expected to
reach the House floor as early as next week. The bill also includes
money for U.S. forces in Kosovo, for fighting drugs in Colombia and
for domestic disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's foreign affairs budget is expected to be cut from
the $15 billion Clinton requested to about $13 billion, Rep. Sonny
Callahan, subcommittee chairman, told Albright.
</P>
<P>
   However, Callahan, R-Ala., said that while he would not support
debt relief unless it requires countries to stay out of debt in the
future, he believes the U.S. government should do more for
Mozambique, where flooding has killed nearly 500 people and left
330,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan urged Albright to use emergency money available now to
immediately step up assistance to the African country.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the U.S. Agency for International Development
already has provided $7 million in emergency food aid and $5.7
million in disaster assistance, and officials are assessing other
needs. U.S. civilian and military disaster teams also have been
dispatched, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Treasury Department is moving to forgive the $4.9
million debt owed by Mozambique to the U.S. government, and
assistance is going to Zimbabwe, Botswana and South Africa, which
also were hit by flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope to have an assessment of additional funds that
may be needed for the region by the time the supplemental
appropriations bill comes up next week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On money for Kosovo, Albright said, ''We strongly oppose the
elimination of funds to revitalize Kosovo's economy and civil
society.''
</P>
<P>
   The money funds what amounts to ''an exit strategy'' for U.S.
troops, she said, because without the rebuilding of Kosovo society,
foreign troops will have to stay longer.
</P>
<P>
   On debt relief, she said, ''It is in our own interest to help
these countries stay on the course to self-sufficiency, and that
means helping to ease their international debt burdens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
