<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manhunt Frightens Md. Community  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX DOMINGUEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOWLEYS QUARTERS, Md. (AP) -- The supermarket and video store
close early these days. Parents are hesitant to let their children
ride bicycles and few people go out at night.
</P>
<P>
   Police cars, helicopters and bloodhounds have become part of an
ominous landscape as authorities search for Joseph Palczynski,
accused of killing four people after kidnapping his girlfriend last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The slayings and subsequent manhunt have made this waterfront
suburb of Baltimore a virtual ghost town at night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Around our neighborhood we have a lot young kids, and you
don't see anyone out at night,'' Yvonne Alberts said. ''Usually,
they're out on their bikes until 7:30, 8 at night, but it's quiet
as a mouse. Spooky in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have tracked the 31-year-old electrician from the
scene of the killings, about 15 miles northeast of Baltimore, to
Virginia and back. There hasn't been a confirmed sighting since
Saturday, when a man abducted in Virginia said he drove Palczynski
back to Bowleys Quarters. But the suspect's return has residents on
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Police have responded to more than 1,000 calls from residents
reporting everything from open shed doors to suspected sightings.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Lambo said one neighbor apparently called police after
seeing her daughter's boyfriend playing in the woods with a
paintball gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police told him to lie down on the ground, and it had just
rained,'' Lambo said. ''He came in and he was covered with mud. He
was really upset. Everybody's on edge. I wish they would just catch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The local supermarket now closes at 6 p.m. instead of 11 p.m.,
as does the video store, which normally shuts down at midnight.
Police urge residents to stay out of the woods and lock their homes
and cars.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 officers have been assigned to the manhunt, including
FBI agents, state police and officers from surrounding counties.
</P>
<P>
   The search has been hampered by Palczynski's outdoor skills and
the landscape surrounding the residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a great deal of territory down there to cover ...
It's marshy, heavily wooded in some areas,'' Baltimore County
police spokesman Bill Toohey said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, police tried to persuade Palczynski to turn himself
in, releasing a handwritten statement by his girlfriend, Tracy
Whitehead. She escaped the day after her abduction by running to a
police officer who happened to be at a motel where Palczynski took
her.
</P>
<P>
   A videotaped plea by Palczynski's mother and statement from his
attorney have also been aired. Police hope Palczynski will hear the
pleas via a battery-operated television investigators said he
bought along with outdoor gear last week.
</P>
<P>
   Palczynski's mother also left a message on her home answering
machine pleading with him to turn himself in, or commit suicide as
he had threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The killings began March 7, four days after Whitehead said
Palczynski beat her when she moved out of the apartment they shared
and moved in with a co-worker, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Palczynski abducted Whitehead at gunpoint after
shooting to death the couple who had sheltered her, then killed a
neighbor. The next day a fourth victim was killed by a stray bullet
as Palczynski carjacked another vehicle, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Baltimore County Police site:
http//www.co.ba.md.us/police
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
