<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Commons Passes Clarity Bill
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Commons voted overwhelmingly Wednesday for
legislation to clarify the rules if Quebec, or any other province,
holds a referendum on secession.
</P>
<P>
   After months of acrimonious debate and political maneuvering
aimed at scuttling the bill, the Bloc Quebecois failed to
neutralize Ottawa's clarity bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bill C-20 passed 208-55. It must still win the approval of
Senate before it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Passage came hours after the House ended 36 hours of recorded
votes on almost 400 Bloc Quebecois amendments, which were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloc says the bill, which among other things allows the
Commons to pass judgment on the clarity of a referendum question,
is undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Acadia Chief Submits Salary Info
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX (AP) -- A Nova Scotia native chief has handed over
sensitive financial documents to the federal government under
threats of losing millions in funding to her band.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Robinson, chief of the Acadia band in Yarmouth, Nova
Scotia, surrendered statements that list her salary, expenses and
honorariums, as well as those of her councilors.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Indian Affairs had asked the band to release
the information by Wednesday after reports indicated the Acadia
band spent $640,248 in 1999 on salaries for the chief, six band
councilors and administrative staff.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa set the March 15 deadline last month and threatened to
withhold millions in funding it gives the band every year.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline also applied to the chief of Cape Breton's Eskasoni
band. Allison Bernard earned about $416,000 in tax-free advances,
salary, bonuses and expenses in the last 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Indian Affairs met with Bernard on Wednesday in
Amherst, Nova Scotia, to discuss the expenditures, as well as the
financial state of the reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The provincial Aboriginal Affairs Department is auditing the
band to determine whether revenues from video lottery terminals and
tobacco sales are spent properly. Bands councils are allowed to
spend the money as they see fit, as long as it relates to economic
development on the reserve.
</P>
