<HEADLINE> Young Mich. Shooter's Fate Halted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT MORRIS TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Parents of a 6-year-old boy
accused of killing a classmate in school have a right to a hearing
before he is expelled, school officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Beecher School Board had planned to vote at its meeting
Wednesday on Superintendent Ira Rutherford's recommendation to
expel the boy. But that vote was pushed back because the parents
have not yet met school officials, Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford has recommended that the boy be expelled for three
months, in accordance with Michigan's school anti-weapons law.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the boy shot and killed Kayla Rolland, 6, on
Feb. 29 after he brought a stolen .32-caliber handgun into class.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, his 5-year-old sister and 8-year-old brother are
getting educational services at home. They are in the temporary
custody of their maternal aunt.
</P>
<P>
   A Michigan law passed in 1995 requires expulsion for 180 days
for any student in grade six or above who carries a weapon to
school. Students in grades five or below are expelled for 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges are expected against the boy, who
authorities have said is too young to understand what happened. A
19-year-old man living at the house where the boy had been staying
has been charged with involuntary manslaughter for allegedly
leaving the gun around.
</P>
</TEXT>
