<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine claims on 700,000 new jobs could bring mixed result  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Jon Corzine, who has applied the ''bold
ideas'' slogan to his campaign for the Democratic nomination for
U.S. Senate, has now made a bold claim: He is responsible for
700,000 New Jersey jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine made the claim at a luncheon for union leaders in East
Brunswick Tuesday, the same day he provided reporters advance
copies of his new, one-minute commercial that repeats the claim:
</P>
<P>
   ''He's helped create and keep 700,000 New Jersey company jobs
alone. Now he's running for the United States Senate with a bold
plan for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the union leaders at one table who heard the
claim, and others who have seen the commercial, drew the same
conclusion: He was taking credit for 700,000 jobs in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting literature for the ad, provided to news
reporters, explains the fine-line difference between ''New Jersey
jobs'' and ''New Jersey company jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim actually concerns the fact the Goldman Sachs
investment banking firm during Corzine's five-year reign as
chairman worked with 40 giant corporations headquartered in New
Jersey that in that time increased their global payrolls by 700,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Lucent Technologies, all of the large ones
were already here. And Lucent was a spinoff from other
telecommunications firms already in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have been happily reporting to legislative committees
that the state's economic expansion, which began in May 1992, added
453,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration at all opportunities discusses the
390,000 new jobs created since she took office.
</P>
<P>
   But these happy statistics pale against the number of new jobs
with which Corzine wishes to be associated for his work leading
some 5,000 investment bankers at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Goldman Sachs who was willing to comment could be
reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With a TV commercial buy of between $500,000 and $1 million
through next Tuesday, millions of New Jersey TV viewers will get to
decide on their own what he may have meant.
</P>
<P>
   What they may think of it could be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   It is already plain what the aides for his opponent, former Gov.
Jim Florio, think about it.
</P>
<P>
   For months they have been anxiously awaiting the launch of the
TV ''air war'' from Corzine, who is investing a piece of his
considerable personal fortune in this, his first-ever run for
elected office.
</P>
<P>
   They have anticipated a ''carpet bombing'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have seen the first launch, and they are pleased,
regarding it as a boomerang bomb that will bounce up and hit the
plane that dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an outrageous lie, a blatant lie,'' said Walter Fields,
a media aide for Florio.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that he is taking credit for jobs that are already
in existence. I believe he takes credit for just about every job
created at Public Service Electric and Gas because people paid
their electric bill,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed the mood at Florio headquarters as joyful.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great example of the public contradiction of Jon
Corzine,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine campaign co-manager Steve Goldstein hammers at the
clarification that Corzine meant jobs across the whole country.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the record, the ad is accurate and it is clear. It means
in New Jersey and across the nation,'' he said, dismissing other
interpretations as ''ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields said this is an effort to split hairs on sentence
structure and it will not protect them from the backlash they
deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Rider University political analyst David Rebovich said the tall
boast illustrates a misjudgment.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has to be more careful in how he words things, in how he
draws connections with average citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Corzine and his advisers have the correct early goal of
connecting with ordinary voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess he wants us to see his economic success (at Goldman
Sachs) has had a positive spillover for working Americans,''
Rebovich said. However, he added, ''The claim is just too
exaggerated, and it may hurt him with ordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Corzine has kept his promises general and his
proposals broad: universal access to education, health insurance
coverage, long-term care for seniors. He has detailed them in
speeches, handouts and on his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   This cannot go on for long, Rebovich said, because special
interest groups like unions want details.
</P>
<P>
   ''Credibility for the newcomer is achieved by his attention to
detail,'' Rebovich said. ''If he is willing to make these sorts of
preposterous-sounding statements, what does it say about him?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-15-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Nations Criticize UN Report  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Several African nations accused of
violating sanctions against Angola's rebels criticized the
explosive U.N. report containing the charges Wednesday as a biased
piece of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Other diplomats called into question the evidence supporting the
accusations, which included charges that the presidents of Burkino
Faso and Togo helped arm the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of the U.N. sanctions committee on Angola,
Ambassador Robert Fowler of Canada, defended the report as solid
and meticulous. He urged the council adopt its recommendations,
including an arms embargo against countries that violated
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council imposed an arms and fuel embargo on UNITA
rebels in 1993, a year before the United Nations brokered a peace
agreement between the rebels and the government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, six months before the peace agreement collapsed, the
council expanded the measures to include a ban on rebel diamond
exports, which are estimated to have supplied the group with up to
$4 billion since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Most ambassadors were cautious over the independent panel's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   France's deputy U.N. ambassador, Yves Doutriaux, said the report
deserved ''detailed scrutiny'' because of the seriousness of the
accusations and the lack of specific dates of alleged violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all due respect, this report seems instead to be built on
illusions rather than on certainties,'' Burkina Faso's U.N.
ambassador, Michel Kafando, told the council.
</P>
<P>
   The report accuses Presidents Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso
and Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo of having helped UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi with arms and fuel shipments in exchange for diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   And it accuses Belgium of having such lax standards at its
Antwerp diamond market that rogue dealers were able to trade UNITA
gems with virtually no obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's U.N. Ambassador, Andre Adam, sharply criticized the
report's failure to include recent improvements enacted by Belgium
to crack down on the illegal trade.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman, Anders Mollander of Sweden, said the
information wasn't turned over in time.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassadors of Burkina Faso and Togo condemned what they
called the ''frivolity'' and ''selective nature'' of the findings
and challenged the panel to produce solid evidence to substantiate
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the person bringing the charge that must provide the
evidence, not the contrary,'' said Togolese Ambassador Roland
Kpotsra.
</P>
<P>
   He and others questioned the report's extensive use of testimony
from rebel defectors, suggesting the panel used a
less-than-meticulous standard when accusing Africans.
</P>
<P>
   But Fowler defended the panel's methods, saying the evidence
collected, particularly against the presidents, was of a higher
legal standard than would have been necessary in a court of law.
UNITA defectors were only used to corroborate information the panel
had independently obtained, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every member of this organization knows that the sanctions are
being violated and it can't really be a surprise to learn how,''
Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report, released this week, details how rebels
bought weapons from Eastern Europe, primarily Bulgaria, and had
them shipped via African countries in exchange for gems.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria's deputy U.N. ambassador, Vladimir Sotirov, denied any
government wrongdoing and decried how Bulgaria was widely cited in
the report based on information it provided about its arms
shipments. Other countries that didn't turn over such information
were let off the hook, Sotirov said.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's U.N. ambassador, Joseph Mutaboba, said the accusations
that Rwanda allowed diamond-for-gun transactions in its territory
''have no foundation,'' and were merely hearsay from biased
sources.
</P>
<P>
   But British Foreign Office minister Peter Hain praised the
report's willingness to expose violators ''who should be ashamed of
the way they are inflicting catastrophe on their fellow Africans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2034 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-China Relations Said 'Mending'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Military relations are ''slowly mending''
between the United States and China, the commander of U.S. Pacific
forces told Congress on Wednesday, but he warned that China's
military balance with Taiwan could be thrown ''out of whack'' by a
Chinese buildup.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Dennis C. Blair said that while Taiwan has a better quality
military and the People's Liberation Army lacks the capability to
''invade and control'' Taiwan, which China claims, China does
''have the ability to inflict significant damage to Taiwan'' with
its much larger force.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying with other regional commanders before the House Armed
Services Committee, Blair said he expects China's military budget
to increase somewhat over the next several years but not the point
where it will significantly alter the military balance across the
Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said U.S.-Chinese military relations were at a new low
last year, with the accidental bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade and other troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a settlement has been negotiated for damage and
lives lost, a U.S. battlegroup was able to visit Hong Kong without
incident, and Blair visited Beijing for talks on regional security.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to congressional questioning, Blair said he warned
Chinese leaders against ''throwing the balance out of whack'' and
told them the United States is committed to maintaining a military
balance in the region.
</P>
<P>
   He said a continued Chinese buildup could result in support for
a theater missile defense system to protect Taiwan, which the
Chinese oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, while not recognizing Taiwan diplomatically,
is required by the Taiwan Security Act to ''react to any resort to
force or other form of coercion'' against Taiwan, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our forces are ready and capable of carrying out their
responsibility toward Taiwan,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Thomas A. Schwartz, commander of U.S. forces in Korea, told
the committee North Korea remains the power ''most likely to
involve the United States in a large-scale war.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that although its economy continues to decline, it is
improving militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ''The army is much more than just a military organization; it is
North Korea's largest employer, purchaser, and consumer, the
central unifying structure in the country, and the source of power
for the regime,'' Schwartz said in his written testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The communist regime has done more to improve its military in
the last year than in the previous five years combined, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Record Set in '82 Stands  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK SCHOFFNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Back in the early 1980s, when her shot
was as automatic as her breathing, Lorri Bauman's jersey was a
signal to her Drake teammates.
</P>
<P>
   If they could see the front of it, they knew exactly what to do:
pass her the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs did that often against Maryland in the 1982 NCAA
tournament and Bauman responded by scoring 50 points. Though
Maryland won that West Regional game 89-78 to advance to the Final
Four, Bauman's total still stands as the most points ever scored in
an NCAA women's tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes never scored that many, nor did Cheryl Miller.
Neither did Lisa Leslie, Chamique Holdsclaw or anyone else who has
come along since.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were all pretty upset about not winning, but I think all of
us realized just what kind of game she had,'' said Connie Newlin,
who was Drake's point guard at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Still to this day, Lorri Bauman from East High School in Des
Moines, Iowa, holds the NCAA scoring record. There have been a lot
of great players who had a lot more opportunities, but she still
holds it. I think that is quite a claim to fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake had reached the regional finals, played at Stanford, by
upsetting top-seeded Long Beach State 91-78. Bauman, a 6-foot-3
sophomore, scored 26 in that game and four teammates were in double
figures, including Newlin with 19.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland started out by having players slough off the person
they were guarding to help on Bauman. But the Terrapins used only
six players that season and the fouls were mounting, so coach Chris
Weller decided at halftime to use only one player on Bauman the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the double- and triple-teaming, Bauman still
scored.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was like 10 of 11 or 10 of 12 in the first half, so I was
kind of on in that game anyway,'' said Bauman, now Lorri Record.
''It was mostly turnaround jumpers and the outside shot. I loved to
shoot outside because nobody would come out and guard me. That was
my all-time favorite shot.''
</P>
<P>
   With only one defender on Bauman, and that player guarding her
from behind, Newlin and the others could see the front of Bauman's
jersey. They did not have to think about what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was automatic then to get it to Bauman because that was a
pretty easy wheel and deal,'' Newlin said. ''That whole game was
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weller said that because of the fouls, she had no choice but to
keep the other players away from Bauman, who averaged 23.5 points
that season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did it knowing she would score a lot of points, but I
thought we could probably pull away,'' Weller said. ''The biggest
thing was we were going to disrupt our offensive continuity if we
kept getting fouls and we were a pretty good offensive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman finished 21-of-35 from the field and made 8-of-11 free
throws while playing all 40 minutes. Carole Baumgarten, Drake's
coach from 1974-86, said she doesn't think Bauman's talents were
recognized at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think people understood how good a shooter Bauman
was,'' Baumgarten said. ''They just saw that as a fluke. Flukes
don't hold the record for that long. The truth is, she wasn't
stoppable. She stopped herself a few nights, but that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes came closer than anyone to Bauman's mark, scoring 47 in
the 1993 national championship game against Ohio State. Only four
others have scored 40 points in an NCAA tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm surprised it's still there,'' said Bauman, who lives in
Gillette, Wyo. ''But records are made to be broken. It's kind of
nice to have them last, but it's nice to see somebody else break
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauman, who played the 6-on-6, half-court game in high school,
left Drake in 1984 with 3,115 points. That's still second on the
NCAA's career list, only seven points behind Mississippi Valley's
Patricia Hoskins.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen a lot of great players on TV and read about them,
but I've never seen anybody that was as prolific a scorer as Lorri
in the women's game,'' Newlin said. ''She wasn't the greatest
mover, but if you could get her the ball, she could score from
anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
