<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana St. Players Defend Knight  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Indiana State guard Nate Green arrived in
the Hoosier State well aware of the huge shadow cast by Indiana
coach Bob Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had heard all the misconceptions and how big of a jerk he
was,'' Green, a senior from Des Moines, Iowa, said.
</P>
<P>
   Green and the Sycamores saw another side of the caustic coach
after Indiana State upset then-No. 14 Indiana 63-60 in Bloomington
in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''That must have been one of the toughest losses for him ever to
get through. He came in the locker room 10 minutes after that game
and said, 'You guys really played well, you really just kicked our
butts out there,''' Green said. ''My opinion of Bobby Knight has
drastically changed from when I first got to Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight has been under fire after former player Neil Reed, in an
interview broadcast Tuesday, accused Knight of physically and
mentally abusing him three years ago. Indiana officials
investigated and denied Reed's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State coach Royce Waltman spent five seasons as an
assistant to Knight, capped by the Hoosiers' NCAA championship in
1987. Waltman calls that ''the biggest thrill I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Green recalled that when Waltman got the Indiana State job three
years ago, the coach said he would just as soon keep his friendship
with Knight than coach the Sycamores.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that speaks volumes about not only their relationship
but what kind of guy coach Knight is,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Knight told the Sycamores stuck in the mind of guard
Michael Menser, who grew up a Hoosiers fan in Batesville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said we could either take the win two ways: it could be our
season or we could go on to bigger and better things,'' he said.
''We did do that, we went on to bigger and better things.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State is in the NCAA tournament for the first time since
1979, when Larry Bird led the Sycamores to a loss in the title game
against Magic Johnson and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA OUT OF WOODS: Arizona found out Wednesday what had
been suspected: center Loren Woods will miss the tournament with a
back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona team physicians reviewed tests done Tuesday on Woods and
decided the compression injury to a disc in his back has not
healed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll continue to miss him as we have the last month, but
these guys have played awfully well without him,'' coach Lute Olson
said. ''It doesn't do you any good to talk about the people that
aren't there. No way can you make a big issue of that because then
you get into excuses and we're not into excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods hurt his back against Washington State on Feb. 12 and
missed the final six games of the regular season. He will make a
full recovery, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-1 center averaged 15.6 points and 7.5 rebounds, and
led the Pac-10 Conference in blocked shots with 3.9 a game. He
blocked a school-record 102 shots, including an NCAA record-tying
14 against Oregon last month.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Thompson, chairman of the NCAA selection committee, said
Sunday that the committee was told that Woods would not play in the
tournament. However, the committee still made Arizona the top seed
in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TRIANGLE OFFENSE: If Los Angeles Lakers assistant Tex Winter
watches Thursday's first-round game between Southeast Missouri and
LSU, he'll see something very familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, in the NCAA tournament for the first time ever, run
the triangle offense that Winter developed years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same offense Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls used
to win six NBA championships, and one the Lakers employ under
Winter and coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of cutting action and a lot of moving,'' said
Southeast Missouri coach Gary Garner, who learned the triangle
under his high school coach and as an assistant to Missouri's Norm
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast Missouri forward Mike Branson said it's a difficult
offense to guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''You get a lot of shots coming off screens if you're able to
read the screens correctly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GLAD TO BE OUT OF THE CAPE: One of the biggest cliches heard
during the NCAA tournament is how glad coaches and teams are to be
here.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Southeast Missouri, the Indians are happier about
being away from Cape Girardeau, a town of 32,000. The school, known
locally as Se Mo, has 8,863 students.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was tremendous fanfare in Cape Girardeau before we left.
Everywhere our players were going, they were patting them on the
back,'' coach Gary Garner said of the locals. ''Since we've gotten
here, they've become much more focused. We're ready to play and put
all that stuff behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Garner has new worries in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't played in as many big arenas as most of the teams
here have,'' he said. ''They've never had the news media attention
that they're getting now and all the distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   UTAH RERUN FOR TEXAS: Texas has been here before and is hoping
for a better outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns lost to Utah 79-73 on Dec. 22 at the Huntsman
Center, where they'll face Indiana State on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Barnes had his team eat at the same restaurant as it
did in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't seem like too new of a place and everyone's real
comfortable here,'' said Chris Mihm, who had 19 points in the loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
