<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Peruvian Underdog Surges  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A one-time shoeshine boy turned economist has
made a surprising surge into second place in the election race
against President Alberto Fujimori, a poll showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, trailing in third place with 14 percent
support just a month ago, had improved to 25 percent in a national
poll conducted by the private firm Datum International.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori still maintained a solid lead with 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But with only 25 days before the April 9 vote, Toledo's sudden
showing evokes memories of Fujimori's meteoric rise a decade ago,
when the then-university rector surged from 3 percent a month
before the election and staged an upset victory over novelist Mario
Vargas Llosa in a second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who finished fourth in Fujimori's 1995 landslide
re-election victory, has emphasized his humble beginnings as a
farmer's son who shined shoes to help make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to hold three graduate degrees, including a doctorate
in economics from Stanford University, and was an adviser to the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Datum poll also showed that 54 percent of Peruvians believe
allegations that Fujimori's re-election campaign used at least 1
million forged signatures to register his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses to the alleged fraud told reporters Wednesday that
they were prepared to offer testimony to a special prosecutor
investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, who has denied any involvement in the scandal, said
Wednesday that he welcomed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's National Elections Board, dominated by Fujimori's
appointees, last week rejected calls to nullify Fujimori's bid for
an unprecedented -- and many say unconstitutional -- third term.
</P>
<P>
   Support for two other candidates -- Lima Mayor Alberto Andrade
former social security director Luis Castaneda -- who had earlier
staged strong challenges to Fujimori slipped in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The Datum poll surveyed 1,505 people between March 10 and March
13 has a margin of error of 2.6 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2057 </TRAILER>
