<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nursing Board Closes Chemo Cases  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN FINUCANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The state nursing board reprimanded a nurse
Wednesday and dismissed complaints against two others, closing the
last cases that arose from chemotherapy overdoses at the Dana
Farber Cancer Institute in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Globe health columnist Betsy Lehman died in September
1994 and another woman's heart was damaged after receiving the
overdoses at the prestigious cancer center. A total of 18 nurses
faced complaints; all cases have now been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The cases against nurses Susan Aikey and Ilene Galinsky were
dismissed Wednesday with an advisory letter. Maura Murray agreed to
a formal reprimand. The other 15 nurses agreed to either a one-year
license probation or a formal reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman and North Andover teacher Maureen Bateman, who later died
of cancer, were given four times the appropriate dosages of radical
chemotherapy treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses delivered dosages prescribed by a doctor, so the
disciplinary actions angered many.
</P>
<P>
   But Marie McCarthy, chairwoman of the state nursing board, said
they were still responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ''A nurse has independent responsibility for knowing that the
dose of a drug being administered to a patient is the correct
dose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Nathan, the Dana-Farber president, and Susan Grant, chief
of nursing, issued a statement saying they believed the actions
against the nurses were ''inappropriate and unwarranted.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor who wrote the erroneous chemotherapy order, James
Foran, did not reapply for his license, heading to London to do
cancer research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
