<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bougainville Peace Talks Resume  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) -- Peace talks between the
Papua New Guinea government and secessionists on Bougainville
island resumed Thursday after stalling earlier on the key issue of
an independence referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Progress towards lasting peace on Bougainville has been slow
since a cease-fire agreement was signed in April 1998, ending a
10-year war by secessionists to gain independence from Papua New
Guinea. It was the longest conflict in the Pacific region since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Bougainville People's Congress demands a referendum so
Bougainvilleans can choose whether to break away. The group's armed
wing, the Bougainville Revolutionary Army, has refused to disarm
until the referendum is agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The Papua New Guinea government has refused to consider a
referendum, and has offered a plan for greater political autonomy
for the province instead.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 40,000 islanders have become displaced and 20,000 people
are thought to have died, mostly through malnutrition and disease,
since fighting began in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The island, the largest of the Solomon Islands but a part of
Papua New Guinea, is 800 miles northeast of the Papua New Guinea
capital, Port Moresby, and is rich in copper resources.
</P>
<P>
   Australia and New Zealand, which have peace monitors deployed on
the island, are growing impatient and are pressuring both sides to
find a lasting political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The latest talks, led by Papua New Guinea's Minister for
Bougainville Affairs Michael Somare, are being held for four days
on the island of Lolata, near Port Moresby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2142 </TRAILER>
