<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dim Prospects for Guatemala Holiday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Guatemala's president wants to create a
holiday recognizing the victims of the country's civil war and to
have schoolchildren study the conflict's bloody history.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal seems to have little chance of being approved
because of strong congressional opposition from President Alfonso
Portillo's own party and little sympathy from human rights groups
who were expected to applaud the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Portillo asked the Senate on Tuesday to declare April 26 ''The
National Day of Dignity for Victims of Violence.'' That is the date
of the 1998 assassination of human rights leader Bishop Juan
Gerardi.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday had been one of the recommendations of the country's
truth commission, which investigated abuses committed during the
country's 36-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued last year, the commission blamed government
security forces for most of the 200,000 killings during the war. It
had recommended that the memorial holiday be held every Feb. 25,
the anniversary of the report's release.
</P>
<P>
   Portillo's proposal would require Guatemala's children to be
taught about the commission's report, as well as a similar report
by the Catholic church's Human Rights Office.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal appears to have little support in the Senate, which
is led by former dictator Efrain Rios Montt. Some of the worst
state-sponsored massacres of the war occurred under Rios Montt's
rule in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rios Montt is the founder and head of Portillo's party,
the Guatemalan Revolutionary Front, the two have continuously
failed to agree on policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rights groups, including the Rigoberta Menchu Foundation --
founded by the 1992 Nobel Laureate -- have dismissed Portillo's
proposal as a political ploy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2210 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Die in Ecuador Malaria Outbreak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- An outbreak of malaria and dengue fever
has killed at least 14 people and has infected more than 14,000
others in Ecuador, health officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Ministry called for a medical state of emergency in
17 of Ecuador's 23 provinces, along the Pacific coast and in
interior jungle regions bordering Peru and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   So far 14,192 cases of malaria have been confirmed, and six
people have died, said Jorge Zambrano, National Health Center
director.
</P>
<P>
   Malaria, which kills about 3 million people worldwide, is spread
by mosquito bite and is marked by fever, chills, joint pain and
vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials also detected 220 cases of dengue, known to
many as break-bone fever because of the excruciating muscle and
joint pains it causes. Zambrano said eight have died.
</P>
<P>
   Dengue, also often carried by mosquitos, attacks the digestive
system and can cause extreme dehydration and hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   The last outbreak in Ecuador occurred in 1997 and 1998 during
the El Nino weather phenomenon, which ravaged this small Andean
nation of 12 million people with heavy flooding -- creating a
perfect environment for mosquitos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2213 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Troop Withdrawal Approved  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A land transfer that had threatened to scuttle
Israeli-Palestinian peace just weeks ago won approval on Wednesday
from both sides, a sign of the new seriousness the leaders attach
to meeting a September peace deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak persuaded key ministers to approve the
transfer of 6.1 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians, even
though areas near Jerusalem are included. The Palestinians accepted
the offer, even though a suburb that abuts the bitterly disputed
city was removed from the map at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, 11th-hour changes and the mere mention of
''Jerusalem'' were a sure recipe for crisis. But Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are feeling the pressure to make
good on September promises: Barak to produce a permanent peace with
the Palestinians, Arafat to declare the state that he says peace
will bring.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's security Cabinet -- nine ministers who vote on peace
issues -- approved the maps 5-3, with one abstention. Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat said Arafat is aware of the revised
withdrawal maps and ''they were granted his approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreement on the interim withdrawal clears the way for the
resumption of permanent status peace talks in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
   Barak won election last year on a campaign of reviving talks
with the Palestinians, and he made good on his promise partly by
luring Arafat with hints of land transfers adjacent to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The talk was that Arafat would get Abu Dis, a bustling suburb
abutting Jerusalem's municipal boundaries. Arafat has built what is
widely believed to be the Palestinian parliament in the suburb, now
jointly controlled by Israel and the Palestinians. Total
Palestinian control would bring Arafat closer to the Jerusalem
capital he has promised for the Palestinian state he says he will
declare in September.
</P>
<P>
   As the February withdrawal date drew near, Barak's aides
strongly hinted that Abu Dis would be handed back, prompting an
uproar among his hawkish Cabinet ministers. Barak withdrew the
offer, instead offering tracts of uninhabited land. A furious
Arafat refused and suspended talks, saying that if he could not
trust Barak on the interim issues, he could not trust him on the
major ones.
</P>
<P>
   The final status talks are addressing the future of Jerusalem,
final borders, Jewish settlements and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent envoys to urge the sides back to the
table. Last week, the leaders shook hands again -- each under new
pressures to show results.
</P>
<P>
   Barak promised clean government, a turnaround in the economy,
and total peace process by the end of 2000. Instead, he has
presided over campaign finance scandals and unabating unemployment,
and peace talks with Syria have deteriorated into saber-rattling in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat promised and delayed statehood once, in May 1999; to do
so again in September could cripple his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it seemed another Abu Dis-style fiasco loomed.
Barak's office leaked maps that included Anata, another suburb that
abuts Jerusalem, but is not as close to the ultrasensitive holy
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from hawkish ministers in his Cabinet, Barak
backed down. Instead of crying 'crisis,' the Palestinians quietly
accepted the maps, which outline a withdrawal from 136 square
miles, and is likely to take place Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just the renewed goodwill that lured the Palestinians
back. The new maps include three crowded villages -- Ubeidiya,
Beituniya and Zatara -- close to, but not abutting Jerusalem. Israel
will also withdraw from near the towns of Jericho, Jenin, Bethlehem
and Hebron, pullbacks that bring Arafat closer to the territorial
continuity he needs to create a state.
</P>
<P>
   In another gesture, Israel said Wednesday it would release about
50 Palestinian prisoners on the occasion of a Muslim holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials also announced the release of 105
prisoners to mark the holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2217 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xavier 67, Marquette 63  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Maurice McAfee hit a 3-pointer and a free
throw in the final two minutes Wednesday night as Xavier switched
roles on Marquette, overcoming the big second-half deficit for a
67-63 victory in the first round of the National Invitation
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier (21-11) trailed by 10 with 15:25 left before rallying
behind the front-line play of Kevin Frey and David West and
McAfee's clutch 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   McAffee's basket beat the shot clock and put Xavier ahead 63-60
with 1:45 left, the Musketeers' first lead since the opening three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Marquette (15-14) had a shot to tie it at 66 with 5 seconds
left, but Brian Wardle's 3-point attempt went off the side of the
rim. Aaron Turner got the rebound, was fouled and hit one free
throw to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   Frey led Xavier with 21 points, and West added 16 points and 11
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cordell Henry matched his career high with 17 points in the
first half as Marquette got up by double-digits, but drew heavy
coverage in the second half and finished with 29. John Cliff added
19 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bookend game to their meeting Jan. 2 at Milwaukee,
where Xavier blew an 18-point lead in the second half for one of
its most crushing losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Musketeers had won five in a row, including their upset of
No. 1 Cincinnati, and were getting national attention when the
Golden Eagles pulled off their big comeback.
</P>
<P>
   From that game on, Xavier made a habit of blowing leads and
losing close games.
</P>
<P>
   Henry hit the big shots in that first game, including a
3-pointer that tied it and a basket that put Marquette ahead to
stay. He pushed Xavier to the verge of its first first-round loss
in seven NIT appearances Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who averages 8.5 points, hit 8-of-10 from the field in
the first half as he tied a career high reached only two other
times.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Price, Xavier's second-leading rebounder and third-leading
scorer at 13.1 points, didn't play because he missed two practices
over the weekend. Price said he needed time to clear his head after
his poor play in the Atlantic 10 tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
