<HEADLINE> Mississippi 62, UNC Charlotte 45  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH D. RUSSO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- Marcus Hicks scored 14 points as
Mississippi held North Carolina Charlotte without a field goal for
seven minutes in the first half of its 62-45 victory in the first
round of the National Invitation Tournament on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lataryl Williams had 13 points for Ole Miss, Rahim Lockhart 12,
Jason Harrison 10 and Jason Flanigan 13. They were the only five
players to score for Mississippi (18-12).
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels, making their first NIT appearance since 1989, may
have played their best game of the season. Mississippi ran its
offense to near perfection, shot well from the perimeter, dominated
on the glass and played sound defense.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Charlotte (17-16), with its poor shooting and the
fact it was without its best inside player, Tremaine Gardiner, was
never in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers made the first basket, then the shots wouldn't fall
from anywhere. North Carolina Charlotte went over seven minutes
without scoring and missed 19 straight field-goal attempts during a
12-minute span.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss, however, seemed to not be able to miss a shot, jumping
out to a 22-4 lead. The Rebels led 34-17 at half after shooting 58
percent (14-of-24), compared to the 49ers' 19 percent (6-of-31).
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi's lead grew to as much as 22 in the second half and
never went below 13. The Rebels shot 49 percent from the floor and
had 16 assists. The 49ers made just 27 percent of their shots.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Tolliver had nine points to lead the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss extended its home non-conference winning streak to 34
games, third-longest in the country behind Maryland (70) and Penn
State (46).
</P>
