By PAUL NEWBERRY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Jalen Rose tied his career high with 32 points,
Reggie Miller had 28 and the Indiana Pacers took control with a
25-3 spurt, beating the Atlanta Hawks 113-107 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers increased their lead in the Eastern Conference to
three games over idle Miami and pushed six games ahead of Toronto,
also off, in the Central.
</P>
<P>
   The hapless Hawks, with the third-worst record in the East, led
55-45 after Isaiah Rider dunked off a fast break with 3:13 left in
the second quarter. But the Pacers scored the final 10 points of
the half, including six by Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana kept up the pace to start the third period, taking
command with a 15-3 run. Rik Smits scored six points, Miller added
four and Mark Jackson hit a 3-pointer for a 70-58 lead with 7:13
remaining for a 70-58 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks committed six turnovers during that eight-minute
stretch. To make matters worse, they hit only 3 of 17 shots in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta closed to 100-96 on Alan Henderson's dunk with 3:39
remaining, then forced a miss by Rose on Indiana's next trip down
the court. Dikembe Mutombo fought with Smits for the rebound, came
up with the loose ball as he stumbled toward the end line and tried
to call timeout.
</P>
<P>
   But official Don Vaden ruled Mutombo already had gone out of
bounds, giving the ball back to the Pacers. Miller took advantage
by hitting a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta made one more run, scoring four straight points to make
it 103-100 before Rose hit a couple of free throws, Jim Jackson
missed for the Hawks and Indiana's Austin Croshere dunked off a
pass from Mark Jackson to make it 107-100 with a minute to go.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Both teams played the previous night in Texas. The Hawks
lost in San Antonio, while the Pacers were beaten by the Mavericks
in Dallas. ... Indiana's Dale Davis didn't make the two-game road
trip because of leg cramps. ... Rider, who has played sparingly
since he showed up late for a March 9 game against San Antonio,
scored three points in seven minutes. Early in the fourth quarter,
several fans behind the bench began chanting, ''We want Rider.'' He
acknowledged their pleas by clapping his hands above his head. ...
Mutombo, Atlanta's Bimbo Coles and Indiana's Travis Best all picked
up technicals.
</P>
