<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cop Brutality Protested in Montreal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Hundreds of people protesting against alleged
police brutality broke windows at a police station and damaged
shops and cars in downtown Montreal Wednesday. Riot squads broke up
the demonstration and arrested about 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest erupted two days shy of the 45th anniversary of
another Montreal riot, when hockey fans enraged by the suspension
of Montreal Canadians star Maurice Richard went on a rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Targets of the estimated 400 protesters, some wearing masks, on
Wednesday night included McDonald's restaurants, a bank, a police
station, and vehicles parked along downtown streets. No injuries
were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Vadier, 62, said he was drinking coffee at a McDonald's
restaurant when the windows were smashed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounded like a bomb,'' he said. ''The windows shattered but
there was no glass flying. Everyone was shocked. We all left the
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest came a few hours after prosecutors said a hearing
would be required to determine if charges would be filed against
two Montreal policemen who allegedly took part in the beating of a
homeless man. The victim died weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Breton, a chief prosecutor, said serious charges against
the policemen could result from the special hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Yves Manseau, a spokesman for the protesters, said the
special hearing was extremely unusual and showed that policemen in
Montreal were getting preferential treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
