<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, March 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NATO Takes Control of Serb Bridge
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Seizing control of a key bridge in a
first step to reunite this ethnically divided city, NATO peacekeepers clashed
Wednesday with angry Serbs in a confrontation during which two people lost limbs
to stun grenades. Serbs responded with a call for a campaign of civil
disobedience against the embattled U.N. and NATO administration, which vowed not
to back down from their pledge to reassert international control. Wednesday's
operation quickly turned into a confrontation as crowds of angry Serbs surged
into a ''security zone'' at the bridgehead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. House Advances Gay Rights Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Citing decades of ''mistreatment, discrimination and
prejudice,'' the state Legislature's only gay member pleaded today for support
of a bill allowing gays the equivalent of marriage. Spectators, some wearing
pink badges for the bill and others wearing white badges against it, packed the
state House as debate began. Both supporters and opponents say the bill would
provide more rights and benefits for same-sex couples than any other state in
the country. Backers said they believed they had enough votes to approve the
bill. The Democratic-controlled House voted 79-68 today to advance the bill for
a final vote expected tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Releases Overnight Guests List
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Trying to allay a growing controversy, George W. Bush's
campaign today released a list of all of his overnight guests at the Governor's
Mansion in Texas. The watchdog Center for Public Integrity released a separate
study saying that 60 of the 131 guests had contributed or raised more than $2.2
million for Bush's presidential campaign. Bush has raised a record $73 million
for the White House bid. Bush campaign officials said they had opened the
mansion to relatives, longtime friends and Republican officials, not
fund-raisers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russian Troops Gain in Chechnya
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALKHAZUROVO, Russia (AP) -- After 10 days of intense fighting, Russia claimed
to control the Chechen village of Komsomolskoye on Wednesday and said it had a
firm hold on the rebel republic's territory. But warplanes and artillery
continued to batter a half-dozen other communities in Chechnya and military
officials admitted Russian forces still didn't have command of many villages.
Even in Komsomolskoye -- seized by rebels earlier this month in an assault that
undermined Russian claims that the rebels faced imminent defeat -- several small
militant groups remained, said Konstantin Makeyev, a spokesman at the Russian
regional military command in Mozdok.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Grand Jury Indicts Man Using DNA
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In what authorities believe is a forensic first, a grand
jury has indicted an unidentified man for three rapes based on his DNA genetic
profile. The rapist is still at large. District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said
the indictment filed today names ''John Doe,'' a man believed to be the East
Side rapist of Manhattan, and it was filed four days before the five-year
statute of limitations lapsed for the first rape. Morgenthau said the rapist has
attacked at least 16 women, the last on Sept. 15, 1998.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Web Auto Shopping Lacking
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Car buyers looking to use the Internet for their next
purchase should probably look elsewhere, according to Consumer Reports' annual
auto issue. The magazine said its review of five major Internet car buying sites
found a lot of useful information but not good service. The auto issue due on
newsstands March 21 also made few changes in its widely followed annual ranking
of best buys, with one notable exception -- the Toyota Tundra replaced the Ford
F-150 as best full-size pickup.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately Thursday. The Nikkei Stock
Average, which was down some 160 points early in the session, rose 62.79 to
19,141.39 at the end of the morning session. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow
soared 320.17 points to 10,131.41. The technology-rich Nasdaq, however, dropped
124.01 points to end at 4,582.62, bringing its loss for the past three days to
465 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Defeat Hawks 113-107
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Jalen Rose tied his career high with 32 points, Reggie Miller
had 28 and the Indiana Pacers took control with a 25-3 spurt, beating the
Atlanta Hawks 113-107 tonight. The Pacers increased their lead in the Eastern
Conference to three games over idle Miami and pushed six games ahead of Toronto,
also off, in the Central. The hapless Hawks, with the third-worst record in the
East, led 55-45 after Isaiah Rider dunked off a fast break with 3:13 left in the
second quarter. But the Pacers scored the final 10 points of the half, including
six by Miller.
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY 
</P>
