<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
Robert L. Barber:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) -- Robert L. Barber, a longtime Santa
Barbara News-Press editor and drama critic, died Sunday. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Barber began his career with the News-Press in 1959 and retired
in 1988. By his own estimate, he reviewed more than 1,000 plays and
musicals performed by area schools, community theaters and
professional touring companies.
</P>
<P>
   Young actors he reviewed included Eric Stoltz and Anthony
Edwards, who went on to major acting careers.
</P>
<P>
   Following his retirement, he worked as a free-lance writer and
regularly contributed features to the News-Press religion page.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of nearly 50 years, Gloris Davis
Barber; four children, Leah Juniper of Ventura, Robert Edward
Barber of San Diego, Geoffrey Michael Barber of Portland, Ore., and
Jana Marie Barber of San Francisco.
Richard Charnock:
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Richard Charnock, a veteran reporter and editor
for United Press International who covered such events as Ernest
Hemingway's death, died Tuesday after a brief illness. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   During his 32-year career with UPI, Charnock headed bureaus in
Montana and Idaho. He became the UPI bureau chief in Phoenix in
1979 but left the company when it closed its operation there in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   During his UPI career, he covered earthquakes in Yellowstone
National Park, the 1964 Republican convention and Hemingway, who
shot himself to death in Idaho in July 1961.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving UPI, he worked as a copy editor and assistant
state editor for The Arizona Republic, retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   While still UPI bureau chief in Boise, Idaho, he wrote a
political column for The Idaho Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Charnock is survived by his wife, Bette; daughters, Gayle
Sherill, Joyce Collins, Ann Buresh, Susan Stefun; and son, David
Charnock. He was preceded in death by another son, Allan.
Tommy Collins:
</P>
<P>
   ASHLAND CITY, Tenn. (AP) -- Tommy Collins, who wrote country
music hits for Merle Haggard, George Strait and other singers, died
Tuesday of complications from emphysema. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   His hits included ''If You Ain't Lovin' (You Ain't Livin')'' by
both Strait and Ferlin Huskey, and Haggard's ''Carolyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Haggard wrote his 1981 hit ''Leonard'' in tribute to Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Born Leonard Sipes in Oklahoma City, he was renamed Tommy
Collins by Huskey after the Tom Collins cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   Collins helped craft the Bakersfield Sound of country music in
California during the 1950s before moving to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   He was inducted into the Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame in
September.
Andrew Ghareeb:
</P>
<P>
   CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) -- Andrew E. Ghareeb, who translated the
works of the Lebanese poet Kahlil Gibran into English, died Sunday.
He was 101.
</P>
<P>
   Ghareeb came to Springfield in 1913 from his native Lebanon and
discovered Gibran's writing in a Lebanese magazine in 1918. His
first translation of the poem ''My Soul Counseled Me'' was
published in the Springfield Republican newspaper in 1926.
</P>
<P>
   Ghareeb sent the translation to Gibran, who was living in New
York City. It was the start of a friendship that lasted until
Gibran's death, and the poet gave Ghareeb permission to translate
all of his Arabic writings into English.
</P>
<P>
   Ghareeb's translation of ''The Prophet'' sold more than 8
million copies. The most famous of his translations, ''Prose
Poems'' was published in 1934 and is in its 31st printing.
Joseph Goldstein:
</P>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Joseph Goldstein, a longtime Yale Law
School professor who introduced the best interests of children into
the canon of family law, died Sunday from a heart attack. He was
76.
</P>
<P>
   His work introduced the idea that courts should handle child
custody disputes according to the child's best interest and should
consider the child's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who also was a psychoanalyst, helped write three
books on the subject: ''Beyond the Best Interests of the Child'' in
1973, ''Before the Best Interests of the Child'' in 1979, and ''In
the Best Interests of the Child'' in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Co-authors included his wife, Sonja, Anna Freud, the
psychoanalyst and daughter of Dr. Sigmund Freud, and Albert Solnit,
the director of the Yale Child Study Center.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein joined Yale's law faculty in 1956 and retired in 1993.
He helped write books on other topics, including volumes on
constitutional and criminal law and ''The My Lai Massacre and Its
Cover Up: Beyond the Reach of Law?'' in 1976.
Bobb McKittrick:
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Bobb McKittrick, a gritty offensive line
coach for the San Francisco 49ers who worked with five Super
Bowl-winning teams, died Wednesday of cancer. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Baker, Ore., McKittrick started his coaching career
in 1961 as an assistant with his alma mater, Oregon State. He also
coached for UCLA and the Los Angeles Rams before returning to
Oregon State for graduate work in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the NFL as an assistant with the San Diego
Chargers the next year and joined Bill Walsh's staff with the 49ers
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick was scheduled for a liver transplant last April, but
it was canceled when doctors determined the cancer had spread. He
responded by returning to work, prowling the sidelines at training
camp in a golf cart.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers honored McKittrick with a special halftime tribute
during a home game against the Tennessee Titans last season.
Manning J. Post:
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Manning J. ''Manny'' Post, a key
fund-raiser for the California Democratic Party and adviser to
generations of candidates, died Monday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Post underwent surgery last year for treatment of lung cancer.
He also suffered from other ailments, including skin cancer and
emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   Post served as treasurer for the California presidential
campaigns of John F. Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson and headed the
inaugural campaign committee for Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as longtime controller for the Democratic State
Central Committee and treasurer for legendary state Assembly
Speaker Jesse Unruh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
