<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lindros May Play Thursday Night  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros, who missed the Philadelphia
Flyers' last game because of a migraine headache, might return to
the lineup as early as Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The captain, who sat out the Flyers' game Monday night at
Phoenix, underwent further tests on Wednesday and did not practice.
However, he could see action when the Flyers play at home Thursday
night against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrery Hartzell, the Flyers' team physician, said the
concussion-like symptoms Lindros had been experiencing were not a
concussion but a variation of a migraine.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has had three concussions in his career, the last one on
Jan. 14 that caused him to miss four games. Late in the 1997-98
season, Lindros received a concussion that kept him out of the last
18 games of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was complaining about headaches all week and not being able
to see things right,'' Flyers forward John LeClair said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartzell said Lindros was playing through the pain for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not until the game in Colorado (Sunday night) did it happen to
affect his performance,'' Hartzell said. ''He began to have some
difficulty concentrating, and because of that latter aspect, we
thought it was best that he not play in Phoenix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
