<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BYU 81, Bowling Green 54  </HEADLINE>
BYU 81, Bowling Green 54   
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVO, Utah (AP) -- Terrell Lyday scored 15 points, hitting
5-of-6 from 3-point range, and Michael Vranes added 14 points as
BYU beat Bowling Green 81-54 in the first round of the NIT on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars (21-10) won for the fifth time in their last six
games and will play next week against the winner of Thursday
night's game between Colorado and Southern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling Green (22-8) came in as the nation's No. 3 shooting team
(49.8 percent), but BYU held the Falcons to 34 percent (9-of-26) in
building a 38-28 halftime lead. Bowling Green finished 32 percent
(17-of-52) from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Esterkamp led the Falcons with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Dakich wanted to see his team run after the Falcons
were lulled into a halfcourt game by Miami, Ohio, during a
first-round upset at the Mid-American Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But BYU showed it can run, too. The Cougars averaged 70.4 points
this season and, after the teams banged inside through the first
half, BYU took control with a 10-3 run over the last 3:48 before
the break.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, regular season champions in the MAC, grew
increasingly frustrated from the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   Lyday heated up early in the second half, connecting three times
from 3-point range in the first 5:30 as BYU stretched the lead to
51-39. It was 55-40 with 11:33 left after an inside basket by Eric
Nielsen, who scored 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave up too many easy baskets and couldn't get much
going offensively, either.
</P>
<P>
   MAC player of the year Anthony Stacey, Bowling Green's leading
scorer at 17 points a game, was held to three first-half points and
finished with 11. The Falcons also had 17 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed nothing would go right for the Falcons. Vranes scored
on a putback with 6:16 to play, giving the Cougars a 62-46 lead,
after the ball went off the hands of three Bowling Green players.
</P>
<P>
   Mekeli Wesley added 13 points for BYU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000315.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame 75, Michigan 65  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Troy Murphy scored 32 points -- 12 of
them at the free-throw line -- as Notre Dame beat Michigan 75-65
Wednesday night in the first round of the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame coach Matt Doherty had worried earlier this week that
the Irish (19-14) would be sluggish after they were left out of the
NCAA tournament and were forced to accept an invitation to the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   But Notre Dame survived a physical final 49.6 seconds without
Murphy after his fifth foul and Michigan (15-14) down 69-64. Notre
Dame made it through a flurry of fouls by hitting 6-of-8 from the
foul line to secure the win.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame went up 60-51 with 9:37 left in the game after Jere
Macura hit a pair of free throws. But Michigan answered with a 9-2
run -- with Notre Dame's only points coming from Murphy, who pushed
the lead back to 66-60 on four straight free throws.
</P>
<P>
   A David Graves 3-pointer upped the lead to 69-61 before Michigan
pulled within 69-64 when Kevin Gaines hit one of two free throws
after Murphy's fifth foul. But the Wolverines couldn't get any
closer as the Irish hit their foul shots down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish finished 24-of-30 from the foul line, while the
Wolverines were 10-of-14.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, which lost 11 of its final 14 games, was led by LaVell
Blanchard with 14 points. Peter Vignier and Josh Asselin scored 12
points apiece for the Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 33 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish will host Xavier (21-11) on Monday in the second
round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
