<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen To Press Japan on U.S. Troops  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said Wednesday he
will press Japanese defense officials not to cut the $5 billion a
year the government pays to keep 47,000 American troops in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to us,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also demanded that the Japanese government take action to
stop what the U.S. Navy contends are dangerous levels of air
pollution spewing from a private incinerator located just outside
the gates of Atsugi Naval Air Facility, west of Tokyo, where about
3,000 U.S. sailors and their families live.
</P>
<P>
   ''It either has to be cleaned up or shut down,'' Cohen told
reporters after visiting Atsugi and looking at the puffs of smoke
rising from the incinerator Thursday. ''This is a serious matter
for the United States,'' he said because it poses a continuing risk
to the health of American servicemen and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to have action taken,'' he said, adding that he would
discuss the matter with senior Japanese government officials later
Thursday and hope to announce that a permanent solution has been
found.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters on Cohen's flight here from Ho Chi Minh
City, Vietnam, a senior aide told reporters on Wednesday that
Washington and Tokyo were on the verge of an agreement to address
the pollution problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Japan's Environment Agency said the levels of
carcinogenic dioxin were dangerously high near the Atsugi naval
facility, which is home to the air wing assigned to the USS Kitty
Hawk carrier battle group.
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted last summer by the Japanese government and the
U.S. Navy found dioxin in concentrations 10 times the level deemed
acceptable by the Japanese government, Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr.
James Graybeal said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said before Cohen's arrival in Japan that they
expected a ''comprehensive agreement'' to be announced Thursday
when Cohen meets with Tsutomu Kawara, chief of the Japanese Defense
Agency. The official declined to provide any details but said the
solution would be ''very expensive'' for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo newspaper The Daily Yomiuri reported in Thursday's
editions that Kawara said on a visit to the incinerator on
Wednesday, before Cohen arrived in Japan, that something must be
done to address the Americans' concerns, including the possibility
of the government taking over the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there may be a need to employ special measures to
solve the problem,'' the newspaper quoted Kawara as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said that the Pentagon is hopeful of reaching a new
five-year ''host nation support'' agreement by this summer, when
President Clinton will travel to Japan for an international summit
conference in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current deal, which expires in 2001, Japan pays about
$100,000 a year for every U.S. soldier, sailor, airman and Marine
based in Japan. That amounts to about $5 billion a year -- by far
the most generous financial support by any ally with American
forces on its soil.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also expects to discuss with Japanese officials his
three-day visit to Vietnam, which was the first by an American
defense secretary since before the Vietnam War ended 25 years ago.
Cohen flew here Wednesday from Ho Chi Minh City, known as Saigon
before the communist defeat of U.S.-backed South Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-15-00 2333 </TRAILER>
