<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symbolic Gun Control Victory  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On a day that both a Democratic president and
a Republican governor pushed for broad new gun controls,
long-stalled legislation won a symbolic victory in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 218-205 to urge House-Senate negotiators to meet
within two weeks. If they did, it would be their first session
since August.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Senate voted to institute 72-hour background
checks on gun show sales, but the House rejected that provision and
gun control has been stalled since then. The negotiators are to
resolve differences between the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the vote, 12 female members of Congress made an
emotional appeal at the White House for their colleagues to ignore
the National Rifle Association's opposition to the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The moms of this country have had it,'' said Rep. Carolyn
McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband was shot to death -- and her son
badly wounded -- on a commuter train six years ago. ''I'm tired of
the lies. ... We represent the people of the United States. The NRA
does not.''
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the
House-Senate committee, to call a meeting. In a statement
Wednesday, Hatch did not address the two-week deadline but said he
was disappointed that President Clinton has ignored his suggestions
for bolstering enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''To my knowledge, he has acted on none of these overdue
reforms,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, where Clinton spoke at a $550,000 fund-raising
dinner for the Democratic National Committee, White House aides
released a letter in which Clinton endorsed a bill in the Maryland
Legislature, which he said would ''make guns safer, and keep them
out of the hands of children and felons.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to events on Capitol Hill, he said: ''At last, earlier
today, the Republican leadership heeded my call to convene a
conference to come to agreement on common-sense gun legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends it increased federal gun
prosecutions by 25.3 percent -- up to 5,500 cases -- from 1998 to
1999, and that combined federal and state prosecutions of gun
charges led to 22 percent more criminals being imprisoned in 1996
than in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Still, approval of the House resolution constituted a rare
victory for gun control. The White House cheered the vote, saying
it revealed a crack in the NRA's armor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The NRA's influence on Republicans may be beginning to
break,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. In all, 46
Republicans supported the measure; 32 Democrats opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, New York Gov. George Pataki, ignoring the sentiment
of many fellow Republicans, called for a series of stiff gun
control measures in his state. They include making trigger locks
mandatory; taking ballistic ''fingerprints'' of guns, requiring
dealers and manufacturers to send to a state lab a test bullet and
shell casing from every handgun they sell in the state; raising the
age for handgun ownership from 18 to 21 and requiring instant
background checks of gun buyers at flea markets and gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, 100 religious leaders sent a letter to Congress
supporting Clinton's efforts to reduce gun violence, and the
National Opinion Research Center issued a study that said the 25
percent of Americans who own handguns are far outnumbered by the 37
percent who favor a handgun ban for all except ''police and other
authorized persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the House vote, Clinton was joined by 33 House
members -- including several Republicans -- in an East Room ceremony
where he released the first annual FBI report on the effectiveness
of instant background checks for gun purchases that began Nov. 30,
1998. The report found that the instant background checks had
stopped 179,000 prohibited gun sales through Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen female House members identified themselves as mothers
and grandmothers summoned women from around the nation to a
''Million Moms March'' against gun violence in Washington on
Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton repeated his complaint that the NRA has
stalled his gun bill with pressure tactics and an argument against
lengthier background checks that he said seemed as senseless as
opposing metal detectors and seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking a little time and a little inconvenience to save a lot
of lives is a good deal for America,'' Clinton said. ''Why should
this be the only area of our national life where we say no
prevention, only punishment?''
</P>
<P>
   In response, NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre said
the White House was trying to ''demonize'' the NRA to distract
attention from ''the complete collapse of enforcement'' of existing
gun laws by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''They try to focus on anything except what they are vulnerable
on,'' LaPierre said. ''What does a criminal have to fear from these
guys? Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends the NRA attack on gun
prosecutions misses the point. Federal policy is to keep the
biggest gun cases and refer lesser ones to state authorities, and
even so, the federal prosecutions rose 25.3 percent in one year, it
says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the administration says the Brady Act was designed
primarily to keep guns out of the hands of criminals, and more than
500,000 people have been denied guns under Brady since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Congress never provided the agents, prosecutors, judges or
prisons to prosecute everyone who tried to get a gun and was barred
from doing so because of Brady checks, and Attorney General Janet
Reno has said that prosecuting all of them would have swamped the
federal criminal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued Wednesday with House Democrats that a
compromise on gun safety issues was best worked out without the
political rhetoric of an open meeting. ''It is not a simple issue
that you can politicize,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans stood with Clinton, including the former
impeachment manager, Rep. Jim Rogan of California, who faces a
tough re-election fight.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
