<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco To Sell Alaska Assets  </HEADLINE>
By T.A. BADGER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC has revived its purchase
of Atlantic Richfield Co. by agreeing to sell off all of Arco's
assets in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum Co. has agreed to buy the Alaska properties,
which include nearly 2 billion barrels of proven oil reserves, for
$7 billion, the companies said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission rejected the $27 billion BP
Amoco-Arco deal last month, saying it would give the combined
company too much clout in Alaska's oil fields and West Coast
gasoline markets heavily dependent on Alaska oil.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday the agency said it had shelved a lawsuit
challenging the BP Amoco-Arco deal, which would create the world's
second largest nongovernment oil company. The lawsuit had been
scheduled for trial Monday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a long and hectic road,'' Rodney Chase, BP Amoco's
deputy chief executive, said while announcing the Phillips deal in
Anchorage. ''Today it seems to me that the destination is clear and
in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in the talks said Phillips' purchase would
likely resolve the most substantial FTC concerns about competition
in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ''In light of the substantial and constructive proposals made by
the defendants, all parties have agreed to seek adjournment of the
federal court proceedings,'' Richard Parker, director of the
agency's Bureau of Competition, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   FTC lawyers must still determine whether Phillips can provide
the competition the agency considers necessary. BP Amoco produces
more than 400,000 barrels of oil in Alaska each day, roughly 40
percent of the state's output.
</P>
<P>
   Arco now produces about 325,000 barrels of oil a day in Alaska,
most of it from the huge Prudhoe Bay field.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, based in Bartlesville, Okla., would get that
production, along with the lion's share of a 425-million-barrel
field due to start flowing later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska assets also include a 22 percent interest in the
trans-Alaska oil pipeline, nine oil tankers, a huge reservoir of
natural gas and more than 1 million acres of land for exploration.
</P>
<P>
   ''In looking at Arco's Alaska business, we see unlimited
potential,'' said Jim Mulva, Phillips chief executive. ''We intend
to be a very strong, independent competitor in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is to combine Phillips' and Arco's plans to grow
production by aggressively pursuing exploration and development
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulva said Phillips would hire all of Arco's Alaska work force.
The original BP Amoco-Arco deal called for roughly 400 layoffs as
the combined company consolidated its Alaska operations.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, the nation's sixth-largest oil company, has been long
been active in Alaska. The company owns 70 percent of a liquefied
natural gas plant south of Anchorage that exports to Asia. The
company also owns a small piece of the Prudhoe Bay field.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips had 15,900 employees and $15 billion of assets at the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.bpamoco.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.arco.com
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' chart and maps of the areas involved in the sale:
http://www.phillips66.com/newsroom/images&AMP;charts/alaska/sld001.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
